[Black "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. Nxc6 { This was recommended by Negi in his legendary 1.e4 series of books. It leads to a very interesting and complex pawn structure that every Taimanov player should be aware of. In general, after taking on c6 with the pawn, we aim for a setup with ...O-O, followed by ...e5 and ...Be6, eventually looking to launch a queenside attack. The pawn on a2 is always a weakness for White, and a3 is not ideal, as it provides us with a breaking point through b4. Moves like Kb1 can also be met with ...b4, which serves as our main source of counterplay. White will attempt to develop an initiative on the kingside, and we'll need to defend against that rather than going all-in on the queenside, as our attack may not be as strong. Overall, it's a very dynamic and fighting position that can lead to exciting chess! } 10... dxc6 { The correct recapture. Black struggles to develop any counterplay after } ( 10... Qxc6 $2 11. g4 ) 11. g4 O-O 12. Qf2 { The main move, stepping off the d-file. Now ...Rd8 no longer gains a tempo. } 12... e5 13. h4 Rd8 $1 { This is the best move, and it was already recommended as such in Negi's original work. Credit to him for his amazing analysis. While } ( 13... Be6 { looks more natural, } 14. Bh3 { threatens g5, leading to positions that are slightly unpleasant for Black. With 13...Rd8, we introduce some new defensive ideas against this Bh3 plan as we will see. You can scroll through the remaining moves to see the recommended continuation from the theoretical chapter. } ) 14. Rxd8+ Qxd8 15. Bh3 h5 $5 { This is an interesting alternative to the well-known main lines, and it has the advantage of not being covered in Negi's books, nor mentioned in other great sources on the Taimanov, like Semkov's recent book or Harikrishna's. The idea is similar to what we saw in a sideline: we want to provoke White into playing g5, allowing our knight to establish a perfect outpost on g6. If White doesn't advance, they still have to deal with the threat on g4. } 16. Qg2 a5 $1 { It is the right moment to launch our counterplay on the queenside. } 17. Rd1 Qe8 $5 { The queen can be more active in other places, but I want to show this idea. From e8, the queen diminishes the strength of g5-g6 ideas. } 18. Ne2 hxg4 { A good moment to take on g4: now that the knight has vacated c3, the pawn on e4 is left vulnerable in some variations. } 19. fxg4 Be6 20. Ng3 $2 $146 Rd8 21. Rg1 Qf8 { A curious way of getting counterplay! } 22. g5 Bxh3 23. Qxh3 Ba3 { Lovely idea! The game ends in a logical draw after } 24. gxf6 Qb4 25. bxa3 Qxa3+ 26. Kb1 Qb4+ $10 * 

