1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Bxd4 { The most natural and popular recapture. } 11... Bb7 12. Kb1 O-O 13. g5 { This has been the most played move, but I do not think it is specially dangerous. } 13... Nh5 14. Ne2 f5 $1 { Very nice theme, and typical of these lines: we activate our pieces and open the f-file, allowing us to start targeting the weak f3-pawn. } 15. gxf6 Bxf6 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 $133 { [%cal Gf8f7,Ga8f8]Both sides have their strengths: White has a stronger attack, but we have the better pawn structure. Next, we will double rooks on the f-file and look to improve our knight's position. } * 

