1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Nxc6 { This is one of the critical moves. White takes on c6 before we play ...Bb7, and typically aims to capitalize on their development advantage. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { White defends the c2-pawn. We were threatening ...b4, so it makes sense. } 9... Ba3 $5 { It is usually not a good idea to force an early crisis when we are down on development, but I think it is concretely justified in this position. White needs to respond to the ...Bxb2 threat, and we have several moves to consider. } 10. Nd1 { The most critical response, asking us what our idea was when initiating this maneuver. } 10... Bb4+ $1 { We first force c3, so that White's knight cannot be easily improved from d1 to c3 again. } 11. c3 Be7 12. Qg3 $1 { White understands that g7 is a weak square and plays this unpleasant move. Something like } 12... Nf6 { This may seem like a blunder, but it's a key novelty that revitalizes this ...b5 line! } ( 12... g6 $2 13. Bd4 f6 14. O-O { is of course very passive and sad for Black, but we have some tactical resources! } ) 13. e5 { The critical move, asking where does our knight go to. } 13... Nh5 $1 14. Qg4 { At first glance, Black looks completely lost: White is threatening Qxh5 and Be4, winnning material. We cannot save both, but we have a fantastic and unexpected tactical resource (and also quite a good trap!). } 14... Bb7 $3 15. Qxh5 $2 Qxg2 16. Rf1 Bf3 $19 { The whole point of our play! White's queen has been trapped in broad daylight! } * 

