1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. Rg1 $5 { A tricky attempt. 8.h4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) does not really help White push g5, so it makes sense to find alternatives. In general, facing this move implies a great probability that our opponent is well-prepared. } 8... Nf6 { Again, the main idea of 7...h6 is to develop the knight to f6 without too much problem. } ( 8... b5 { is also playable, but I trust this variation more. } ) 9. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 ( 9... Qxc6 $2 { was our move against 8.h4, but here the g4-pawn is defended, and White can immediately centralize their queen with } 10. Qd4 $16 { avoiding any ...Bb4 or ...Ba3 counterplay, nonsense, shenanigans, and tomfoolery. } ) * 

