1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. Rg1 $5 { A tricky attempt. 8.h4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) does not really help White push g5, so it makes sense to find alternatives. In general, facing this move implies a great probability that our opponent is well-prepared. } 8... Nf6 { Again, the main idea of 7...h6 is to be able to develop the knight to f6 without too much problem. } ( 8... b5 { is also playable, but I trust this variation more. } ) 9. Nxc6 $1 { This is the critical move. ...Ne5 is a very important part of our counterplay, so this move makes a lot of sense. } 9... bxc6 ( 9... Qxc6 $2 { This was our move with 8.h4, but here the g4-pawn is defended, and White can immediately centralize their queen with } 10. Qd4 $16 { avoiding any ...Bb4 or ...Ba3 counterplay, nonsense, shenanigans, and tomfoolery. } ) 10. Qf3 { The critical move, preparing O-O-O. } 10... d5 11. O-O-O Bb4 { Other moves have been tried, but I find this the most reliable one, forcing matters on the center. } 12. Bd2 $5 { Another suggestion by the engine, although I think that it is more dificult to face this from an unprepared opponent. White does not release tension in the center. } 12... d4 13. Nb1 $1 { The strongest move. The knight has a very good square on c4. } 13... Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 c5 { We protect our center and intend to play ...Bb7 next. White now has two approaches: pushing g5 immediately or preparing it with h4. } 15. g5 hxg5 16. Rxg5 Bb7 $1 { There was no way of defending the g7-pawn, but fortunately we can get good compensation for it. } ( 16... Rg8 $2 17. e5 Bb7 18. Qh3 Nd5 $146 19. Rxg7 { Black's position falls apart. } ) 17. Rxg7 Ke7 { Now that we have managed to complete development, we can take a look at the position and give a clearer evaluation. White is a pawn up, but it is the one on h2, which is well controlled by our rook on h8. Our king is still a little bit weak, but in an endgame we will enjoy good compensation on the kingside in the style of a mirrored Benko gambit, with open lines and weak squares as compensation. } 18. Bc4 $2 Rag8 { We should not be greedy. } 19. Rxg8 Rxg8 20. h3 Nxe4 $146 { An important tactical point. } 21. Nxe4 $146 Qe5 22. Bd3 c4 23. Bxc4 Bxe4 24. Qe2 a5 $10 $13 { Black has sufficient compensation in the form of a big center and easy play against White's weakness on the kingside. Our king is prepared to support our central majority in case of an endgame. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "6.Be2 - 7th Move Sidelines: 7.Nbd5"]
