1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing 9. Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. Bg5 { This is actually a novelty, but it looks very natural and it is the first choice of the machine. } 10... h6 { This move does not hurt us and can help us avoid back-rank issues. } 11. Bh4 d6 { Stopping e5 is necessary. } ( 11... a6 12. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 13. e5 { is a trick we should be aware of. } 13... axb5 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qg4+ Kh8 17. Qh4 Kg7 18. Rae1 { Black will not survive this attack. } ) 12. c4 { Gaining space in the center is also quite logical. } 12... a6 { The right moment to force White to exchange: now d3 has been slightly weakened. } 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Nc3 e5 15. c5 $5 { A typical pawn sacrifice in this kind of position. } 15... dxc5 16. Bc4 Rd8 $133 { [%cal Gd8d4]White has active bishops, but it is not completely certain how is he going to continue the attack and the d4-square will be perfect for our rook. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "6.a3: 7.Nxc6 "]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.a3: 7.Nxc6 "]
[Black "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. a3 a6 7. Nxc6 $5 { This dangerous try was given by Miguel Santos in his fantastic Open Sicilian course. It is quite dangerous, and typical Taimanov play can quickly lead to bad positions, so we should be careful. Actually, I believe there is only one clear equalizer against this line, and it was already shown in his repertoire! } ( 7. f4 { transposes to 6.f4. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) ( 7. Be3 { transposes to 6.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 7... bxc6 { The most reliable move, in accordance with our reaction to most of these early Nxc6 moves. } ( 7... dxc6 { Better than 7...bxc6 and quite playable, but it is not the best version of this pawn structure for us. } 8. Be3 $2 { There are other moves, but this looks like the most promising to me. } 8... b5 9. Qf3 e5 10. g4 $2 $36 { Black has still an acceptable position, but it looks very easy to play with White. } ) 8. Qg4 { White develops the queen to an active square and tries to exchange queens with Qg3. } 8... Nf6 9. Qg3 Qxg3 { We cannot avoid a queen exchange. } ( 9... e5 $2 10. Be2 g6 $2 11. f4 $16 { is highly dangerous for Black. } ) 10. hxg3 d5 11. Bd3 { The most natural move, developing the bishop to a good square while defending the pawn. } 11... Bd6 $1 { This is arguably the most important move in the entire line for us! From d6, we avoid White's most natural plan, which consists of playing f3 & g4 and usually grants them a comfortable edge. } 12. Bf4 $1 { The most critical move, also suggested by Santos. If we exchange, White gets another pawn in the center, and if we play 12...e5, which seems very natural and is actually our choice, we slightly weaken the d5-square. White will try to play on the light squares with this move. } 12... e5 { The most ambitious and the move that leads to clear-cut equality. } ( 12... Bxf4 13. gxf4 a5 { This is also playable if you want to cut the theory, but I am not sure Black has equalizes completely now that White has more pawns controlling the center. } 14. f3 Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. O-O-O $14 ) 13. Bg5 Be6 { This is technically a novelty, it was already given by Santos in his 1.e4 course! It is a very natural one: we should not weaken the light squares in the center with 13...d4 unprovoked. } ( 13... d4 $2 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Na4 $146 Be6 16. f3 c5 17. b3 $16 ) 14. f4 $1 { The most critical move. White continues to play actively and puts us under pressure. } 14... d4 $1 { Now that there is a lot of tension in the center this advance gains strength. } ( 14... exf4 { should equalize in the end, but it leads to dry play. } ) 15. Na4 exf4 { Now we have to be ready for both captures: both are decent and testing! } 16. gxf4 Ng4 $1 { A strong move, getting out of e5 and improving the knight to better squares. } 17. f5 f6 $1 { [%cal Ge6c4][%csl Yc4]Another key move to remember! We need the bishop on the g8-a2 diagonal to control the weak light squares. } 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. fxe6 Ke7 20. Rh5 Ne3 $133 { [%cal Ga8g8,Gg8g2]Black gets enough counterplay on the kingside for the pawn. } * 

