1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qc2 Ne7 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5,Ge7c6]The best move in the position. Black's knight would have no future on f6: by developing it to e7, we are immediately putting our eye on the weak d4-square. } ( 8... Qf6 { is tempting, but it is not clear how Black should proceed after the ugly } 9. Bc1 $14 ) 9. Nc3 c5 10. Rd1 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4]} 11. Qd2 { This has also been tried, but it is not too critical because it allows Black's knight to immediately occupy the d4-square. } 11... Nd4 $1 12. Bd3 Be7 13. e5 { At first, this looks quite promising for White, but we have a diabolical tactical trick. } 13... Bb7 14. O-O Bf3 $1 { This move breaks White's coordination. } 15. Rde1 { This looks normal, but it can lead to problems for White. } 15... dxe5 16. Rxe5 Rb7 $1 { [%cal Gb7d7,Gf3a8]Black has excellent coordination between their pieces. We plan to improve the rook to d7 in the short term. } * 

