1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ( 3. Nc3 $146 { has little independent value, as } 3... Nc6 $146 4. d4 { transposes to the Open Sicilian, while 4... Nc6 4.Bb5 leads to harmless Rossolimo lines without c3. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 Nd4 $1 { The strongest move, forcing White to decide how to handle the bishop. } 5. O-O { The most critical move, recommended by British Grandmaster Gawain Jones in his Coffeehouse Repertoire series. We need to know our response by heart because it is not so intuitive. } 5... a6 6. Bd3 Nc6 $1 7. b3 { It is logical to develop the bishop to the diagonal, but we counter it. } 7... g6 $1 { The easiest. Our bishop on g7 will neutralize the bishop on b2. } 8. Bb2 Bg7 9. Re1 g5 { [%cal Gg5g4]} 10. h3 ( 10. e5 $2 { is a tricky idea, and although Black should be fine, I prefer to play in a more active way and spring a surprise on White. } ) 10... h5 $1 { [%cal Gg5g4,Gd7d6]} 11. g4 { This never works out well for White. } 11... hxg4 12. hxg4 Qf6 $19 { [%cal Gf6h6]Black has a decisive attack. } * 

