1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. Bd3 { This looks strange, but we should know what we're doing because White's plan is fundamentally sound: they want to put the bishop on c2 and then get great control of the center with d4. } 4... d5 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bc2 c4 7. Qe2 { This has been recommended recently by the well-known theoretician Michael Roiz, so we should examine it closely. } ( 7. O-O { transposes to 6.O-O (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 7... Nc6 8. d4 { We will study Roiz's main recommendation } ( 8. O-O { via the 6.O-O move order. } ) 8... cxd3 9. Bxd3 h6 $1 { A good move, we control the g5-square and prepare the ...g5 push, which is a good way to fight for control of the e5-square. } 10. h4 Be7 11. Bf4 Nc5 12. b4 $5 { The best move according to Stockfish, and also the recommendation of Roiz in his repertoire. } 12... Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 { Roiz stops here, calling it a complex position. I agree with him, but it is also clear that with the bishop pair we are not the side risking being worse. } 13... Bd7 14. Nbd2 Qc7 $133 { [%cal Ge8c8,Gc8b8,Gh8g8,Gg7g5]I like the plan of castling queenside and trying to push ...g5 on the kingside. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
