[Black "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { This is clearly the most testing move. It is not easy for White to develop the minor pieces on the queenside to good squares, so he decides to improve the queen and the rook to its best available squares: e2 for the queen and d1 for the rook. } 9... dxe5 $5 { There are other moves, but I like to play in a forcing way against this variation. First, we release tension in the center and force White to decide if he wants to take with the knight or the pawn. } 10. dxe5 Bd7 $1 { The key move in our system against the Alapin is to develop the bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal. It's important to avoid the natural move ...b6, for both concrete and positional reasons. the concerete reason is } ( 10... b6 $2 11. Rd1 Bb7 12. Nc3 $146 { and after 13...Bxf3? 14.Qxf3 , our rook on a8 is hanging! The positional reason is that the bishop will be protected on c6 by a pawn, which can be quite useful. } ) 11. Rd1 { The mainline, putting pressure on the d5-knight and centralizing the rook. } 11... Bc6 12. Nd4 Bc5 $1 { The strongest move, in my opinion. We improve the bishop and make contact with White's knight, which reduces White's mobility. } 13. Nxc6 $2 { This has been played quite a bit, but it is not very good. We are very ahead in development. } 13... Nxc6 14. Bd2 $2 { A weak move. A high-profile GM game finished quite quickly: } 14... Bd4 15. Bc3 Bxc3 $1 16. Bxd5 $2 Nd4 $19 { [%cal Rc3b2][%csl Rb2]0-1 Van Foreest,L (2556)-Harsha,B (2602) Sharjah Masters 6th 2023 (3) } * 

