1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { This is clearly the most testing move. It is not easy for White to develop the minor pieces on the queenside to good squares, so he decides to improve the queen and the rook to its best available squares: e2 for the queen and d1 for the rook. } 9... dxe5 $5 { There are other moves, but I like to play in a forcing way against this variation. First, we release tension in the center and force White to decide if he wants to take with the knight or the pawn. } 10. dxe5 Bd7 $1 { The key move in our system against the Alapin is to develop the bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal. It's important to avoid the natural move ...b6, for both concrete and positional reasons. the concerete reason is } ( 10... b6 $2 11. Rd1 Bb7 12. Nc3 $146 { and after 13...Bxf3? 14.Qxf3 , our rook on a8 is hanging! The positional reason is that the bishop will be protected on c6 by a pawn, which can be quite useful. } ) 11. Rd1 { The mainline, putting pressure on the d5-knight and centralizing the rook. } 11... Bc6 12. Bxd5 { This is a very concrete attempt. Black is fine, but we should remember the following lines. } 12... Bxd5 13. Nc3 ( 13. Nd4 $146 Nc6 $146 { transposes to 12.Nd4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 13... Bxf3 $1 14. Qxf3 Qb6 { [%cal Gb8c6]Positionally, we are perfectly fine and even slightly better, but White has some attacking opportunities on the kingside that we should know how to parry. } 15. Ne4 Nc6 $1 { Not fearing any ghosts. } 16. Nf6+ Bxf6 17. exf6 Rfd8 $1 { This looks extremely dangerous, but everything works out tactically. } 18. Be3 Qxb2 19. fxg7 Rd5 $15 { Black has survived the attack and is likely to emerge a pawn up from the complications. 0-1 Khamrakulov,I-Grieve,H 2024 } * 

