1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. Kb1 Bb7 11. Bf4 $5 { The only line with independent value. It's not particularly strong, but it's useful to know the following moves and the engine's evaluation at the end of the line, as it will give us greater confidence when defending! } ( 11. g4 Nxd4 $146 12. Bxd4 O-O { this transposes to 10.g4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 11... e5 12. Nf5 { White's idea. } 12... exf4 13. Nd5 Qb8 $1 { We could not take on d5 because of exd5 & d6, so we calmly retreat the queen. } ( 13... Qe5 $2 { This is not good because the bishop on b7 is hanging after } 14. Ndxe7 $146 Nxe7 $146 15. Nd6+ $146 Kf8 16. Nxb7 $16 $146 ) 14. Nxg7+ Kf8 15. Nf5 Qe5 $1 { A strong centralizing queen move. } 16. Nxf4 h5 $1 { Covering the key square h6 while stopping g4, a possible White plan. } 17. g3 Bd8 $15 { [%cal Gc6e7]Another strong move, planning to remove White's knight with ...Ne7, while possibly maneuvering the bishop to better squares, like c7 or b6. Objectively, Black is more than fine, although the position is quite wild, and all three results are possible. } * 

