1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. Nxc6 { This was recommended by Negi in his legendary 1. e4 series of books. It leads to a very interesting and complex pawn structure that every Taimanov player should be aware of. In general, after taking on c6 with the pawn, we aim for a setup with ...O-O, followed by ...e5 and ...Be6, eventually looking to launch a queenside attack. The pawn on a2 is always a weakness for White, and a3 is not ideal, as it provides us with a breaking point through b4. Moves like Kb1 can also be met with ...b4, which serves as our main source of counterplay. White will attempt to develop an initiative on the kingside, and we'll need to defend against that rather than going all-in on the queenside, as our attack may not be as strong. Overall, it's a very dynamic and fighting position that can lead to exciting chess! } 10... dxc6 { The correct recapture. Black struggles to develop any counterplay after } ( 10... Qxc6 $2 11. g4 ) 11. g4 O-O 12. g5 { Quite risky for White; the knight on h5 is difficult to expel, and White creates significant weaknesses on the kingside. Additionally, their structure has become much less flexible. } 12... Nh5 13. Bh3 Rd8 $1 14. Qf2 Nf4 $1 { Black manages to occupy the f4-square, and the g5-pawn also comes under attack. } 15. Bg4 Bxg5 $15 { Not enough compensation for White. } * 

