1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. Nxc6 { This was recommended by Negi in his legendary 1. e4 series of books. It leads to a very interesting and complex pawn structure that every Taimanov player should be aware of. In general, after taking on c6 with the pawn, we aim for a setup with ...O-O, followed by ...e5 and ...Be6, eventually looking to launch a queenside attack. The pawn on a2 is always a weakness for White, and a3 is not ideal, as it provides us with a breaking point through b4. Moves like Kb1 can also be met with ...b4, which serves as our main source of counterplay. White will attempt to develop an initiative on the kingside, and we'll need to defend against that rather than going all-in on the queenside, as our attack may not be as strong. Overall, it's a very dynamic and fighting position that can lead to exciting chess! } 10... dxc6 { The correct recapture. Black struggles to develop any counterplay after } ( 10... Qxc6 $2 11. g4 ) 11. g4 O-O 12. h4 { This is solid, but not particularly inspiring. } 12... Rd8 13. Qh2 { Negi mentions this as a possible try for an advantage, but it does not give anything for White with precise play. } 13... Qxh2 14. Rxh2 e5 15. Rxd8+ Bxd8 { [%cal Gd8c7,Gc8e6,Gf6d7]Black is fine in this endgame. White has more space on the kingside, but these are also potential weaknesses, such as the pawn on h4, the pawn on f3, and the square on f4. If White pushes h5, we can maneuver our knight to g5, possibly first exchanging dark-squared bishops on g5. If White doesn't push, we can play ...h5 ourselves, and after White plays g5, we can try to bring the knight to g6, where it will be very well-placed. Note also that the immediate h5 is not possible. } 16. h5 $2 Bxg4 $1 17. fxg4 Nxg4 $17 { Black wins material. } * 

