1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Qxd4 { This is also possible, although not so critical in my opinion. This move has two main problems: after ...Bb7 & ...Rc8, White needs to spend a tempo defending against ...b4, and White also has to consider ...Bc5, which exchanges dark-squared bishops—something that always works in our favor. } 11... Bb7 12. g5 { White needs to create some play; otherwise we will be more than fine after ...Rc8. } 12... Nh5 13. Bh3 { The most direct move, but Black is well-placed to meet it. } 13... Rc8 $1 14. Rd2 $6 { This defends against one threat, but we can enter a very favourable endgame. } 14... Bc5 $1 15. Qxc5 Qxc5 16. Bxc5 Rxc5 $17 { [%cal Gh5f4,Ge8e7,Gd7d6,Gh7h6][%csl Rf3,Rg5,Rh2]The g5-pawn is under a lot of pressure, and we have a magnificent outpost for our knight on f4. White should not survive this. They shall perish. } * 

