1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Qxd4 { This is also possible, although not so critical in my opinion. This move has two main problems: after ...Bb7 & ...Rc8, White needs to spend a tempo defending against ...b4, and White also has to consider ...Bc5, which exchanges dark-squared bishops—something that always works in our favor. } 11... Bb7 12. g5 { White needs to create some play; otherwise we will be more than fine after ...Rc8. } 12... Nh5 13. Bh3 { The most direct move, but Black is well-placed to meet it. } 13... Rc8 $1 14. Qd2 { It cannot be good to take on d4 with the queen and then go back to d2. } 14... b4 15. Ne2 d5 $1 { We launch our counterplay with no delay. } 16. Bg4 g6 17. Bxh5 gxh5 18. e5 d4 $1 { As always, we do not allow White to block our bishops or occupy the outpost on d4. } 19. Nxd4 O-O $19 { [%cal Gb7d5,Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Gb4b3]Our structure on the kingside is bad, but it makes it very difficult for White to advance with h4-h5-g6. They would first need to take the pawn on h5 and then advance, but that takes too many tempi. White is going to get mated on the queenside in the meantime! } * 

