1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Qxd4 { This is also possible, although not so critical in my opinion. This move has two main problems: after ...Bb7 & ...Rc8, White needs to spend a tempo defending against ...b4, and White also has to consider ...Bc5, which exchanges dark-squared bishops—something that always works in our favor. } 11... Bb7 12. g5 { White needs to create some play; otherwise we will be more than fine after ...Rc8. } 12... Nh5 13. Ne2 $6 { This move does not make a lot of sense and we can punish it. } 13... Rc8 14. Qd2 d5 $1 { We should always keep this move in mind in the English Attack! Many times, its appearance on the board signals that Black is taking control. } 15. e5 d4 $1 { A very beautiful move that has appeared in other parts of the course. It is more important to open the bishop on b7 than to keep a pawn. Here, White doesn't even manage to hold material due to their weaknesses on f3 and e5. } 16. Nxd4 O-O $15 { [%cal Gc7e5,Gf8d8]0-1 Kurmann, O - Berkes, F Bad Wiessee, 2013 e5 is about to fall. f4 is not possible since the h1-rook is hanging and Bf4 is looking terrible since the dark-squared bishop is extremely important in these kinds of positions. } * 

