1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Qxd4 { This is also possible, although not so critical in my opinion. This move has two main problems: after ...Bb7 & ...Rc8, White needs to spend a tempo defending against ...b4, and White also has to consider ...Bc5, which exchanges dark-squared bishops—something that always works in our favor. } 11... Bb7 12. g5 { White needs to create some play; otherwise we will be more than fine after ...Rc8. } 12... Nh5 13. Kb1 { This prudent move is the main line. } 13... Rc8 { [%cal Gb5b4]Threatening ...b4. } 14. Qd2 g6 $1 { A strong prophylactic move. The knight is defended in many variations, giving us more freedom of action. } 15. Bh3 b4 16. Ne2 d5 $1 { This move releases a lot of latent energy in our position. } 17. e5 { White's idea is to play Nd4 and even sacrifice the e5-pawn if it means keeping our bishops trapped. However, we have a typical breakthrough that gives us excellent counterplay. } 17... d4 $1 18. Nxd4 O-O { After this elegant pawn sacrifice, Black is more than fine. The e5-pawn is hanging, and we have a straightforward plan to launch an attack on the queenside, while White faces much greater difficulty due to our strong knight on h5. } 19. Bg4 ( 19. Qf2 { is too slow, as Black wins material after } 19... Qxe5 $15 ) ( 19. Rhe1 Rfd8 { improving the rook and pinning the knight } 20. Qf2 Qxe5 $15 { No compensation for the pawn. Black is better. } ) 19... Rfd8 20. Bxh5 gxh5 $17 { [%cal Ga6a5,Ga5a4,Ga4a3]Black's attack is unstoppable, while White lacks meaningful counterplay on the queenside. } * 

