1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Bxd4 { The most natural and popular recapture. } 11... Bb7 12. g5 { The most concrete move, leading to many forced lines. } 12... Nh5 13. Be5 { This surprising move has been known for a long time, and Black has found decent antidotes against it. } 13... Qxe5 14. Qxd7+ Kf8 15. Qxb7 Qb8 $1 { This was already mentioned by Van Kampen as an interesting alternative to taking on g5, and I still believe it's easier for us to play and trickier for White to handle. } ( 15... Bxg5+ { This is much more natural, recovering the pawn with check, but Black sometimes struggles to generate sufficient counterplay on the kingside. The pawn on g5 actually helps us do it! } 16. Kb1 Qb8 17. Rd7 Qxb7 18. Rxb7 Bd2 19. a4 Bxc3 20. bxc3 bxa4 21. Bxa6 $13 { This endgame is roughly equal, but I think in practice it's easier to play with White. Their plan is very straightforward: advancing and queening the c-pawn. } ) 16. Qxb8+ { This leads to similar play, but I believe it's better for White to have the rook on d7—a rook on the seventh rank is always a bit unpleasant! } 16... Rxb8 17. Rg1 Nf4 $133 { [%cal Ge7c5,Gh7h6]The pawn on h2 is very weak and after an eventual ...h6 we will take it back. } * 

