1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Bxd4 { The most natural and popular recapture. } 11... Bb7 12. h4 { This is also a possible move. White aims to push the pawn to h5 before playing g5, preventing our knight from going to h5. } 12... O-O 13. h5 b4 $1 { We cannot stand still: we need to go for active counterplay on the queenside. } 14. Na4 Rac8 { Threatening ...Nxe4 followed by ...Bxe4. } 15. Bd3 d5 $1 { Always the same move! } 16. e5 Nd7 17. Qe3 Bc6 18. Nb6 Nxb6 19. Bxb6 Qd7 $10 { [%cal Bc6b5,Ba6a5,Ba5a4,Bc8c6,Bf8c8]The position becomes a bit drier without knights, and neither side has a clear advantage in the speed of attacks, so the position is roughly equal. Our plan is to exchange light-squared bishops with ...Bb5 and push on the queenside with ...a5-a4. } * 

