1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Bxd4 { The most natural and popular recapture. } 11... Bb7 12. Kb1 O-O 13. Bd3 e5 $5 { I think this is the safest move, } ( 13... b4 { can lead to very big complications. } ) 14. Bf2 b4 15. Nd5 $1 { White's best: } ( 15. Na4 $146 d5 { is very good for us. } ) 15... Nxd5 16. exd5 Bxd5 17. Bxh7+ { White's point. } 17... Kxh7 18. Qxd5 d6 $13 { [%cal Ba8c8,Bc8c4,Bf7f5]This position is roughly equal. White may try to launch an attack on the kingside, but ...Rac8 & ...Qc4 are coming quickly, and after exchanging queens, our central majority should make a difference, with moves like ...f5 becoming possible. } * 

