1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Bxd4 { The most natural and popular recapture. } 11... Bb7 12. Kb1 O-O 13. Rg1 $5 { Tried by Shankland, a Taimanov expert, so we should be attentive to this idea. } 13... e5 { I think that, the same as against 13.Bd3, it makes sense to avoid the complications that arise after } ( 13... b4 14. Na4 $146 d5 15. Nb6 $146 Rad8 16. e5 Ne4 $2 $146 17. fxe4 dxe4 18. Nc4 $146 { , where Black needs to be very precise to prove compensation for the piece. Note that with the pawn on h4, as in the So-Artemiev game, Nc4 was not possible because of ...e3!, but now the rook is not threatened on h1. } ) 14. Bf2 Rfd8 $1 { [%cal Gd7d5]} 15. g5 Nh5 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. exd5 Bc5 $13 { This position can get quite tricky for White: our knight will be very strong on f4 after the exchange of dark-squared bishops. } * 

