1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Bxd4 { The most natural and popular recapture. } 11... Bb7 12. Kb1 O-O 13. Qf2 { This has been tried by Caruana and is also decent, because f2 is a good square for White's queen in this kind of position, although it is a little bit slow. } 13... d5 $1 { Playing concretely. } 14. g5 Nh5 15. e5 { This is a viable pawn sacrifice, although with the pawn on e5, the dark- squared bishop no longer participates in the attack. } 15... Bxg5 $1 16. Rg1 f6 $13 { [%cal Gf8f7,Ga8c8,Gh5f4]Strong: now the queen will participate in the defense, and we can also reinforce the g7-pawn with ...Rf7. The position is complex, but Black is fine—White still needs to prove compensation. } * 

