1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O ( 8. f3 { does not have any independent value. White will need to castle long and he does not get anything from avoiding it or delaying it. } 8... Be7 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nh5 $146 11. O-O-O Nxd4 $146 { Now, any recapture on d4 transposes to 8.O-O-O } ) 8... Be7 9. f3 b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } ( 10... Bb7 $2 11. g5 Nh5 $146 { Our knight is normally well-placed on h5, but here White can take advantage of our mistake and start to put pressure against it. } ) 11. Bxd4 { The most natural and popular recapture. } 11... Bb7 12. Kb1 O-O 13. Qf2 { This has been tried by Caruana and is also decent, because f2 is a good square for White's queen in this kind of position, although it is a little bit slow. } 13... d5 $1 { Playing concretely. } 14. g5 Nh5 15. exd5 b4 16. Bb6 Qb8 17. Na4 Bxd5 $13 { The bishop on d5 is very strong, and Black's knight can come to f4. The queen can also reach b7 in some variations, and White needs to be cautious with the knight on a4. Black's position seems more pleasant to me, although it has consistently ended in a draw in correspondence games, as usual! } * 

