1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 { Some years ago, there were some players that started to experiment with 7...Be7!? because of the 8.f4 try that we are going to analyze. However, if White is ready for it, in the end he has more flexibility and the subtlety can backfire. } ( 7... Be7 { The idea is to avoid some sidelines and transpose to the main line, however, it also allows several unpleasant possibilities: } ) 8. f4 { Creates the positional threat of e4-e5, so Black has to take action immediately. } 8... Bb4 { Now that f3 is not possible, this is the best move, putting pressure on e4. } 9. Nxc6 { This has never been tried, and probably for good reason. All recaptures are fine, maybe the easiest is... } 9... dxc6 $5 10. e5 Nd5 $13 { A good position thanks to the pressure on c3. } * 

