[White "6.Be3 / 7.Qd2 / 8.f4: 9.Bd3 / 10.e5 #1"]
[Black "3) 6.Be3 / 7.Qd2 / 8.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 { Some years ago, there were some players that started to experiment with 7...Be7!? because of the 8.f4 try that we are going to analyze. However, if White is ready for it, in the end he has more flexibility and the subtlety can backfire. } ( 7... Be7 { The idea is to avoid some sidelines and transpose to the main line, however, it also allows several unpleasant possibilities: } ) 8. f4 { Creates the positional threat of e4-e5, so Black has to take action immediately. } 8... Bb4 { Now that f3 is not possible, this is the best move, putting pressure on e4. } 9. Bd3 { Tha main move, defending e4. } 9... Na5 { [%cal Ga5c4]I have tried to make other moves work, but this is simply the most reliable. We want to play ...Nc4 and prepare ...Bxc3 in the meantime. } 10. e5 { This has been tried only three times, but it is actually a decent attempt that we should be aware of. } 10... Nd5 11. O-O $1 { White sacrifices material to speed up development. } 11... Bxc3 ( 11... Nxc3 $146 { This is tempting, but I think the endgame after } 12. a3 Be7 13. Qxc3 Qxc3 14. bxc3 { is more tricky to defend. } ) 12. bxc3 Nc4 { We force the exchange of one of White's bishops. } 13. Bxc4 Qxc4 14. a4 $5 b6 $1 { A difficult move, but necessary: a5 is a positional threat in many variations. Now White has nothing but f5, which should lead to play similar to the next line. } ( 14... Qxc3 { The following game is a good illustration of why playing ...b6 is necessary. } 15. Qxc3 Nxc3 $146 16. Rfe1 Nd5 $146 17. c4 Ne7 $146 18. Rab1 Nc6 $146 19. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 20. a5 ) * 

