1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 { Some years ago, there were some players that started to experiment with 7...Be7!? because of the 8.f4 try that we are going to analyze. However, if White is ready for it, in the end he has more flexibility and the subtlety can backfire. } ( 7... Be7 { The idea is to avoid some sidelines and transpose to the main line, however, it also allows several unpleasant possibilities: } ) 8. f4 { Creates the positional threat of e4-e5, so Black has to take action immediately. } 8... Bb4 { Now that f3 is not possible, this is the best move, putting pressure on e4. } 9. Bd3 { Tha main move, defending e4. } 9... Na5 { [%cal Ga5c4]I have tried to make other moves work, but this is simply the most reliable. We want to play ...Nc4 and prepare ...Bxc3 in the meantime. } 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 12. bxc3 d5 $1 { It is necessary to fight for the e4 and c4 central light squares. Now our bishop can also be developed. } 13. e5 { The antidote to this line was already played in 2014 by Giri, and showed by Van Kampen in his Chess24 Taimanov course! Times have changed, but we should still be prepared for this move. } 13... Ne4 { Black's bishop is passive on c8, but in return, the knights are very active. } 14. Bxe4 $6 { This is completely harmless for Black. } 14... dxe4 $37 { [%cal Ga5c4,Gc8d7]Next, the knight goes to c4. From that square, it can be easily supported with moves like ...Bd7 & ...Rc8. } * 

