and the endgame is just too unpleasant. } ) 14. Nb3 $1 { A very precise move, vacating the d4-square for White's bishop. Otherwise, Black equalizes very comfortably. } 14... Nc4 15. Bd4 Ne4 { [%cal Bd4g7,Gh8g8,Gg8g7][%csl Rg7][%cal Gg7g2][%csl Rg2]Now our knights occupy the ideal squares in the center. The g7-pawn is not hanging, because of ...Rxg2 at the end of the line. } 16. Nc5 { The best try for White, trying to exchange our strong knight. } 16... Nxc5 17. Bxc5 Bd7 $5 { Khalifman mentions } ( 17... b6 { , which is also a clear equalizer, but I believe ...Bd7 is more principled: we do not need to give up material just yet. } ) 18. O-O $5 { Much less played than O-O-O, but there are some differences with the main line that we should be aware of. The pawn on g2 being defended makes a big difference. } 18... O-O-O 19. Bd4 f6 20. Rfe1 Rde8 21. Rxe8+ Bxe8 $1 { With the king on f2, as happened in Werle's game in the next line, Black was able to take with the rook. Now, the pawn on h2 is defended, and we should take with the bishop. A draw was agreed in a correspondence game after... } 22. g4 Bg6 23. Kf2 Be4 { Black didnt face any problems in the final position with the strong pieces Be4 and Nc4 in ½-½ Haugen, A - Kovac, S, 2019 } * 

