1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 { Some years ago, there were some players that started to experiment with } ( 7... Be7 $2 { because of the } 8. f4 { try that we are going to analyze. However, if White is ready for it, in the end they have more flexibility and the subtlety can backfire. } ) 8. O-O-O Be7 { This has been preferred by strong players in recent years. } 9. f4 { White's idea is to play e4-e5 while Black already lost a tempo with ...Be7, so ...Bb4 isn't the best move in this position. } 9... b5 { The best move, threatening ...b4. } 10. Bd3 { This is much less critical. If White plays f4, they should really play e5. } 10... Bb7 11. e5 b4 $1 { The key move in these variations. } 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Rc8 $1 { [%cal Gc6e5]A strong move, threatening some tactical tricks like ...Nxe5 and against Bxb7, ...Nc4. } 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Bxc6 Qxc6 $15 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gf8d8,Gd7d6][%csl Rc2]We will manage to castle without problems thanks to the weakness of the c2-pawn. } * 

