1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 { Some years ago, there were some players that started to experiment with } ( 7... Be7 $2 { because of the } 8. f4 { try that we are going to analyze. However, if White is ready for it, in the end they have more flexibility and the subtlety can backfire. } ) 8. O-O-O Be7 { This has been preferred by strong players in recent years. } 9. f4 { White's idea is to play e4-e5 while Black already lost a tempo with ...Be7, so ...Bb4 isn't the best move in this position. } 9... b5 { The best move, threatening ...b4. } 10. e5 { The critical move. } 10... b4 $1 { The logical and typical Taimanov response to the central advance e5 . } ( 10... Ng4 $146 11. Bg1 $16 ) 11. exf6 { This is also a very direct line that we should know by heart. } 11... bxc3 12. Qxc3 Bxf6 13. g4 { The best move, trying to rudely eject our f6-bishop with g5. } 13... h6 $1 { It is key to stop g5. } 14. g5 $6 hxg5 15. fxg5 Be5 $15 { Our bishop does not leave the diagonal, so we are a smidge better. } * 

