1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 { Some years ago, there were some players that started to experiment with } ( 7... Be7 $2 { because of the } 8. f4 { try that we are going to analyze. However, if White is ready for it, in the end they have more flexibility and the subtlety can backfire. } ) 8. O-O-O Be7 { This has been preferred by strong players in recent years. } 9. f4 { White's idea is to play e4-e5 while Black already lost a tempo with ...Be7, so ...Bb4 isn't the best move in this position. } 9... b5 { The best move, threatening ...b4. } 10. e5 { The critical move. } 10... b4 $1 { The logical and typical Taimanov response to the central advance e5 . } ( 10... Ng4 $146 11. Bg1 $16 ) 11. exf6 { This is also a very direct line that we should know by heart. } 11... bxc3 12. Qxc3 Bxf6 13. g4 { The best move, trying to rudely eject our f6-bishop with g5. } 13... h6 $1 { It is key to stop g5. } 14. h4 Bb7 15. Rh2 Qd6 $1 { The key move in the line, and a difficult one! We get out of the pin on the c-file and threaten to exchange on d4, making the pawn on f4 a bit loose. It looks strange to place the queen on d6 with such a strong rook on d1, but White doesn't have any effective discovered attacks. } 16. Rhd2 { The most straightforward move, which leads to a complex position. } 16... Nxd4 { The following sequence is forced. } 17. Bxd4 Qxf4 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Qxf6 gxf6 20. Rxd7 Bf3 21. R1d6 { Now comes a key move we should remember. } 21... h5 $1 { Taking on g4 with the bishop would maintain material equality, but our rook on h8 would have a hard time getting into play. This move is much stronger because White is forced to activate our rook; g5 would give us a very strong passed h-pawn. } ( 21... Bxg4 $2 22. Bxa6 $16 ) 22. gxh5 Rxh5 23. Bxa6 Bc6 $1 { Another key move! We break the coordination between White's pieces. } ( 23... Rxh4 $2 24. Bb5 Kf8 25. Rd8+ Rxd8 26. Rxd8+ Kg7 27. c4 $36 { Although with perfect play it is probably a draw, White looks much faster to the human eye. } ) 24. Be2 Bxd7 25. Bxh5 Rxa2 26. b4 { ½-½ Lubienski, A - Chronopoulos, A. 2021. A draw was agreed to here in this very complex endgame between correspondence players. In a human practical endgame, anything can happen; our central majority is also very strong. } * 

