1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 { Some years ago, there were some players that started to experiment with } ( 7... Be7 $2 { because of the } 8. f4 { try that we are going to analyze. However, if White is ready for it, in the end they have more flexibility and the subtlety can backfire. } ) 8. O-O-O Be7 { This has been preferred by strong players in recent years. } 9. f4 { White's idea is to play e4-e5 while Black already lost a tempo with ...Be7, so ...Bb4 isn't the best move in this position. } 9... b5 { The best move, threatening ...b4. } 10. e5 { The critical move. } 10... b4 $1 { The logical and typical Taimanov response to the central advance e5 . } ( 10... Ng4 $146 11. Bg1 $16 ) 11. Ncb5 $5 { The most critical move, leading to crazy complications in many variations. Black is fine, but he needs to know some key variations by heart, because they are not very intuitive. } 11... axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 $1 { The most reliable move. } ( 12... Qb8 { is possible, but it is not clear that Black completely equalizes after } 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Kb1 d5 15. Qf2 $14 ) 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Nd6+ ( 14. Bc4 { was not possible because of } 14... d5 { , so White needs to take up the gauntlet and enter the complications. } ) 14... Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Qxa2 16. Rd3 $1 { A very strong move. Now the king can escape via d2, and the rook is very well located on the third rank in many variations. } 16... Qa1+ 17. Kd2 Ra2 $3 { This is the key move to remember. We need to keep coordination between our major pieces. Taking on b2 inmediately would be a great mistake. } ( 17... Qxb2 $2 18. Rb3 Qa1 19. Bc5 $16 ) 18. Rb3 { White does not let us coordinate on the second rank. } 18... Rxb2 19. Bb5 $1 { White's concrete idea. Now the game gets even crazier and forced. } 19... Qxh1 20. Bxc6 { White takes on c6 and defends g2. We need to take the pawn; otherwise White can take on d7 and deliver mate. } 20... dxc6 21. Qxc6+ Kf8 22. Bc5+ Kg7 23. Rg3+ { This seems scary, but White lacks another major piece and cannot deliver mate. } 23... Kh6 24. Rh3+ Kg7 25. Rg3+ Kh6 26. Rh3+ Kg7 { ½-½ Sosa, T - Iermito, S San Cristobal de La Laguna, 2022. The game ended in perpetual. } * 

