1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 { Some years ago, there were some players that started to experiment with } ( 7... Be7 $2 { because of the } 8. f4 { try that we are going to analyze. However, if White is ready for it, in the end they have more flexibility and the subtlety can backfire. } ) 8. O-O-O Be7 { This has been preferred by strong players in recent years. } 9. f4 { White's idea is to play e4-e5 while Black already lost a tempo with ...Be7, so ...Bb4 isn't the best move in this position. } 9... b5 { The best move, threatening ...b4. } 10. e5 { The critical move. } 10... b4 $1 { The logical and typical Taimanov response to the central advance e5 . } ( 10... Ng4 $146 11. Bg1 $16 ) 11. Ncb5 $5 { The most critical move, leading to crazy complications in many variations. Black is fine, but he needs to know some key variations by heart, because they are not very intuitive. } 11... axb5 12. Nxb5 Qa5 $1 { The most reliable move. } ( 12... Qb8 { is possible, but it is not clear that Black completely equalizes after } 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Kb1 d5 15. Qf2 $14 ) 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Nd6+ ( 14. Bc4 { was not possible because of } 14... d5 { , so White needs to take up the gauntlet and enter the complications. } ) 14... Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Qxa2 16. Rd3 $1 { A very strong move. Now the king can escape via d2, and the rook is very well located on the third rank in many variations. } 16... Qa1+ 17. Kd2 Ra2 $3 { This is the key move to remember. We need to keep coordination between our major pieces. Taking on b2 inmediately would be a great mistake. } ( 17... Qxb2 $2 18. Rb3 Qa1 19. Bc5 $16 ) 18. Rb3 { White does not let us coordinate on the second rank. } 18... Rxb2 19. Bb5 $1 { White's concrete idea. Now the game gets even crazier and forced. } 19... Qxh1 20. Bxc6 { White takes on c6 and defends g2. We need to take the pawn; otherwise White can take on d7 and deliver mate. } 20... dxc6 21. Qxc6+ Kf8 22. Bd4 $5 { The most critical. White takes on f6 and tries to deliver mate on the dark squares, and the rook can also swing to g3. That's the reason we take on h2: to avoid Rg3 in some variations and to threaten the pawn on f4. } 22... Qxh2 $1 { The only move that saves the day. Now the game gets quite forced again. } 23. Qc5+ Kg8 $1 { Only move, the other retreats lead to mate. } 24. Qxc8+ Kg7 25. Bxf6+ Kxf6 26. Qxh8+ { It looks like we are losing a rook, but in reality we are giving a perpetual check because of the exposed position of White's king. } 26... Ke7 27. Qxb2 Qxg2+ 28. Kd3 Qf3+ 29. Kd2 Qf2+ 30. Kd3 Qf3+ 31. Kd2 { White cannot get out of the checks. Even if he gets to the queenside, their major pieces will not manage to cover the king out of the checks. Quite a long variation! } * 

