1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. Qe2 $5 { The modern way. White keeps flexibility on which way is he going to castle, and gains some options in case of 8...b5. } 8... b5 9. f4 $5 { This pawn gambit has also been tried by some strong players, like Amonatov or Kovaleskaya, so we should give attention to it. Normally it is dangerous to take it, but here it works tactically. } 9... Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Qxf4 $1 { No fear! } 11. Rf1 Qd6 $1 { The key move. The threat on White's bishop gives us a much needed tempo. } 12. Qf2 { [%cal Ge4e5]} 12... e5 13. Be3 Be7 14. O-O-O O-O $13 { White has some compensation for the pawn, but he has to prove it. } 15. Bxb5 { recovers the pawn, but it opens the b-file and after } 15... Qb4 { we have good counterplay! } * 

