1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. Qe2 $5 { The modern way. White keeps flexibility on which way is he going to castle, and gains some options in case of 8...b5. } 8... b5 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 $5 { This move has a bad reputation, and Harikhrisna even awards it a '?!' sign in his brilliant course. Stockfish initially dislikes it, but I believe it is a good move, and in practical terms, I would argue that it is even better than 9...dxc6. With 9...dxc6 White can force a repetition quite quickly, and he has several testing tries that force us to remember some lines with great precision. } ( 9... Qxc6 { leads to a strange position in the main line after } 10. e5 { , that the engines assess as White's advantage, but I think the position is a three-results game and quite decent to play with Black. } ) 10. O-O-O b4 11. Nd5 $5 { White's idea. } 11... exd5 $5 { We can take the knight, because the discovery attacks are not too dangerous. } 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Be4 $2 { This seems winning for White, but we have a strong tactical theme. } 13... Nc3 $1 14. bxc3 Qxe4 $19 * 

