1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. Qe2 $5 { The modern way. White keeps flexibility on which way is he going to castle, and gains some options in case of 8...b5. } 8... b5 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 $5 { This move has a bad reputation, and Harikhrisna even awards it a '?!' sign in his brilliant course. Stockfish initially dislikes it, but I believe it is a good move, and in practical terms, I would argue that it is even better than 9...dxc6. With 9...dxc6 White can force a repetition quite quickly, and he has several testing tries that force us to remember some lines with great precision. } ( 9... Qxc6 { leads to a strange position in the main line after } 10. e5 { , that the engines assess as White's advantage, but I think the position is a three-results game and quite decent to play with Black. } ) 10. e5 $1 { If White had castled instead of playing 8.Qe2, we would play the intermezzo } 10... b4 $1 { Our idea is to launch this typical Taimanov intermezzo, instead of removing the knight from f6. } ( 10... Bb7 { , with a great position. We do not have that here and that is one of the main points of 8.Qe2. } ) ( 10... Nd5 $146 11. Be4 Bb4 12. Bd2 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Bb7 14. Bb4 $14 { This is solid for Black, but passive, and I do not like to tolerate such a dark-squared bishop. } ) 11. exf6 bxc3 12. Bd4 cxb2 13. Bxb2 g6 $1 { The roles are reversed with respect to 12.fxg7: now we are the ones with the king that does not breathe too comfortably! But we have enough counterplay and we do not need to define the position of our king too quick: the king is reasonably safe. } 14. O-O Bb7 15. Qg4 h5 $1 16. Qh3 Bc5 $13 { [%cal Gh5h4,Gh8h5,Gh5g5,Ge8d8,Ga8b8]We have a very complex and strange position in front of us. The key factor is our king safety, and we are going to play around it: it is pretty safe on e8 at the moment, with our pawn shield! The problem with that is that our rooks cannot be connected, so we will focus on playing around that with moves like ...h4, ...Rh5, or ...Rb8 & ...Ba8. The position is dynamically equal according to Stockfish. } * 

