1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. Qe2 $5 { The modern way. White keeps flexibility on which way is he going to castle, and gains some options in case of 8...b5. } 8... b5 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 $5 { This move has a bad reputation, and Harikhrisna even awards it a '?!' sign in his brilliant course. Stockfish initially dislikes it, but I believe it is a good move, and in practical terms, I would argue that it is even better than 9...dxc6. With 9...dxc6 White can force a repetition quite quickly, and he has several testing tries that force us to remember some lines with great precision. } ( 9... Qxc6 { leads to a strange position in the main line after } 10. e5 { , that the engines assess as White's advantage, but I think the position is a three-results game and quite decent to play with Black. } ) 10. e5 $1 { If White had castled instead of playing 8.Qe2, we would play the intermezzo } 10... b4 $1 { Our idea is to launch this typical Taimanov intermezzo, instead of removing the knight from f6. } ( 10... Bb7 { , with a great position. We do not have that here and that is one of the main points of 8.Qe2. } ) ( 10... Nd5 $146 11. Be4 Bb4 12. Bd2 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Bb7 14. Bb4 $14 { This is solid for Black, but passive, and I do not like to tolerate such a dark-squared bishop. } ) 11. exf6 bxc3 12. fxg7 { The most critical, opening our kingside. } 12... Bxg7 13. b3 { This is the strategical position that engine assesses as an advantage for White. White has a better pawn structure, and the safer king after O-O-O & Kb1 because the threats on the queenside with ...Qa5-Qa3 are not too dangerous because of the Bc1 retort. But we also have our play! The pawn on c3 is still an asset more than a weakness most of the time, and after castling queenside, our king will not be so weak, and we will try to put pressure along the g-file. } 13... Bb7 14. O-O-O d5 { The problem for us, compared to 14.f3, is that castling short is no longer a possibility. So we change our priorities now: pushing in the center and castling queenside. } ( 14... h5 { This was the move seen in practice, but I do not like it because of the maneuver found by Pichot. } 15. f4 O-O-O 16. Qf2 $14 { (1-0 Pichot-Manzone, Buenos Aires 2022) The queen stands very well on f2, supporting Bd4. I prefer to avoid this set-up. } ) 15. f4 $2 { This is no longer possible, because we can immediately push our d5-pawn. } 15... d4 $1 16. Bf2 Qd6 $19 { [%cal Gd6a3][%csl Rc1]White loses the game, once the bishop leaves the h6-c1 diagonal, it can no longer protect the king with Kb1 & Bc1. } * 

