1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. Qe2 $5 { The modern way. White keeps flexibility on which way is he going to castle, and gains some options in case of 8...b5. } 8... b5 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 $5 { This move has a bad reputation, and Harikhrisna even awards it a '?!' sign in his brilliant course. Stockfish initially dislikes it, but I believe it is a good move, and in practical terms, I would argue that it is even better than 9...dxc6. With 9...dxc6 White can force a repetition quite quickly, and he has several testing tries that force us to remember some lines with great precision. } ( 9... Qxc6 { leads to a strange position in the main line after } 10. e5 { , that the engines assess as White's advantage, but I think the position is a three-results game and quite decent to play with Black. } ) 10. e5 $1 { If White had castled instead of playing 8.Qe2, we would play the intermezzo } 10... b4 $1 { Our idea is to launch this typical Taimanov intermezzo, instead of removing the knight from f6. } ( 10... Bb7 { , with a great position. We do not have that here and that is one of the main points of 8.Qe2. } ) ( 10... Nd5 $146 11. Be4 Bb4 12. Bd2 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Bb7 14. Bb4 $14 { This is solid for Black, but passive, and I do not like to tolerate such a dark-squared bishop. } ) 11. exf6 bxc3 12. fxg7 { The most critical, opening our kingside. } 12... Bxg7 13. b3 { This is the strategical position that engine assesses as an advantage for White. White has a better pawn structure, and the safer king after O-O-O & Kb1 because the threats on the queenside with ...Qa5-Qa3 are not too dangerous because of the Bc1 retort. But we also have our play! The pawn on c3 is still an asset more than a weakness most of the time, and after castling queenside, our king will not be so weak, and we will try to put pressure along the g-file. } 13... Bb7 14. O-O-O d5 { The problem for us, compared to 14.f3, is that castling short is no longer a possibility. So we change our priorities now: pushing in the center and castling queenside. } ( 14... h5 { This was the move seen in practice, but I do not like it because of the maneuver found by Pichot. } 15. f4 O-O-O 16. Qf2 $14 { (1-0 Pichot-Manzone, Buenos Aires 2022) The queen stands very well on f2, supporting Bd4. I prefer to avoid this set-up. } ) 15. Kb1 { Just getting the king out of a possible check on a3 looks very logical. } 15... O-O-O { We continue the plan, putting our king to safety. } 16. Qg4 Bf6 17. Bd4 $1 { This is the most dangerous plan. Normally, it would be dangerous for White to exchange bishops with such weak dark squares around their king, but here their queen on d4 will be very active and our queen cannot get to those squares yet, so this is tricky because our pawn on c3 can be weak. } 17... Rhg8 18. Qf4 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 Qc7 $1 { [%cal Ge6e5]It is key to put our center to work before taking on g2. } ( 19... Rxg2 $2 20. Rdg1 Rxg1+ $2 21. Rxg1 { This is the kind of position we have to avoid: our center is completely fixed and all of White's pieces are more active than ours. They have all the time in the world to advance on the kingside or try to play Rg3 & Bf1 and take our pawn. } ) 20. f4 Rxg2 21. Rdg1 Rd2 $1 { [%cal Ga6a5,Gc8b8,Gb7a6]We keep this rook in an advanced position for activity. Now Black has new counterplay due to the pin. Black is fine in this complex position. } 22. Rg7 Kb8 23. Rxh7 a5 $133 { [%cal Gb7a6]} * 

