1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. O-O { The most logical move. } 8... b5 9. Nb3 Be7 $5 { Harikrishna recommends ...Bb7, delaying the development the of the dark- squared bishop, but I think in this particular position it is interesting to delay the position of the c8-bishop. } 10. f4 d6 11. Qf3 O-O { Our idea behind delaying ...Bb7 is that sometimes, when White plays a3, it will be very useful to have ...Rb8 & ...b4 and threaten to take on b4 with the rook, when the bishop will not block our rook if its still on c8. } 12. Rae1 Nb4 $1 { The beauty of our system is that we can play the same plan against practically everything. } 13. Nd4 { White tries to delay a3, but we can react in a concrete way. } 13... e5 $1 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. exf5 Nxd3 { A natural novelty compared to a Smirin game, whose games are worth studying to learn more about these Sicilian middlegames. } 16. cxd3 Rab8 $15 { [%cal Gb5b4,Gc7b7]} * 

