[Black "5) 6.Be3 / 7.Bd3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. O-O { The most logical move. } 8... b5 9. Qe2 { Connecting the rooks makes perfect sense. } 9... Bb7 $1 10. Nb3 Bd6 { A strong move that has never been played. It looks like White has f4, but we have a strong idea in mind. } 11. f4 e5 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Ne7 14. fxe5 Bxe5 15. Bd4 Bxd4+ 16. Nxd4 Qc5 $1 { We could not castle just yet, but with this move we attack White's knight while defending our knight on e7. } 17. Qf2 O-O $13 { [%csl Rd5]White cannot really defend their pawn on d5, and although their pieces are well-placed, White will need to play precisely to prove compensation for the pawn. } * 

