[Black "5) 6.Be3 / 7.Bd3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. O-O { The most logical move. } 8... b5 9. Qe2 { Connecting the rooks makes perfect sense. } 9... Bb7 $1 10. f4 { The move White hopes to play ideally, but we can go for the typical plan in this kind of position: exchange dark square bishops. } 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc5 12. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 13. Kh1 b4 $1 { Expelling White's knight from c3 before castling. } 14. Nb1 O-O $37 { [%cal Gd7d6,Ga6a5]Black has a very easy game. We will put the pawn on d6, and then push the a5-pawn down the board to create weaknesses and counterplay on the queenside. White's attacking potential is limited after exchanging two minor pieces. } * 

