[White "6.Be3 / 7.Bd3: 8.O-O / 9.Nxc6 #1"]
[Black "5) 6.Be3 / 7.Bd3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. O-O { The most logical move. } 8... b5 9. Nxc6 { White cannot play f4 yet because of ...Bc5 ideas, so taking on c6 first makes sense. This territory is no longer so popular for White, it has been quite explored and it turns out Black is fine. } 9... Qxc6 10. Be2 { A computerish idea, known from the 7.a3 line. White repositions their bishop to the main diagonal after ...b5 has been played. } 10... Bd6 $1 { Very strong! If } 11. Qd4 { White's strongest move, covering e5 and preparing to bring a rook to d1. They also stop ...Bc5 ideas, so now f4 is more dangerous. } ( 11. f4 { is answered with } 11... Bc5 ) ( 11. Bf3 { then we show the idea of ...Bd6 with ...Be5!, blocking the e5 push. } ) 11... Bb7 12. Rad1 { This is less precise. } 12... Bb8 $1 { Paradoxically, a good square for the bishop. We allow ...Ba7 in some variations and the battery with ...Qc7. } 13. a4 { This loses strength now that the rook has left a1. } 13... Qc7 $1 14. e5 Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Bxe5 16. axb5 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nd5 $1 { If the rook was on a1, now White could take on a6, but now they do not have time. } 18. Bd4 Nf4 $17 * 

