1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. O-O { The most logical move. } 8... b5 9. Nxc6 { White cannot play f4 yet because of ...Bc5 ideas, so taking on c6 first makes sense. This territory is no longer so popular for White, it has been quite explored and it turns out Black is fine. } 9... Qxc6 10. Be2 { A computerish idea, known from the 7.a3 line. White repositions their bishop to the main diagonal after ...b5 has been played. } 10... Bd6 $1 { Very strong! If } 11. Qd4 { White's strongest move, covering e5 and preparing to bring a rook to d1. They also stop ...Bc5 ideas, so now f4 is more dangerous. } ( 11. f4 { is answered with } 11... Bc5 ) ( 11. Bf3 { then we show the idea of ...Bd6 with ...Be5!, blocking the e5 push. } ) 11... Bb7 12. Rfd1 Be7 $5 { Here I think it is stronger to put the bishop on e7, so that we are better prepared to meet a4 ideas. } ( 12... Bb8 13. a4 Qc7 { Black looks fine, but after the strong } 14. e5 Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Bxe5 16. axb5 $36 { this position looks a little bit unpleasant to me. } ) 13. Bf3 { The critical move, threatening e5. } 13... Qc7 14. e5 { The only critical move, otherwise we can even play ...e5 ourselves, when the bishop on f3 would be very poor, and we would have a decent Najdorf-like position. } 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nh5 { Our knight on the rim is not the best one ever, but we have the better pawn structure and if we manage to break with ...f6, our knight will come back to play and we will take advantage of White's weak king. } 16. a4 b4 17. Ne4 f6 { This is very similar to the main line and Black is also fine. } * 

