1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. O-O { The most logical move. } 8... b5 9. Nxc6 { White cannot play f4 yet because of ...Bc5 ideas, so taking on c6 first makes sense. This territory is no longer so popular for White, it has been quite explored and it turns out Black is fine. } 9... Qxc6 10. a3 Bb7 11. Qe2 { The critical move, } ( 11. f4 Bc5 { would be completely fine for Black as always. } ) 11... Be7 { Harikhrisna prefers 11...Rc8 which is also possible, but I think Grandelius has recently showed an interesting idea here. } 12. f4 h5 $1 { I like a lot this typical move, giving the g4-square to our knight and fighting for the dark squares. } 13. e5 Ng4 14. Bd4 Bc5 $1 15. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 16. Kh1 Qe3 $1 { Our king on e8 will feel a lot safer on e7 after exchanging queens. } 17. Qxe3 Nxe3 $15 { [%csl Gb7,Ge3,Rg2]Black has a very comfortable Taimanov endgame with their strong minor pieces. } * 

