1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 { With this move, White usually plans to castle short and launch a kingside attack with f4 and e5, supporting the e4-pawn with pieces – the bishop on d3 and usually the queen on e2 – rather than with f3. After e5, the bishop will be well-placed on d3, eyeing h7. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... b5 $2 { This is inaccurate for several reasons. } 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qf3 { Very simple and typical of the Taimanov, bringing the queen to g3. Black is worse in this position as practice has showed. } ) 8. O-O { The most logical move. } 8... b5 9. Nxc6 { White cannot play f4 yet because of ...Bc5 ideas, so taking on c6 first makes sense. This territory is no longer so popular for White, it has been quite explored and it turns out Black is fine. } 9... Qxc6 10. a3 Bb7 11. Qe2 { The critical move, } ( 11. f4 Bc5 { would be completely fine for Black as always. } ) 11... Be7 { Harikhrisna prefers 11...Rc8 which is also possible, but I think Grandelius has recently showed an interesting idea here. } 12. f4 h5 $1 { I like a lot this typical move, giving the g4-square to our knight and fighting for the dark squares. } 13. e5 Ng4 14. Be4 Qc4 { A surprising theme that works out well for Black. } ( 14... Qc7 { This is also playable and was the move chosen by Grandelius in the game that attracted my attention to this ...h5 variation. } 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. Bd4 Nh6 $146 17. Ne4 $146 Nf5 $146 18. Bf2 Rc8 19. Rad1 h4 $13 ) 15. Bxb7 Qxe2 16. Nxe2 Rb8 $1 { White cannot save both pieces simultaneously! } 17. Bxa6 $2 Nxe3 18. Rf3 Rb6 $17 { [%cal Ge7c5,Gb6a6]White loses the bishop. } * 

