1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Be2 { This is, of course, possible, but not very critical and can quickly lead to trouble for White if he plays in an excessively simple manner. } 8... Bb7 9. O-O Nf6 10. f4 $6 { Very natural, but not very good! White has problems along the a7-g1 diagonal. } 10... Bc5 $1 11. Qd3 { Sad, but the best that White can do once he has reached this position. } 11... Nxd4 { Black can also opt for a more sophisticated approach with 11...d5, but I prefer to keep things simple and play in the spirit of the Taimanov. } 12. Bxd4 d6 $13 { [%cal Ge8g8,Ga8d8,Gc5d4]We have a fantastic Sicilian position. This would be a typical setup with the bishop on e7, but here we manage to exchange the bishops, reducing White's attacking potential. This plays to our advantage, as we have a very comfortable Sicilian in the long run with our central majority. } * 

