1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { The bishop is not so well-placed on d3. It cannot go to a more threatening square like f3, so it is just a solid developing move. } 9... Bb7 10. O-O { White is playing in a very logical way, but their play is just not very dangerous for us. } 10... Nf6 11. Qe2 { Almost universally played, connecting both rooks. } ( 11. f4 { is as always not very good because of } 11... Bc5 ) 11... Be7 12. f4 h5 $1 { A very typical Taimanov idea that is very strong. We try to get the g4-square for our knight, and if h3 then ...h4 with the idea ...Nh5 & ...g3 is strong. } 13. e5 ( 13. h3 h4 $133 ) 13... Ng4 14. Be4 Qc4 { Everyone has played } ( 14... Qc7 { here, but this move is even stronger and can come as a surprise to the White player. } ) 15. Qxc4 bxc4 16. Bxb7 Rb8 { The point is White cannot save both bishops. } 17. Bd4 Rxb7 $133 { [%cal Gf7f6,Gg4h6,Gh6f5,Ge8f7][%csl Yb2]We have a complex endgame. White has a strong center that we will try to break, while putting some pressure on the queenside. } * 

