1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { The bishop is not so well-placed on d3. It cannot go to a more threatening square like f3, so it is just a solid developing move. } 9... Bb7 10. Qd2 $5 { This position can also be reached from the 9... Qxc6 9.Qd2 Bb7 10.Bd3 move order. } 10... b4 $5 { There are alternatives, but this is the most concrete move and it has been mentioned so much in other sources. We want to develop our f8-bishop with tempo. } 11. Ne2 { This looks strange but it is actually a tricky try for an advantage. } 11... Nf6 12. f3 bxa3 13. bxa3 Qc7 $1 ( 13... Qc5 { looks much more natural, but it is better to avoid it due to Qb4 ideas. } ) ( 13... Bc5 14. Bxc5 Qxc5 15. Qb4 $14 { White has the more pleasant position. } ) 14. Qc3 Qxc3+ 15. Nxc3 Bc6 $10 { [%cal Gf8d6,Ge8e7,Gh8b8]The endgame is completely equal: we have the slightly better pawn structure, but White is more active, so it is around equal. } * 

