1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { The bishop is not so well-placed on d3. It cannot go to a more threatening square like f3, so it is just a solid developing move. } 9... Bb7 10. Qd2 $5 { This position can also be reached from the 9... Qxc6 9.Qd2 Bb7 10.Bd3 move order. } 10... b4 $5 { There are alternatives, but this is the most concrete move and it has been mentioned so much in other sources. We want to develop our f8-bishop with tempo. } 11. axb4 Bxb4 12. O-O Nf6 13. f3 a5 $1 { Now that f3 has been played, our bishop does not have a bright future on b7, so we immediately try to exchange it. } 14. Qf2 Ba6 $10 { ½-½ Bragesjoe-Wegelin, 2023 Black was completely fine in this correspondence game. } * 

