1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. h4 $5 { This is a tricky sideline that for example, was not mentioned by Harikhrisna in their excellent course. It is a very computerish idea: White just wants to gain space and more space on the kingside. } 9... Nf6 $1 { I think it's important to take the bull by the horns and go for the most forced solution. The position after the standard 8...Bb7 doesn't look pleasant at all for Black. } ( 9... Bb7 { I would like to show a sample line where Black plays normally but ends up much worse. } 10. h5 Rc8 11. Bd4 { Now ...h6 seems unpleasant. } 11... h6 12. Rh3 { We see another point of 9.h4. I wouldn't want to be in Black's shoes here—the position looks terribly dangerous, and White's plan is very straightforward: put the rook on g3, move the queen, castle long, and attack! } ) 10. e5 { This allows us to exchange knights and is not very dangerous. } 10... Ne4 11. Nxe4 Qxe4 { Now we threaten to take on e5. } 12. Qd4 Bb7 13. c3 Qxd4 14. cxd4 Be7 $10 { [%cal Gf7f5]This is fine for Black too, and even more comfortable looking at the range of the b7-bishop. } * 

