[Site "6.Be3 / 7.a3: 8.Nxc6 / 9.h4 #5"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.Be3 / 7.a3: 8.Nxc6 / 9.h4 #5"]
[Black "6) 6.Be3 / 7.a3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. h4 $5 { This is a tricky sideline that for example, was not mentioned by Harikhrisna in their excellent course. It is a very computerish idea: White just wants to gain space and more space on the kingside. } 9... Nf6 $1 { I think it's important to take the bull by the horns and go for the most forced solution. The position after the standard 8...Bb7 doesn't look pleasant at all for Black. } ( 9... Bb7 { I would like to show a sample line where Black plays normally but ends up much worse. } 10. h5 Rc8 11. Bd4 { Now ...h6 seems unpleasant. } 11... h6 12. Rh3 { We see another point of 9.h4. I wouldn't want to be in Black's shoes here—the position looks terribly dangerous, and White's plan is very straightforward: put the rook on g3, move the queen, castle long, and attack! } ) 10. h5 $5 { The most dangerous move, sacrificing the pawn on e4 but gaining even more space. } 10... Nxe4 $1 { We accept the challenge! } ( 10... h6 11. e5 Ne4 $146 12. Qf3 Bb7 13. Nxe4 $146 Qxe4 14. Rh3 $14 { This kind of endgame was completely fine for Black with the pawn on h4, but now we have a weakness on g7, making it a bit unpleasant. } ) 11. Nxe4 Qxe4 12. Be2 Rb8 { We need to avoid Bf3, winning the rook. } 13. h6 { This is also logical, trying to open the kingside, but it is not very good. } 13... Bb7 { We can actually ignore White, putting more pressure on the g2-pawn. } 14. Bf3 Qe5 15. Bxb7 Rxb7 16. Qd4 $2 { This is not threatening, because we can sidestep the pin. } 16... Qxd4 17. Bxd4 Rg8 $17 * 

