1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Qd4 { A logical alternative, now that the knight on c6 is gone the d4-square looks very good for the queen, and also stops ...b4 ideas. But it all comes for a price: the queen is also more exposed on d4. } 9... Bb7 10. O-O-O Nf6 $1 11. f3 Rc8 { Threatening ...Bxa3 and preparing the typical resource ...Bc5. } 12. Rd2 $5 { A little trap by the White player. } 12... Bc5 $1 ( 12... Bxa3 13. Nxb5 $146 { is White's idea. } ) 13. Qxc5 Qxc5 14. Bxc5 Rxc5 $10 { As many other times in the Taimanov, the endgame is very comfortable for Black. We can equalize with ...d5, but it is also possible to play a dark- squared strategy with ...Ke7, ...d6, ...g5, & ...Nd7, keeping more tension. Either way, Black is fine. } * 

