1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. Qd4 { This transposes to 9.Qd4. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } * 

