1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. Qd2 { This hybrid system, where White does not leave their intentions clear, has been tried by strong players, Firoujza being the most notable. } 10... b4 $5 ( 10... Bd6 $2 11. O-O-O Be5 12. Bd4 $16 { This is very good for White, so we cannot play the same set-up we play against short castle systems. } ) ( 10... Qd6 $2 { This original move was played successfully by Fedorchuk. Taimanov endgames are usually very fine for Black, but in this particular case White should be able to get a slight pull with precise play, although it is perfectly playable. } ) 11. axb4 Bxb4 12. Qd4 $5 { This leads to forced play that is fine for Black. } 12... Qxe4 $1 13. Qxg7 Qxg2 $1 14. Qxh8 Qxh1+ 15. Kd2 { Fancy looking, but actually just a draw by repetition. } 15... Qxa1 16. Qxg8+ Ke7 17. Qg5+ Ke8 18. Qg8+ $10 Ke7 * 

