1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. Qd2 { This hybrid system, where White does not leave their intentions clear, has been tried by strong players, Firoujza being the most notable. } 10... b4 $5 ( 10... Bd6 $2 11. O-O-O Be5 12. Bd4 $16 { This is very good for White, so we cannot play the same set-up we play against short castle systems. } ) ( 10... Qd6 $2 { This original move was played successfully by Fedorchuk. Taimanov endgames are usually very fine for Black, but in this particular case White should be able to get a slight pull with precise play, although it is perfectly playable. } ) 11. axb4 Bxb4 12. f3 Nf6 13. Qd4 a5 $1 14. Kf2 ( 14. e5 { is always answered with } 14... Nd5 $146 { , and now we have a new idea: ...Ba6, exchanging our bad bishop. } ) 14... O-O 15. e5 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nd5 17. Bd2 Ne7 $133 { [%cal Ge7f5]I like this regrouping move. Our next moves are ...Nf5 and ...Bc6, trying to get ...a4 in. White is the one who has to act quick in this endgame to not become worse in this position in my opinion. } * 

