1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Bd6 $5 { This move is not very popular over the board (OTB), but it has been the choice of several strong correspondence players. In my opinion, it is a clean equalizer and fits the needs of the position perfectly: we would love to bring the bishop to e5. } 11. Qd3 Nf6 ( 11... Ne7 $146 { is also possible, but we go for this move for consistency. } ) 12. Rad1 Be5 { This is the advantage compared to 11.Qd4 for Black: we can use the e5-square for the bishop. } ( 12... Bb8 13. f4 O-O 14. Bf3 $16 ) 13. Bd4 { White immediately exchanges it. } 13... Bxd4 14. Qxd4 O-O $133 { [%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Gc6c5]Black does not have problems in this typical Sicilian middlegame. } * 

