1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Bd6 $5 { This move is not very popular over the board (OTB), but it has been the choice of several strong correspondence players. In my opinion, it is a clean equalizer and fits the needs of the position perfectly: we would love to bring the bishop to e5. } 11. f4 { This is natural but not very dangerous, because it allows us to exchange bishops on c5. } 11... Ne7 12. Bf3 Bc5 13. Qd2 Bxe3+ $1 ( 13... d6 14. Rad1 { Up until this point, we were following a game by Lazavic, where he played ...d6. However, it's possible to leave the pawn on d7 and use the c6-square as a safe and defended outpost for the bishop. For example: } ) 14. Qxe3 Rc8 { [%cal Gc6c5]} 15. Kh1 Qc5 16. Qd2 Rc7 $13 { [%cal Ge8g8]Black has an easy Sicilian middlegame. } * 

