1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Bd6 $5 { This move is not very popular over the board (OTB), but it has been the choice of several strong correspondence players. In my opinion, it is a clean equalizer and fits the needs of the position perfectly: we would love to bring the bishop to e5. } 11. Qd4 { The most dangerous idea—centralizing the queen and denying us the e5-square for the bishop. } 11... Nf6 12. Rad1 { This is not so critical in my opinion, it is important for White to have the resource a4 with the rook on a1. } 12... Bb8 $1 { This is slightly better than ...Bc7 because it allows ...Ba7, exchanging dark- squared bishops in some variations. } 13. Bg5 Qc7 $1 { Forcing White to debilitate their position. } 14. g3 Ba7 15. Qd3 h6 { The exchange on f6 is of course beneficial for us. } 16. Bf4 e5 $1 { 16...Qc6 is also possible, but I like this Najdorf-like solution that has been chosen by 2 strong correspondence players. } 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. Qxe3 O-O $133 { [%cal Gf8d8,Gb7c6,Ga8b8]Black has some weak squares on the d-file, but White cannot effectively take advantage of them. We will defend our pawn with ...Bc6, and if a rook goes to d6, we can always play ...Ne8 to expel it. Meanwhile, we can try to generate counterplay on the queenside with ...Bc6, ...Rb8, ...a5, and ...b4. } * 

