1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Bd6 $5 { This move is not very popular over the board (OTB), but it has been the choice of several strong correspondence players. In my opinion, it is a clean equalizer and fits the needs of the position perfectly: we would love to bring the bishop to e5. } 11. Qd4 { The most dangerous idea—centralizing the queen and denying us the e5-square for the bishop. } 11... Nf6 12. Rfd1 Bb8 $1 { We still go for the same retreat. ...Qc7 can be useful and ...Ba7 is always a possibility. } 13. a4 { The critical test of our idea, opening the position immediately. Unfortunately for us, } 13... Qc7 $1 { We win an important tempo by threatening mate. } ( 13... Ba7 $2 { is not working because of the intermezzo } 14. axb5 ) 14. e5 $1 { White plays in an active and forced way. } 14... Qxe5 15. Qxe5 { The next few moves are more or less forced. } 15... Bxe5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8+ Bxa8 18. Bc5 { This was also tried OTB, and although it looks interesting, it should not be too dangerous. I like Stockfish improvement over the game. } 18... b4 ( 18... Bxc3 ) 19. Bxb4 Bc6 20. Ra1 Kd8 $10 { [%cal Gd8c7,Gg7g5,Gh7h5,Gh8b8]At first glance, Black's position looks cramped, but Ra7 can always be hit with ...Bd4 and White cannot really do anything to improve their position. Once the king comes to c7, we can try to generate play on the kingside. } * 

