1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. a3 { A modern, high-class waiting move. White stops ...Bb4 and discourages ...b4, as this would give them the semi-open b-file after axb4. In the meantime, they keep us guessing regarding their setup, although O-O-O is pretty much off the table. } 7... b5 8. Nxc6 { This is the only critical move. Once the bishop comes to b7, we can always recapture with the bishop, and our pieces will be well-coordinated. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Bd6 $5 { This move is not very popular over the board (OTB), but it has been the choice of several strong correspondence players. In my opinion, it is a clean equalizer and fits the needs of the position perfectly: we would love to bring the bishop to e5. } 11. Qd4 { The most dangerous idea—centralizing the queen and denying us the e5-square for the bishop. } 11... Nf6 12. Rfd1 Bb8 $1 { We still go for the same retreat. ...Qc7 can be useful and ...Ba7 is always a possibility. } 13. a4 { The critical test of our idea, opening the position immediately. Unfortunately for us, } 13... Qc7 $1 { We win an important tempo by threatening mate. } ( 13... Ba7 $2 { is not working because of the intermezzo } 14. axb5 ) 14. e5 $1 { White plays in an active and forced way. } 14... Qxe5 15. Qxe5 { The next few moves are more or less forced. } 15... Bxe5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8+ Bxa8 18. Nxb5 { This is the move preferred by correspondence players. } 18... O-O 19. c3 { Passive play is not dangerous for us. } 19... Nd5 20. Bc5 Rc8 21. Ba3 Nb6 $10 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gf7f5,Gg8f7]White's queenside is under control, and we do not have any problems. Our plan should be to generate play on the kingside and improve our king. } * 

