[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Qg3 $5 { This is the most solid line for White, entering an endgame where he has some pressure thanks to the semi-open h-file and active pieces. But as we will see, Black has no issues in the endgame if he understands the typical plans and correct piece placement. } 8... Qxg3 9. hxg3 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bb7 11. f3 { The strongest move, because we were threatening b4 taking the pawn on e4. 11.O-O-O would actually transpose to the imprecise 8.O-O-O (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 11... Ne7 12. g4 { A subtle move order that has never been tried in practice. It is similar in concept to 12.Bf2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). White gains some flexibility delaying O-O-O because White can sometimes generate initiative on the queenside. } 12... Nc6 13. Bf2 Bb4 { We play in the same way we play against the 12.O-O-O (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) main line. } 14. g5 { Gaining space on the kingside looks logical. Now, I like the idea of a zig-zag maneuver! } 14... Be7 $1 15. Be3 f6 $1 { I like this move, liberating our kingside. g6 appears threatening but poses no real danger. } 16. g6 $6 h6 $1 { [%cal Gc6e5,Ge5g6]The pawn on g6 is going to fall. } * 

