1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Qg3 $5 { This is the most solid line for White, entering an endgame where he has some pressure thanks to the semi-open h-file and active pieces. But as we will see, Black has no issues in the endgame if he understands the typical plans and correct piece placement. } 8... Qxg3 9. hxg3 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bb7 11. f3 { The strongest move, because we were threatening b4 taking the pawn on e4. 11.O-O-O would actually transpose to the imprecise 8.O-O-O (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 11... Ne7 12. a4 { This is also a possible idea, although a little bit non-standard. } 12... b4 13. Nd1 f5 $1 { Aiming to weaken White's light squares in the center. } 14. Nf2 { The strongest move. } 14... fxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 { It's a bit difficult to part with such a strong bishop, but the knight on e4 is simply too powerful! We will also get some dark squares in the center and easy development. } 16. fxe4 Nc6 17. Bf2 Bd6 $1 18. O-O-O Ke7 { [%cal Gh7h6]Black has a decent endgame. After placing the pawn on h6, we will play ...Rhf8 and ...Ne5, establishing a solid central position. } * 

