1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Qg3 $5 { This is the most solid line for White, entering an endgame where he has some pressure thanks to the semi-open h-file and active pieces. But as we will see, Black has no issues in the endgame if he understands the typical plans and correct piece placement. } 8... Qxg3 9. hxg3 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bb7 11. f3 { The strongest move, because we were threatening b4 taking the pawn on e4. 11.O-O-O would actually transpose to the imprecise 8.O-O-O (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 11... Ne7 12. O-O-O Nc6 13. Be3 Bb4 14. a4 $5 { This idea is also a potential idea, even involving a pawn sacrifice. } 14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 bxa4 16. g4 f6 $133 { [%cal Gc6e5,Ga8c8,Ge8e7]It makes sense to put the pawn on f6 before initiating the counterplay on the queenside with moves like ...Ne5, ...Bc6, ...Rc8. It is not so easy for White to recover the pawn on a4, because we can always move the knight and play ...Bc6 to defend it, but the bishop pair compensates it so the position is around equal. } * 

