1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Qg3 $5 { This is the most solid line for White, entering an endgame where he has some pressure thanks to the semi-open h-file and active pieces. But as we will see, Black has no issues in the endgame if he understands the typical plans and correct piece placement. } 8... Qxg3 9. hxg3 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Bb7 11. f3 { The strongest move, because we were threatening b4 taking the pawn on e4. 11.O-O-O would actually transpose to the imprecise 8.O-O-O (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 11... Ne7 12. O-O-O Nc6 13. Be3 Bb4 14. Ne2 { The most solid move, avoiding the possible weakness on c3. } 14... f6 $1 { A good stabilizing move, giving us control of the e5 and g5-squares. Also, the king can go to f7 in some variations. } 15. g4 Ne5 { This is a good square for the knight. It can go both to the c4-square, and to f7 if needed in the defense of the kingside. } 16. Kb1 Be7 $5 { A decent move, stopping g5. } 17. b3 { White stops ...Nc4. } 17... Rc8 18. Bd4 Bd6 $133 { [%cal Ge8e7]Another move that I like. Black could not play ...Kf7 connecting the rooks because of Bxe5 & Rxd7, but with ...Bd6 they are able to connect the rooks after ...Ke7. The endgame is tense and around equal. } * 

