1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. O-O-O { This is a move we are very happy to see; Black equalizes easily and, in most cases, can even play for the initiative. It looks very natural, but White cannot play Qg3 without losing the e4-pawn now, making it imprecise. } 8... Bb7 9. Bd3 $6 { This looks very natural, but Black's initiative grows to gigantic proportions. White has developed their pieces, but to poor squares! Both the light-squared bishop and the queen are quite clumsy. } 9... Ne5 $1 { It is time for energetic play. } 10. Qe2 Nxd3+ 11. Qxd3 b4 12. Na4 Nf6 $1 13. f3 d5 $17 { [%csl Ra4,Gb7,Re4,Gf8]The nail in the coffin for White. White cannot maintain their center, and they cannot punish us for having the king on e8, so their position doesn't make much sense. } * 

