1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. O-O-O { This is a move we are very happy to see; Black equalizes easily and, in most cases, can even play for the initiative. It looks very natural, but White cannot play Qg3 without losing the e4-pawn now, making it imprecise. } 8... Bb7 9. Qg3 { The most natural idea. } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nxd4 $1 { Our point is that the pawn on e4 is in trouble. } 11. Bxd4 { The best move, sacrificing the e4-pawn for initiative. } 11... b4 $1 12. Na4 Bxe4 13. Nb6 Rd8 $1 ( 13... Rb8 $2 { This is not highly recommended! } 14. Nxd7 $146 ) 14. f3 Bb7 $13 { [%csl Ra2,Rb2,Gb4,Rc2]White still needs to prove compensation for the pawn. Even if they manage to get back the a6-pawn, like in the model game that reached this position, we still have a great position because our pawn on b4 controls White's majority on the queenside. } * 

