[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Nxc6 { This is one of the critical moves. White takes on c6 before we play ...Bb7, and typically aims to capitalize on their development advantage. } 8... Qxc6 9. a3 { This is less natural in my opinion. White stops the ...b4 threat manually, instead of just playing Bd3 defending the c2-pawn. This gives us a pawn hook on the queenside to obtain counterplay. } 9... b4 10. axb4 Bxb4 { Thanks to ...b4, we develop the bishop with tempo. } 11. Bd4 f6 $1 { [%cal Ge6e5,Rb4c3]Now ...e5 is a threat. } 12. O-O-O $5 { Note that } ( 12. Qg3 { at the very least least hangs the pawn on e4. O-O-O is the most critical move, the king might be weak on c1 in the long run, but for now, our king is still on e8, so White wants to exploit their development advantage. } ) 12... Ne7 { Just developing pieces. } ( 12... e5 $2 { This turns out badly for us after the intermezzo } 13. Nd5 $146 ) 13. e5 { This is not problematic. } 13... Qxf3 14. gxf3 fxe5 15. Bxe5 O-O $13 { [%cal Ge7g6]Black has safely castled and has the better pawn structure, so we are not worse at all. } * 

