1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Nxc6 { This is one of the critical moves. White takes on c6 before we play ...Bb7, and typically aims to capitalize on their development advantage. } 8... Qxc6 9. a3 { This is less natural in my opinion. White stops the ...b4 threat manually, instead of just playing Bd3 defending the c2-pawn. This gives us a pawn hook on the queenside to obtain counterplay. } 9... b4 10. axb4 Bxb4 { Thanks to ...b4, we develop the bishop with tempo. } 11. Bd3 $5 { An interesting idea by Stockifsh, giving up a pawn but completing development. } 11... Bxc3+ $1 { It's always risky to take such a pawn, but we are already behind in development, so let's make it worthwhile! } 12. bxc3 Qxc3+ 13. Ke2 Ne7 { White has a big lead in development, but we have everything protected and it is not easy to get anything in return. Play can follow: } 14. Rhb1 O-O 15. e5 { White tries to launch a kingside attack. } 15... Nc6 $1 16. Qe4 g6 17. f4 a5 $13 { [%cal Gc8a6]We welcome any exchange here. White has compensation but we are still a pawn up! } * 

