1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Nxc6 { This is one of the critical moves. White takes on c6 before we play ...Bb7, and typically aims to capitalize on their development advantage. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { White defends the c2-pawn. We were threatening ...b4, so it makes sense. } 9... Ba3 $5 { It is usually not a good idea to force an early crisis when we are down on development, but I think it is concretely justified in this position. White needs to respond to the ...Bxb2 threat, and we have several moves to consider. } 10. Bc1 { The most solid move, although not very threatening. Now we have achieved our main goal, avoiding O-O-O and an aggressive scheme by White, so we are quite OK in general. } 10... Bb7 11. Qg3 { The pawn on g7 is always weak for us in these variations. } 11... Be7 $1 { We have to retreat, but not all the way to f8! The point is } 12. O-O ( 12. Qxg7 Bf6 { wins material for us. } ) 12... b4 $1 { Destabilizing White's knight. } 13. Nd1 Nf6 $1 { Leading to big complications that are fine for us. } 14. e5 { The critical move. } 14... Ne4 $1 { The most fun, although } ( 14... Nh5 $146 { is also possible. } ) 15. Qxg7 O-O-O $1 { We do not mind giving up more material, because it will open more lines against White's king. } 16. Qxf7 $4 Ng5 $19 { [%cal Gc6g2,Gg5f7]There is no way to defend against ...Qxg2 mate. We are winning. } * 

