1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Nxc6 { This is one of the critical moves. White takes on c6 before we play ...Bb7, and typically aims to capitalize on their development advantage. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { White defends the c2-pawn. We were threatening ...b4, so it makes sense. } 9... Ba3 $5 { It is usually not a good idea to force an early crisis when we are down on development, but I think it is concretely justified in this position. White needs to respond to the ...Bxb2 threat, and we have several moves to consider. } 10. Bc1 { The most solid move, although not very threatening. Now we have achieved our main goal, avoiding O-O-O and an aggressive scheme by White, so we are quite OK in general. } 10... Bb7 11. Qg3 { The pawn on g7 is always weak for us in these variations. } 11... Be7 $1 { We have to retreat, but not all the way to f8! The point is } 12. a4 { The move that Stockifsh likes. I do not think it can be very threatening, ...b4 was already in our plans! } ( 12. Qxg7 Bf6 { wins material for us. } ) 12... b4 13. Ne2 Nf6 14. f3 O-O 15. Bh6 Ne8 { [%cal Ge7c5,Gd7d6]The simplest. Black is conceptually fine with all their pieces developed and the kingside well protected, so we do not need to enter the complications that arise after 15...Nh5. Next, ...Bc5 is in the cards, and after an upcoming ...Kh8, then we will be able to activate the knight and enjoy a complex Sicilian middlegame. } * 

