1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Nxc6 { This is one of the critical moves. White takes on c6 before we play ...Bb7, and typically aims to capitalize on their development advantage. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { White defends the c2-pawn. We were threatening ...b4, so it makes sense. } 9... Ba3 $5 { It is usually not a good idea to force an early crisis when we are down on development, but I think it is concretely justified in this position. White needs to respond to the ...Bxb2 threat, and we have several moves to consider. } 10. Na4 { This move has never been played but it is quite an interesting idea. It is White's most solid move, going after our bishop pair. } 10... Be7 11. Nb6 Rb8 12. Nxc8 Rxc8 { White has gained the bishop pair, but their bishop pair is not very active right now. They will try to open the position on the queenside with c4 or a4. This should not be too dangerous if we know what we are doing and slowly extinguish White's initiative, but it can be unpleasant to defend, so be careful! } 13. O-O Nf6 14. a4 bxa4 15. e5 { White wants to exchange our queen so that the a4-pawn looses support, but it is not really problematic. } 15... Qxf3 16. gxf3 Nd5 17. Rxa4 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Rc5 19. f4 a5 20. Rfa1 Bd8 $13 { Black manages to defend everything and the position is very probably going to end in a draw due to the presence of the opposite-colored bishops. } * 

