the knight on h5! White should improve the knight on d1 if they want to continue to fight for the initiative, and they can do so while exchanging light-squared bishops by including Be4. } 16. Be4 { The most critcal option probably. The bishop on b7 is a very good piece so it makes sense to exchange it. } 16... Qc7 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. g4 $1 { Forcing our knight to go to a very sad square. } 18... Ng7 19. Nf2 d6 $1 { I think we need to break White's center, the pawn on e5 let White maneuver freely and give their knight strong advanced positions on f6 and d6. } 20. exd6 Bxd6 21. Ne4 { White keeps improving their pieces with tempo. } 21... Be7 22. Bd4 { The problem is that White gets some initiative playing very concretely. This forces us to be very precise, but we will also have our chances after defending correctly! } 22... O-O 23. Nf6+ $2 { This is tempting, getting control of the dark squares, but not very good. } 23... Bxf6 24. Bxf6 Ne8 $1 25. Bd4 f6 $1 { [%cal Ge6e5,Ge8d6,Ge8g7,Gg7e6]We cover all of our holes, and after we push ...e5 it is White who will be left with some weaknesses that are easier to take advantage of with a knight rather than a bishop. } * 

