1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qf3 { White's queen is coming to g3 – either immediately to invite a queen trade and head for an endgame ( } 7... b5 $5 ( 7... b5 $2 8. Qg3 $2 { ), or later, after luring our queen to c6 with 7. Qf3 7...b5 8.Nxc6 Qxc6 9.Bd3 Ba3 10.Nd1 Bb4+ 11.c3 Be7 12.Qg3 , targeting our soft spot on g7. } ) 8. Nxc6 { This is one of the critical moves. White takes on c6 before we play ...Bb7, and typically aims to capitalize on their development advantage. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { White defends the c2-pawn. We were threatening ...b4, so it makes sense. } 9... Ba3 $5 { It is usually not a good idea to force an early crisis when we are down on development, but I think it is concretely justified in this position. White needs to respond to the ...Bxb2 threat, and we have several moves to consider. } 10. Nd1 { The most critical response, asking us what our idea was when initiating this maneuver. } 10... Bb4+ $1 { We first force c3, so that White's knight cannot be easily improved from d1 to c3 again. } 11. c3 Be7 12. Qg3 $1 { White understands that g7 is a weak square and plays this unpleasant move. Something like } 12... Nf6 { This may seem like a blunder, but it's a key novelty that revitalizes this ...b5 line! } ( 12... g6 $2 13. Bd4 f6 14. O-O { is of course very passive and sad for Black, but we have some tactical resources! } ) 13. e5 { The critical move, asking where does our knight go to. } 13... Nh5 $1 14. Qh3 $1 { White is not fooled by appearances and plays the strongest move. The queen is better placed on h3, making contact with the h7-square later in the game in some key variations, and also allowing the pawn on g2 to advance. } 14... Bb7 15. f3 g6 { Now we really needed to defend the knight on h5! White should improve the knight on d1 if they want to continue to fight for the initiative, and they can do so while exchanging light-squared bishops by including Be4. } 16. Be4 { The most critcal option probably. The bishop on b7 is a very good piece so it makes sense to exchange it. } 16... Qc7 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. g4 $1 { Forcing our knight to go to a very sad square. } 18... Ng7 19. Nf2 d6 $1 { I think we need to break White's center, the pawn on e5 let White maneuver freely and give their knight strong advanced positions on f6 and d6. } 20. exd6 Bxd6 21. Ne4 { White keeps improving their pieces with tempo. } 21... Be7 22. Bd4 { The problem is that White gets some initiative playing very concretely. This forces us to be very precise, but we will also have our chances after defending correctly! } 22... O-O 23. Qh6 $1 { White keeps playing in the most concrete way possible. } 23... Ne8 24. g5 $5 { This looks like a very logical move. But we have a splendid resource that gives us a great game. } 24... Rd8 $1 25. h4 Rxd4 $3 { The big point! The bishop on d4 is a very good piece and our knight could not be improved, but now it is going to reach some great squares from where it can attack White's weakneses. } 26. cxd4 Ng7 27. Nf6+ { Only move, otherwise we trap White's queen. } 27... Bxf6 28. gxf6 Nh5 $1 { [%cal Gb7f3]} 29. Qe3 Qd5 $13 { There is no rush to recover the f6-pawn. Stockfish calls this 0.00, confirming that Black's compensation is more than sufficient with White's broken pawn structure and weak king. In a practical game I think it is much more fun to play with Black! We will try to keep a rook over the board, and that should give us always perennial counterplay. } * 

