the knight on h5! White should improve the knight on d1 if they want to continue to fight for the initiative, and they can do so while exchanging light-squared bishops by including Be4. } 16. Be4 { The most critcal option probably. The bishop on b7 is a very good piece so it makes sense to exchange it. } 16... Qc7 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. g4 $1 { Forcing our knight to go to a very sad square. } 18... Ng7 19. Nf2 d6 $1 { I think we need to break White's center, the pawn on e5 let White maneuver freely and give their knight strong advanced positions on f6 and d6. } 20. exd6 Bxd6 21. Ne4 { White keeps improving their pieces with tempo. } 21... Be7 22. Bd4 { The problem is that White gets some initiative playing very concretely. This forces us to be very precise, but we will also have our chances after defending correctly! } 22... O-O 23. Qh6 $1 { White keeps playing in the most concrete way possible. } 23... Ne8 24. O-O-O { Natural and testing, just bringing the king to the kingside first before initiating any attack. } 24... f5 $1 { A key move, liberating our position and allowing our rook to contribute to the defense of the kingside. } 25. gxf5 Rxf5 26. Rhg1 $1 { White keeps playing very precisely. Now our weak point is g6, so their intentions are not so well hidden. They want to sacrifice on g6 and mate us! } 26... e5 $1 { Blocking the bishop's contact with the g7-square. } 27. Rxg6+ $1 { Continuing the forced line. } 27... hxg6 28. Qxg6+ Ng7 29. Rg1 { Now White threatens both Qxg7# and Qxf5, and } 29... Bg5+ $1 ( 29... Rf7 $2 30. Bxe5 { just loses. But we have a strong defensive resource that allows our queen to participate in the defense. } ) 30. Rxg5 Qf7 $1 31. Qc6 Rd8 $1 { Precise until the end! The rook on d8 sometimes cuts off some escape routes of White's king on c1. } 32. Qb6 $1 Rf8 $13 { The position is still very complex, but we have managed to parry White's attack and I think it is a good place to stop. We are an exchange up, and although the machine finds some very strange ways (for example, in some lines playing b3, Kb2 & Ka3 to safely put the king on a3!) to continue the game, in a practical game Black does not have worse chances. } * 

