1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. Qd2 { Not very good: in this system, it usually makes more sense to place the queen on f3. The queen is more exposed to ...Bb4 & ...Nf6 ideas here, and compared to the usual English Attack, not only is the pawn on e4 hanging, but so is the one on e4. } 8... Ne5 $5 { I like to put immediate pressure on White's position. } 9. f3 { This move is also quite logical. } 9... b5 $1 10. h4 Bb7 11. Be2 d5 $1 { No game has reached this position yet, but I wanted to show this instructive idea showed by the engine. We can play very actively when White's king is still on e1. } 12. exd5 Nf6 $1 13. dxe6 O-O-O $1 { [%cal Gf8c5]White is taking all of our pawns, but our pieces are tremendously active and exude a lot of energy. } 14. exf7 Bc5 $133 { [%cal Ge5f3]White has to be careful with tactics on f3. } * 

