1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. Rg1 $5 { A tricky attempt. We saw that 8.h4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) did not really help White to push g5, so it makes sense to find alternatives. In general, facing this move implies a great probability that our opponent is well-prepared. } 8... Nf6 { Again, the main idea of 7...h6 is to be able to develop the knight to f6 without too much problem. } ( 8... b5 { is also playable, but I trust this variation more. } ) 9. h4 { This leads to a forced line where Black is not worse at all and White has several ways of going wrong, so this is a move that we want to see. } 9... Bb4 10. f3 Ne5 11. Qd2 d5 $1 { We continue playing in the most active way possible while White's king still is on e1. } 12. g5 { White has to also play actively! } 12... hxg5 13. hxg5 Nfd7 14. exd5 $6 Nb6 $1 { A very strong move. We are not so preocupied with material but with developing active play. } 15. dxe6 Nbc4 $1 16. Bxc4 Nxc4 17. Qc1 Nxb2 $1 { Note that this trick works even if White puts the queen on c1. } * 

