1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. Rg1 $5 { A tricky attempt. We saw that 8.h4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) did not really help White to push g5, so it makes sense to find alternatives. In general, facing this move implies a great probability that our opponent is well-prepared. } 8... Nf6 { Again, the main idea of 7...h6 is to be able to develop the knight to f6 without too much problem. } ( 8... b5 { is also playable, but I trust this variation more. } ) 9. Nxc6 $1 { This is the critical move. As we saw in the 8.h4 line, ...Ne5 is a very important part of our counterplay, so this move makes a lot of sense. } 9... bxc6 ( 9... Qxc6 $2 { This was our move with 8.h4, but here the g4-pawn is defended, and White can immediately centralize their queen with } 10. Qd4 $16 { avoiding any ...Bb4 or ...Ba3 counterplay, nonsense, shenanigans, and tomfoolery. } ) 10. Qf3 { The critical move, preparing O-O-O. } 10... d5 11. O-O-O Bb4 { Other moves have been tried, but I find this the most reliable one, forcing matters on the center. } 12. Bd2 $5 { Another suggestion by the engine, although I think that it is more dificult to face this from an unprepared opponent. White does not release tension on the center. } 12... d4 13. Nb1 $1 { The strongest move. The knight has a very good square on c4. } 13... Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 c5 { We protect our center and intend to play ...Bb7 next. White now has two approaches: pushing g5 immediately or preparing it with h4. } 15. h4 Nd7 16. g5 hxg5 17. hxg5 g6 $1 { We need to stop g6; this move would imply destruction of our position. } 18. Bc4 $1 { The best move, although a little bit counterintuitive because the knight looks more natural on c4. White develops as quick as possible, preparing Rh1 and making contact with our e6-pawn. } 18... Rh4 $1 { Trying to get a grip on the dark squares and prophylaxis against Rh1. } 19. Rh1 Qf4 20. Qxf4 Rxf4 21. Rh8+ Ke7 { [%cal Ga6a5,Gc8b7]White's initiative is temporary, and after ...a5 & ...Bb7 we will enjoy a good endgame. } * 

