1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. Rg1 $5 { A tricky attempt. We saw that 8.h4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) did not really help White to push g5, so it makes sense to find alternatives. In general, facing this move implies a great probability that our opponent is well-prepared. } 8... Nf6 { Again, the main idea of 7...h6 is to be able to develop the knight to f6 without too much problem. } ( 8... b5 { is also playable, but I trust this variation more. } ) 9. Nxc6 $1 { This is the critical move. As we saw in the 8.h4 line, ...Ne5 is a very important part of our counterplay, so this move makes a lot of sense. } 9... bxc6 ( 9... Qxc6 $2 { This was our move with 8.h4, but here the g4-pawn is defended, and White can immediately centralize their queen with } 10. Qd4 $16 { avoiding any ...Bb4 or ...Ba3 counterplay, nonsense, shenanigans, and tomfoolery. } ) 10. Qf3 { The critical move, preparing O-O-O. } 10... d5 11. O-O-O Bb4 { Other moves have been tried, but I find this the most reliable one, forcing matters on the center. } 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Bd4 Bb7 $1 { A strong pawn sacrifice. Finishing development is more important than the pawn on f6. Also, after giving away their dark-squared bishop, White's firepower gets reduced significantly. } 14. g5 $1 hxg5 15. Rxg5 Qxh2 16. Kb1 $5 { Getting out of ...Qh6+ ideas, or ...Bd6 like in the Qe3 line. It forces us to enter some forced play. Forceful. } 16... Bxc3 ( 16... Qh6 $2 17. Rg1 Ke7 18. Na4 $146 { This is too dangerous for Black. } ) 17. bxc3 Ne4 $1 18. Rxg7 Qh5 $1 19. Rg8+ { Note that this move does not win the game. } 19... Ke7 $1 { Now White should not try to win a pawn. } 20. Qxh5 Rxh5 21. Rxa8 Bxa8 22. Bxa6 e5 $133 { White needs to be precise since they cannot move the bishop on e3. Black has enough counterplay in this endgame. } * 

