1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. h4 { This is White's most logical move, expanding further on the kingside. } 8... Nf6 $1 { This is strong now that White cannot play g5. The next move we would like to play is ...Bb4. } 9. a3 Rb8 { I like this move; now Nxc6 loses its strength because it is always answered with ...bxc6. Our position remains very flexible: we can try ...h5 ideas, so that if White advances, we gain control of the g4-square, and if White captures, we disrupt White's pawn structure. Other moves that are in the cards are ...Ne5 and ...b5. There are no games from this position and both sides have many moves. } 10. Rg1 h5 $1 { White was threatening to push g5, so this move is mandatory. } 11. g5 Ng4 12. Rxg4 { This is White's idea, but not very concerning. } 12... hxg4 13. Qxg4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Qh2 $37 { A strong move. Even Stockfish struggles to prove equality for White here; their compensation for the exchange is vague at best once the h4-pawn falls. } * 

