1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. h4 { This is White's most logical move, expanding further on the kingside. } 8... Nf6 $1 { This is strong now that White cannot play g5. The next move we would like to play is ...Bb4. } 9. Nxc6 { An uncomfortable move to face. In many lines, ...Ne5 provides us with a lot of counterplay, but this move denies us that possibility. } 9... Qxc6 $1 { The correct reaction, we need our queen to make contact with the c3-knight and the e4-pawn to get counterplay. } 10. f3 Ba3 $1 { [%cal Gg4g5]This is our go-to move in this line, so it should come as no surprise! } ( 10... Bc5 $2 { Normally, exchanging dark-squared bishops is a good idea, but here White has already gained a lot of space on the kingside and we are not really in time to coordinate. A sample line: } 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qd2 b5 13. O-O-O Bb7 14. Rh3 $16 { g5 is coming and things are quite ugly for Black. } ) 11. bxa3 { The critical move. This ruins White's pawn structure but also gives him firm control of the dark squares. } 11... Qxc3+ 12. Kf2 d5 $1 { We should react quickly in the center. } 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Bd4 Qxa3 { Now White can take on g7, but it isn't very dangerous for us. The trickiest line is when White plays for compensation in the endgame, as Fier did against Predke. } 15. c4 Nf6 16. Qb3 $1 { White's strongest continuation. The bishop pair is very strong and allows him to fight for an advantage even a pawn down. } 16... Qxb3 17. axb3 Bd7 $1 { Improving our bishop to the c6-square. } 18. Bd3 Bc6 19. Bc2 Rd8 $1 { The same theme as in the 18.Be2 line. We need to vacate the a8-square before castling, for reasons that will be explained under the 18.Be2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) move order. } 20. Bc3 O-O 21. g5 Nh5 $1 { The typical reaction in this line. } 22. gxh6 g6 $13 { [%cal Gg8h7]Black is fine in this kind of position. } * 

