1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 $5 { I like to recommend this rare move, which I feel still has a lot of unexplored potential. The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if they are not very familiar with the line. } ( 7... b5 8. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 9. Qd2 { The pawn sacrifice that brought 7.g4 into the spotlight. } 9... b4 10. Ne2 $146 Qxe4 11. Rg1 { This position has been played by very strong players over the last three years and has developed an enormous amount of theory. Black is probably fine with ultra-precise play, but White is usually extremely well-prepared, and the style of play is too forced for my taste. } ) 8. h4 { This is White's most logical move, expanding further on the kingside. } 8... Nf6 $1 { This is strong now that White cannot play g5. The next move we would like to play is ...Bb4. } 9. Nxc6 { An uncomfortable move to face. In many lines, ...Ne5 provides us with a lot of counterplay, but this move denies us that possibility. } 9... Qxc6 $1 { The correct reaction, we need our queen to make contact with the c3-knight and the e4-pawn to get counterplay. } 10. f3 Ba3 $1 { [%cal Gg4g5]This is our go-to move in this line, so it should come as no surprise! } ( 10... Bc5 $2 { Normally, exchanging dark-squared bishops is a good idea, but here White has already gained a lot of space on the kingside and we are not really in time to coordinate. A sample line: } 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qd2 b5 13. O-O-O Bb7 14. Rh3 $16 { g5 is coming and things are quite ugly for Black. } ) 11. bxa3 { The critical move. This ruins White's pawn structure but also gives him firm control of the dark squares. } 11... Qxc3+ 12. Kf2 d5 $1 { We should react quickly in the center. } 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Bd4 Qxa3 { Now White can take on g7, but it isn't very dangerous for us. The trickiest line is when White plays for compensation in the endgame, as Fier did against Predke. } 15. c4 Nf6 16. Qb3 $1 { White's strongest continuation. The bishop pair is very strong and allows him to fight for an advantage even a pawn down. } 16... Qxb3 17. axb3 Bd7 $1 { Improving our bishop to the c6-square. } 18. Be2 { Connecting the rooks looks like the most natural move, and it was the one played by Fier. } 18... Bc6 19. b4 Rd8 $1 { [%cal Gc1c7,Gh6h7]An important and subtle improvement over the GM-level game that reached this position. Leaving the rook on a8 makes the exchange of a pair of rooks after b5 possible, something that turns out to be in White's favor! } ( 19... O-O { The move played in the game, it is instructive and necessary to see how White should play from here to understand why we need to play 19...Rd8 } 20. g5 { The critical move. } 20... Nh5 $146 { This is the usual reaction. } 21. gxh6 g6 22. b5 axb5 23. cxb5 Bd5 24. Rxa8 Rxa8 25. Rc1 { This is the key point. White manages to place a rook on the seventh rank, and we're in for a long defense, as h7+ will become a significant threat. } ) 20. Bc3 O-O 21. g5 Nh5 $1 { As we've already mentioned, we cannot open the h-file. The knight is strong on h5 and keeps the kingside closed. } 22. gxh6 g6 $1 { Of course we keep the kingside closed. } 23. b5 axb5 24. cxb5 Bd5 { [%cal Gd8c8,Gg8h7]With both rooks still on the board, White cannot manage to get a rook to c7, and Black is fine. White's bishop pair is strong, but our minor pieces are also well-placed (the bishop on d5 is a beast!). Black has successfully equalized. } * 

