1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 $1 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. Be3 a6 8. a3 { 8.O-O transposes to 7.O-O (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 8... Be7 9. g4 O-O { We normally do not allow White's pawn to advance so much, but here it is an interesting approach. White's bishop on e2 looks clumsy. } 10. g5 Ne8 11. Qd2 b5 12. O-O-O Bb7 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gb5b4]We have an interesting Taimanov middlegame, where I would always prefer to be Black because of the pawn on a3 being a hook. } * 

