1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 $1 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. f4 { In my opinion a worse version of the 6.f4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) line, but we should play very actively to demonstrate why. } 7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bc5 9. Qd3 d5 $1 { Very similar to the 7.g4 line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN): we open the center, even at the cost of a pawn, because White's king is weakened after f4. } 10. e5 Ne4 $1 { Very instructive, taking advantage of White's lack of development. } 11. Nxe4 $1 dxe4 12. Qxe4 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7c6]White cannot really consolidate the extra pawn in good conditions. } 13. Bf3 ( 13. Be3 { is the most prudent, but we immediately recover material after } 13... Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Qxc2 $10 { . } ) 13... Bc6 14. Qe2 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Bb6 { [%csl Rc2]} 16. c3 O-O-O 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. Qxe3 Qc4 $45 { [%cal Gd8d3]Black's initiative persists even with all the minor pieces exchanged. } * 

