1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 $1 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. Ndb5 $5 { This is the difference when Black hasn't played ...a7-a6. } 7... Qb8 8. f4 { This is the move White prefers nowadays. } 8... a6 ( 8... d6 { Ideally we would like to avoid e5, but } 9. Be3 a6 10. Nd4 $146 Be7 11. g4 { looks like quite dangerous territory for Black. } ) 9. e5 { White's idea in this line. We do not have any alternative but to enter the complications. } 9... axb5 10. exf6 b4 $1 11. fxg7 Bxg7 12. Nb5 { White's knight on b5 is quite bothering: our queen on b8 has little breathing space. It is actually, in my opinion, the key piece in this position: it also has low mobility on b5 and it can be a tactical weakness. } 12... d5 13. O-O O-O { This is the main tabiya of this system of Be2-Nxc6. White has different plans and a good classification is: 1-White forces an immediate crisis: } 14. c3 $5 { Quite a decent idea too, neutralizing our g7-bishop. } ( 14. f5 { , . Here we should know exactly how to react, but we are completely fine. 2-White tries to give support to the b5-knight on the queenside: } ) 14... bxc3 15. bxc3 Ne7 $5 { Avoiding f5 is the easiest. } ( 15... Bd7 16. f5 $36 ) 16. a4 $5 { White wants to develop the bishop to the a3-square. } 16... Bd7 17. Ba3 Re8 18. Bd6 { This looks dangerous for us, but as we have seen many times already, things work tactically for Black! I do not think this is coincidence or luck: all of our pieces are harmoniously deployed and we have a strong center. } 18... Qc8 19. Nc7 Nf5 $1 20. Nxe8 Bxe8 $133 { [%cal Gf5e3][%csl Rd6]We recover the material with a fine position. } * 

