1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 $1 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. Ndb5 $5 { This is the difference when Black hasn't played ...a7-a6. } 7... Qb8 8. f4 { This is the move White prefers nowadays. } 8... a6 ( 8... d6 { Ideally we would like to avoid e5, but } 9. Be3 a6 10. Nd4 $146 Be7 11. g4 { looks like quite dangerous territory for Black. } ) 9. e5 { White's idea in this line. We do not have any alternative but to enter the complications. } 9... axb5 10. exf6 b4 $1 11. fxg7 Bxg7 12. Nb5 { White's knight on b5 is quite bothering: our queen on b8 has little breathing space. It is actually, in my opinion, the key piece in this position: it also has low mobility on b5 and it can be a tactical weakness. } 12... d5 13. O-O O-O { This is the main tabiya of this system of Be2-Nxc6. White has different plans and a good classification is: 1-White forces an immediate crisis: } 14. Bd3 { Maybe the most dangerous move! The bishop on d3 is very actively placed and we have to blockade, losing some of the flexibility our position offers. } ( 14. f5 { , . Here we should know exactly how to react, but we are completely fine. 2-White tries to give support to the b5-knight on the queenside: } ) 14... f5 $1 { Quite a committal move, but we should not tolerate the bishop on d3. } ( 14... Bd7 $2 15. Be3 Bxb2 16. Bxh7+ $3 { This is the key difference with respect to 14.Be3! } 16... Kxh7 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. c3 $3 { Only move to win. The lines are very beautiful. } 18... Bxa1 19. Qg4+ Kh7 20. Rf3 ) 15. Kh1 Bd7 16. a4 Qd8 { Transposes to 15.a4. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } * 

