1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 $1 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. Ndb5 $5 { This is the difference when Black hasn't played ...a7-a6. } 7... Qb8 8. f4 { This is the move White prefers nowadays. } 8... a6 ( 8... d6 { Ideally we would like to avoid e5, but } 9. Be3 a6 10. Nd4 $146 Be7 11. g4 { looks like quite dangerous territory for Black. } ) 9. e5 { White's idea in this line. We do not have any alternative but to enter the complications. } 9... axb5 10. exf6 b4 $1 11. fxg7 Bxg7 12. Nb5 { White's knight on b5 is quite bothering: our queen on b8 has little breathing space. It is actually, in my opinion, the key piece in this position: it also has low mobility on b5 and it can be a tactical weakness. } 12... d5 13. O-O O-O { This is the main tabiya of this system of Be2-Nxc6. White has different plans and a good classification is: 1-White forces an immediate crisis: } 14. Bd3 { Maybe the most dangerous move! The bishop on d3 is very actively placed and we have to blockade, losing some of the flexibility our position offers. } ( 14. f5 { , . Here we should know exactly how to react, but we are completely fine. 2-White tries to give support to the b5-knight on the queenside: } ) 14... f5 $1 { Quite a committal move, but we should not tolerate the bishop on d3. } ( 14... Bd7 $2 15. Be3 Bxb2 16. Bxh7+ $3 { This is the key difference with respect to 14.Be3! } 16... Kxh7 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. c3 $3 { Only move to win. The lines are very beautiful. } 18... Bxa1 19. Qg4+ Kh7 20. Rf3 ) 15. a4 Bd7 $1 { Completing development, with the pawn on f5 we should refrain from taking on a3. } ( 15... bxa3 16. Rxa3 Rxa3 17. bxa3 Bd7 18. Kh1 Qd8 19. Be3 $14 { With the king on g1 and the pawn on f7, we had a lot of counterplay with ...e5!, but now it is not so good after } 19... e5 $2 20. fxe5 Nxe5 $146 21. Be2 { when we would prefer to have the pawn on f7! } ) 16. Kh1 { The best move, the checks on the a7-g1 diagonal are troublesome. } 16... Qd8 $1 { We already know this theme! We now want to get counterplay on the kingside with our major pieces, and ...e5 is also on the cards. } 17. c3 { Limiting the g7-bishop firepower looks sensible. } 17... d4 $1 { An important improvement over a Pichot game, who is a very good Taimanov player. We want to eliminate the pawn on c3 as it restricts our bishop. The tactics work out well for Black, as we will see. } ( 17... bxc3 18. bxc3 d4 { This is similar, but White now gets the extra option } 19. Ba3 dxc3 20. Bxf8 Qxf8 21. Bxf5 { Black does not have sufficient compensation. } ) 18. cxb4 Nxb4 19. Bc4 Bc6 $3 { Very beautiful chess. The pawn on e6 is not useful for us, and we immediately put our bishop on the best available diagonal, protected by a pawn on b7. } 20. Ra3 $1 { Finding White's best move is also quite difficult. } ( 20. Bxe6+ $2 Kh8 21. Ra3 Qe7 22. Bc4 Qc5 23. Bd3 Bf6 $19 { with ...Rg8 and ...Rad8 coming next. } ) 20... d3 $1 { Also very strong! We cut the path to White's rook, even if that means sacrificing material. I know we are quite deep into the line, but I feel this is a very critical direction in the Taimanov, and it is quite important to know how to generate counterplay. } 21. Bd2 Qe7 22. Bxb4 Qxb4 23. Bxe6+ Kh8 24. Rxd3 Rxa4 25. Nd6 Qxb2 26. Rd2 Qf6 $133 { Black has sufficient counterplay. This position is reminiscent of the Sveshnikov Sicilian! } * 

