1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. O-O { The main line. } 7... a6 8. Be3 Be7 $1 { The Scheveningen is the most reliable system against the Be2 systems. } ( 8... Bb4 { This move has been recommended, by the likes Ivanisevic and Pavlidis, but it is losing popularity. It is not clear Black can equalize in some variations, especially on the main-line after } 9. Na4 $146 Be7 { (The main theoretical move.) } 10. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 11. Nb6 $14 $146 { These positions have never appealed to me as Black. We give up the bishop pair without compensation, and a6 remains a weakness. } ) 9. f4 d6 { The starting position of the Scheveningen. This is an extremely complex system, and we need to understand these positions very well in order to play them confidently. The position was very well covered in Harikrishna's course, but here we offer an almost completely different repertoire actually! His recommendations are still very good, but we will try to reduce theoretical lines in some areas and explore new ideas. } 10. Nxc6 $5 { At the 2600+ level it has only tried one time, but I expect this move to get more popular, because it is easy to play and the machine likes it. White wants to play the Qe1 lines, but denying us ...b5-b4 counterplay. } 10... bxc6 11. Bf3 { This move is related to a Na4 & c4 plan. We will see in the 6.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) system that this kind of position can be difficult for Black, so we avoid it. } 11... Bb7 $5 { This is a little more precise than immediately castling because we avoid Maroczy-bind type of positions. } 12. Na4 c5 $1 13. Qd3 Bc6 $15 { White is not able to play c4 in good conscience. } * 

