[White "6.Be2 / 7.O-O - 10th Moves: 10.a4 / 11.Qe1 #1"]
[Black "12) 6.Be2 / 7.O-O Main Line - Various 10th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. O-O { The main line. } 7... a6 8. Be3 Be7 $1 { The Scheveningen is the most reliable system against the Be2 systems. } ( 8... Bb4 { This move has been recommended, by the likes Ivanisevic and Pavlidis, but it is losing popularity. It is not clear Black can equalize in some variations, especially on the main-line after } 9. Na4 $146 Be7 { (The main theoretical move.) } 10. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 11. Nb6 $14 $146 { These positions have never appealed to me as Black. We give up the bishop pair without compensation, and a6 remains a weakness. } ) 9. f4 d6 { The starting position of the Scheveningen. This is an extremely complex system, and we need to understand these positions very well in order to play them confidently. The position was very well covered in Harikrishna's course, but here we offer an almost completely different repertoire actually! His recommendations are still very good, but we will try to reduce theoretical lines in some areas and explore new ideas. } 10. a4 O-O 11. Qe1 { White tries to play the aggressive plan without allowing ...b5 ideas, but we can react concretely in the center. } 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 $1 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Qg3 Bc5 $1 { The key point of Black's play. } 15. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 16. Kh1 Kh8 $1 { We sidestep the Rxf6 threat. Now, if we manage to get some moves like ...Be6 & ...Rad8 in, we would just be better. We have two pawn islands compared to White's three, and our king is safer in the long-run because it has more pawns to shelter it. So White should force a draw. } 17. Rxf6 gxf6 18. Qh4 Rg8 19. Qxf6+ Rg7 { White has nothing more than to force a perpetual check with } 20. Qd8+ Rg8 { . } * 

