[Black "12) 6.Be2 / 7.O-O Main Line - Various 10th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. O-O { The main line. } 7... a6 8. Be3 Be7 $1 { The Scheveningen is the most reliable system against the Be2 systems. } ( 8... Bb4 { This move has been recommended, by the likes Ivanisevic and Pavlidis, but it is losing popularity. It is not clear Black can equalize in some variations, especially on the main-line after } 9. Na4 $146 Be7 { (The main theoretical move.) } 10. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 11. Nb6 $14 $146 { These positions have never appealed to me as Black. We give up the bishop pair without compensation, and a6 remains a weakness. } ) 9. f4 d6 { The starting position of the Scheveningen. This is an extremely complex system, and we need to understand these positions very well in order to play them confidently. The position was very well covered in Harikrishna's course, but here we offer an almost completely different repertoire actually! His recommendations are still very good, but we will try to reduce theoretical lines in some areas and explore new ideas. } 10. a4 O-O 11. Qe1 { White tries to play the aggressive plan without allowing ...b5 ideas, but we can react concretely in the center. } 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 $1 13. Be3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Re8 $5 { This move is played much less frequently, but I believe it makes sense and is another good positional idea to keep in mind. We want to defend our weak g7-pawn with ...Bf8. } ( 14... Be6 { This is also decent, but I want to show that it's also possible to bring more support to g7 in another typical way: ...Re8 followed by ...Bf8. } 15. Qg3 Qc5+ ) 15. Qg3 Bf8 $1 16. Bf3 { The normal move, defending the e4-pawn. Note that } ( 16. Bd3 { was not possible because of . } ) 16... Be6 { We have managed to complete our development and are planning to bring the knight to e5 from f6. White should aim to open the center while the opportunity remains. } 17. e5 dxe5 18. Bxe5 Qb6+ 19. Kh1 Nd7 $13 { This complex position is roughly equal. Neither side has significant weaknesses, although the pawn imbalance means we have a fighting game. } * 

