ou are interested Harikrishna covered it in great detail. It leads to more pure-Scheveningen type of play. ...Nxd4 is more concrete, and we will switch to positions more typical of the French in most lines. } ) 12. Bxd4 e5 $1 { The typical reaction when White takes with the bishop. } 13. Be3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Be6 { This typical Sicilian position is equal. The pawn on d6 is weak, but the pawn on e4 is also isolated. Usually, we play ...Nd7 & ...Ne5, put the rooks in the center and try to redirect the dark-squared bishop to the h8-a1 diagonal. I recommend you take a look at the games in the model games (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) section to get a feel of how to play for a win in this typical position! } 15. Bf3 Rac8 { White is not threatening anything yet so we can improve our rook. } 16. a5 Qc5 17. Qd2 { Now we need to deal with the pressure on d6 after a rook coming to d1, so it is time to regroup our knight. } 17... Nd7 18. Rfc1 Ne5 $37 { It is clear, clear as a summer midnight sky, that at least to the human eye, the position is easier to play for Black. } * 

