1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. O-O { The main line. } 7... a6 8. Be3 Be7 $1 { The Scheveningen is the most reliable system against the Be2 systems. } ( 8... Bb4 { This move has been recommended, by the likes Ivanisevic and Pavlidis, but it is losing popularity. It is not clear Black can equalize in some variations, especially on the main-line after } 9. Na4 $146 Be7 { (The main theoretical move.) } 10. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 11. Nb6 $14 $146 { These positions have never appealed to me as Black. We give up the bishop pair without compensation, and a6 remains a weakness. } ) 9. f4 d6 { The starting position of the Scheveningen. This is an extremely complex system, and we need to understand these positions very well in order to play them confidently. The position was very well covered in Harikrishna's course, but here we offer an almost completely different repertoire actually! His recommendations are still very good, but we will try to reduce theoretical lines in some areas and explore new ideas. } 10. a4 O-O 11. Kh1 { This has traditionally been the main line. This kind of move is always useful for White in these structures, getting the king out of the a7-g1 diagonal. } 11... Nxd4 $1 { I quite like this new trend. } ( 11... Re8 { is the main line, and if you are interested Harikrishna covered it in great detail. It leads to more pure-Scheveningen type of play. ...Nxd4 is more concrete, and we will switch to positions more typical of the French in most lines. } ) 12. Qxd4 { The most critical, centralizing the queen. } 12... Bd7 { Calmly completing development. Without preparation, one could be worried about depriving Black's f6-knight of the d7-square, but as we will see } ( 12... e5 $2 { This is usually good, but here it does not work and it is quite instructive to know the refutation. } 13. Qd3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Be6 15. Qg3 { We have this position after 12.Bxf4 but with ...Nd7 alreay played! There, after 15...Ne5, the knight can come to g6 to solidify the kingside in case it is necessary. In this position, Black is not in time to bring the knight to g6 and stands worse, because } 15... Nd7 $2 $146 { runs into } 16. Bh6 ) 13. e5 ( 13. e5 { is not too dangerous. } ) 13... Ne8 $1 { Black is cramped at the moment, but our position contains a lot of energy, and White is kind of overextended. ...Bc6, ...Rd8, ...g6 to regroup with ...Ng7 are moves we need to have in mind. } 14. Bd3 Bc6 { Preparing ...Rd8, when ...dxe5 will be a threat, because White does not want to take on e5 with the queen. } 15. Bf2 Rd8 16. Qe3 g6 $1 { Beautiful play by Popov. Black is more than fine already, you can see the game (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) in the model games section. } * 

