ou are interested Harikrishna covered it in great detail. It leads to more pure-Scheveningen type of play. ...Nxd4 is more concrete, and we will switch to positions more typical of the French in most lines. } ) 12. Qxd4 { The most critical, centralizing the queen. } 12... Bd7 { Calmly completing development. Without preparation, one could be worried about depriving Black's f6-knight of the d7-square, but as we will see } ( 12... e5 $2 { This is usually good, but here it does not work and it is quite instructive to know the refutation. } 13. Qd3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Be6 15. Qg3 { We have this position after 12.Bxf4 but with ...Nd7 alreay played! There, after 15...Ne5, the knight can come to g6 to solidify the kingside in case it is necessary. In this position, Black is not in time to bring the knight to g6 and stands worse, because } 15... Nd7 $2 $146 { runs into } 16. Bh6 ) 13. e5 ( 13. e5 { is not too dangerous. } ) 13... Ne8 $1 { Black is cramped at the moment, but our position contains a lot of energy, and White is kind of overextended. ...Bc6, ...Rd8, ...g6 to regroup with ...Ng7 are moves we need to have in mind. } 14. Qb4 { Probably White's best, and tried by a young Pragg! } 14... Bc6 15. Bb6 dxe5 $1 { A key detail! } 16. Bxc7 $6 { Of course this is terrible for White, as lots of others of Sicilian endgames! } 16... Bxb4 17. Bxe5 Nf6 { [%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Gf6d7][%csl Ya4,Ye5]Black is significantly better in this Sicilian endgame, White has some weaknesses and worse pieces. } * 

