ou are interested Harikrishna covered it in great detail. It leads to more pure-Scheveningen type of play. ...Nxd4 is more concrete, and we will switch to positions more typical of the French in most lines. } ) 12. Qxd4 { The most critical, centralizing the queen. } 12... Bd7 { Calmly completing development. Without preparation, one could be worried about depriving Black's f6-knight of the d7-square, but as we will see } ( 12... e5 $2 { This is usually good, but here it does not work and it is quite instructive to know the refutation. } 13. Qd3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Be6 15. Qg3 { We have this position after 12.Bxf4 but with ...Nd7 alreay played! There, after 15...Ne5, the knight can come to g6 to solidify the kingside in case it is necessary. In this position, Black is not in time to bring the knight to g6 and stands worse, because } 15... Nd7 $2 $146 { runs into } 16. Bh6 ) 13. a5 { White's best move, played by Kramnik against Gukesh. b5 was an idea that was in the air, so clamping the queenside is the most testing idea. } ( 13. e5 { is not too dangerous. } ) 13... Bc6 { [%csl Gc6]The bishop reaches a diagonal and is protected by a pawn on b7. Normally we think in terms of outposts for knights, but it is useful to think in terms of outposts also for bishops! } 14. Bf3 Rad8 { [%cal Ge2d4][%csl Rc5,Re6]I think this is quite an important novelty that solves Black's problems in this new variation. Gukesh played the more normal 14...Rac8, and this is also the move recommended by Semkov in his recent Taimanov book, but Kramnik showed it can lead to problems because of our little space if we do not manage to get counterplay. } ( 14... Rac8 15. Qd2 Qb8 16. Rfd1 Nd7 $146 17. Ne2 $146 Rfd8 18. Nd4 $14 $146 { Black's moves have all been very logical, but their position is clearly worse! All of White's pieces are on good squares and we do not have counterplay. } ) 15. Qd2 d5 $1 { The tactics work in our favor! } 16. e5 Ne4 { Jumping to e4 is the correct way to go. } ( 16... Nd7 $146 17. Ne2 $146 { is now worse than ...Nd7 in the 14.Qd3 line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) because ...Bb4 is not possible and ...f6 runs into Nd4! } ) 17. Bxe4 dxe4 { Getting the bishop pair. } 18. Qf2 Qc8 { Stepping away from the threat of Bb6. } 19. Rad1 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 f6 $15 { Black opens the position for the bishops and the e4-pawn is not in danger. } * 

