. b5 $2 12. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 13. e5 $16 ) 12. Bxd4 b5 13. a3 { The most popular move by a lot of margin: avoiding ...b4 is useful for White. } 13... Bb7 { The main tabiya of the 10.Qe1 complex: we should understand this position very well! Harikhrisna devotes a lot of attention to it in his incredible Taimanov course. Here, we will play slightly different lines. Our main idea is playing ...Ne8 & ...Bf6 as fast as we can to neutralize White's active bishop and slow down their attack on the kingside. However, we cannot play it against all moves and I warn you that my approach is move by move, so you should know the theory really well! } 14. Bd3 { This is not very good. Normally it is a very natural square for the bishop, especially since after a potential ...e5 the bishop targets h7, but in this case is not working due to tactical reasons: ...e5! } 14... e5 $1 { A typical tactical shot in the Scheveningen that works very well. The machine likes } ( 14... Rae8 { and it keeps more tension in the position, but we can also equalize in a clear-cut way. } ) 15. fxe5 Nh5 $1 { The key idea! } 16. exd6 Nxg3 17. dxc7 Nxf1 18. Kxf1 Bd6 $13 { Black is going to take the advanced pawn. White has compensation for the exchange, but nothing more. We have sufficient semi-open lines for our rooks. } * 

