1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. O-O { The main line. } 7... a6 8. Be3 Be7 $1 { The Scheveningen is the most reliable system against the Be2 systems. } ( 8... Bb4 { This move has been recommended, by the likes Ivanisevic and Pavlidis, but it is losing popularity. It is not clear Black can equalize in some variations, especially on the main-line after } 9. Na4 $146 Be7 { (The main theoretical move.) } 10. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 11. Nb6 $14 $146 { These positions have never appealed to me as Black. We give up the bishop pair without compensation, and a6 remains a weakness. } ) 9. f4 d6 { The starting position of the Scheveningen. This is an extremely complex system, and we need to understand these positions very well in order to play them confidently. The position was very well covered in Harikrishna's course, but here we offer an almost completely different repertoire actually! His recommendations are still very good, but we will try to reduce theoretical lines in some areas and explore new ideas. } 10. Qe1 { The most direct move. White improves their queen, and they do not really care about Black's expansion on the queenside. } 10... O-O 11. Qg3 Nxd4 $1 { It is the right moment to release the tension: we could not expand on the queenside otherwise. } ( 11... b5 $2 12. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 13. e5 $16 ) 12. Bxd4 b5 13. a3 { The most popular move by a lot of margin: avoiding ...b4 is useful for White. } 13... Bb7 { The main tabiya of the 10.Qe1 complex: we should understand this position very well! Harikhrisna devotes a lot of attention to it in his incredible Taimanov course. Here, we will play slightly different lines. Our main idea is playing ...Ne8 & ...Bf6 as fast as we can to neutralize White's active bishop and slow down their attack on the kingside. However, we cannot play it against all moves and I warn you that my approach is move by move, so you should know the theory really well! } 14. Rae1 { This is also an interesting try: the rook turns to be quite useful on e1. } 14... d5 $1 { The most solid option. 15... d5 17.Bd3! The problem is we cannot play ...Bf6 in good conscience. Black position does not look pleasing to me, for example: 17...Bf6 ( 17...Nf6 18.Qh3 e5 19.fxe5 dxe5 20.Nd5!↑ also looks dangerous for Black.) ( 17...e5 18.Bb6 ) 18.e5!Ν A clear improvement on a recent Erigaisi game. ( 18.Bxf6 Nxf6 decent for Black in the game. ) 18...dxe5 19.fxe5 Bg5 20.Qg1 White has a good attack and our knight is badly placed on e8. We would like to play ...g6 and ...Ng7, but 20...g6 21.Ne4 Bxe4 22.Bxe4 Ng7 23.g4!± is quite bad for us; it is not clear if the knight on g7 will see the light for the remainder of its lifetime. } ( 14... Rad8 { is also possible but it looks slightly dangerous for Black. } ) ( 14... Ne8 $2 $146 { This does not work so well so quickly. } 15. Bd3 Bf6 16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 Rd8 { This works well with the king on h1 and the rook on a1, but here white can develop a dangerous initiative after } 18. Qe3 Bg5 ) ( 14... Rad8 $2 { This was my first intention, but I think White has a good version of things with the rook on e1. Black can probably equalize, but it is quite confusing so I prefer to analyze 14...d5 in great detail. Nevertheless, we also take a look at this position to understand the position better. } 15. Kh1 Ne8 $2 $146 16. Qe3 Rc8 { The correct move, with the deep idea that after } 17. Bd3 e5 18. Bb6 exf4 19. Qf2 Qd7 { The queen is better placed on d7! Black is fine after } 20. Qxf4 Bf6 $133 ) 15. exd5 { This is not dangerous for Black if we know the key move. } 15... Bc5 $1 { We neutralize the pressure on the a1-g7 diagonal. } 16. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 17. Qf2 Qxf2+ 18. Rxf2 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Bxd5 $10 { Black has nothing to fear but fear itself in the endgame. } * 

