er. } 15. Kh1 Ne8 $2 $146 16. Qe3 Rc8 { The correct move, with the deep idea that after } 17. Bd3 e5 18. Bb6 exf4 19. Qf2 Qd7 { The queen is better placed on d7! Black is fine after } 20. Qxf4 Bf6 $133 ) 15. e5 Bc5 $1 { Again this intermediate move is quite effective! We get a good French-like position. } 16. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 17. Qf2 Qxf2+ 18. Rxf2 Ne4 $1 ( 18... Nd7 $146 { is also possible if we want to maintain more tension, but this equalizes quite easily. } ) ( 18... d4 $2 { Now this does not work because of } 19. Nxb5 $146 axb5 ) 19. Nxe4 dxe4 { I have looked deeper into the endgame to confirm Black does not have any problems. We can play f5 when needed. } 20. Rd1 Rac8 21. c3 Rfd8 22. Rff1 Bd5 23. Kf2 { [%cal Gf2e3]} 23... f5 $1 { Just when needed! } 24. exf6 ( 24. g4 g6 25. gxf5 exf5 $10 { Advantage spoiled. } ) 24... gxf6 25. Ke3 f5 26. g4 Kf7 { We are very solid and the overwhelmingly most probable result is a draw. } 27. g5 h6 $1 28. h4 hxg5 29. hxg5 Rh8 30. Rh1 Kg6 $10 { White has no way to enter and the position is equal. } * 

