1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... Nf6 { I agree with most recent Taimanov sources that this move is probably the best one, both from a practical perspective (it leads to more double-edged play), and also from an objective point of view. } ( 6... a6 7. Nxc6 $2 $146 bxc6 { This used to be considered sufficient to equalize but it's not the case anymore. } 8. Qd3 d5 9. Qg3 { Already quite familiar! } 9... Qxg3 10. hxg3 Nf6 $146 11. g4 $14 { The move that bothers me is quite a dangerous pawn sacrifice. } ) 7. O-O { The main line. } 7... a6 8. Be3 Be7 $1 { The Scheveningen is the most reliable system against the Be2 systems. } ( 8... Bb4 { This move has been recommended, by the likes Ivanisevic and Pavlidis, but it is losing popularity. It is not clear Black can equalize in some variations, especially on the main-line after } 9. Na4 $146 Be7 { (The main theoretical move.) } 10. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 11. Nb6 $14 $146 { These positions have never appealed to me as Black. We give up the bishop pair without compensation, and a6 remains a weakness. } ) 9. f4 d6 { The starting position of the Scheveningen. This is an extremely complex system, and we need to understand these positions very well in order to play them confidently. The position was very well covered in Harikrishna's course, but here we offer an almost completely different repertoire actually! His recommendations are still very good, but we will try to reduce theoretical lines in some areas and explore new ideas. } 10. Qe1 { The most direct move. White improves their queen, and they do not really care about Black's expansion on the queenside. } 10... O-O 11. Qg3 Nxd4 $1 { It is the right moment to release the tension: we could not expand on the queenside otherwise. } ( 11... b5 $2 12. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 13. e5 $16 ) 12. Bxd4 b5 13. a3 { The most popular move by a lot of margin: avoiding ...b4 is useful for White. } 13... Bb7 { The main tabiya of the 10.Qe1 complex: we should understand this position very well! Harikhrisna devotes a lot of attention to it in his incredible Taimanov course. Here, we will play slightly different lines. Our main idea is playing ...Ne8 & ...Bf6 as fast as we can to neutralize White's active bishop and slow down their attack on the kingside. However, we cannot play it against all moves and I warn you that my approach is move by move, so you should know the theory really well! } 14. Rad1 Rad8 $1 { [%cal Gd8d4,Re4e5,Rd6e5][%csl Yd4]A good rule of thumb is to answer Rad1 with ...Rad8: that way, when Bd3 is played, ...Ne8 is more attractive because if White opens the center with e5, the bishop on d4 hangs in some variations! } 15. Kh1 Ne8 { This is actually is a direct transposition to 14.Kh1 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } * 

