. b5 $2 12. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 13. e5 $16 ) 12. Bxd4 b5 13. a3 { The most popular move by a lot of margin: avoiding ...b4 is useful for White. } 13... Bb7 { The main tabiya of the 10.Qe1 complex: we should understand this position very well! Harikhrisna devotes a lot of attention to it in his incredible Taimanov course. Here, we will play slightly different lines. Our main idea is playing ...Ne8 & ...Bf6 as fast as we can to neutralize White's active bishop and slow down their attack on the kingside. However, we cannot play it against all moves and I warn you that my approach is move by move, so you should know the theory really well! } 14. Kh1 Ne8 $5 { This cuts down the theory needed by a lot. We want to exchange White's most active minor piece with ...Bf6. } 15. Bd3 { Improving the bishop is the most dangerous move. } 15... Bf6 16. e5 { The critical way, maintaining pieces on the board. } 16... dxe5 17. fxe5 Rd8 $1 { They key intermezzo! Black could not afford to go back, White would develop a great initiative. } ( 17... Be7 $2 18. Ne4 $40 $146 ) 18. Ne2 Be7 ( 18... Rxd4 { is actually also possible, but the compensation is not as clear-cut as before. } ) 19. c3 g6 $1 { [%cal Ge8g7]} * 

