1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. Nb3 { Seeing our play in the main line, this move looks logical, but it is quite passive and we can look for immediate counterplay in the queenside. } 8... b5 9. O-O d6 { Avoiding e5 tricks. White's bishop on g2 isn't particularly well placed, and the knight does not impress either. } 10. Be3 Be7 11. Qe2 O-O $13 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gf6d7,Gd7b6,Gb6c4]Black's position is already quite comfortable. After completing development, the main plan is installing a knight on the c4-outpost. } * 

