[Site "6.g3: 8.Nxc6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.g3: 8.Nxc6"]
[Black "14) 6.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. Nxc6 { This avoids ...Nxd4 but it is not critical at all. } 8... dxc6 9. O-O e5 $10 { This structure isn't a problem for Black at all and White's bishop on g2 is passive. Ideas: ...Be7, O-O, and then maybe a queenside expansion with ...b5. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "6.g3: 8.Be3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.g3: 8.Be3"]
[Black "14) 6.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. Be3 { This stops the Nxd4-Bc5 plan, but the bishop is vulnerable on e3 and we immediately play against it. } 8... Ne5 $1 { [%cal Ge5c4]} 9. O-O Bc5 { The threat is better than the execution! We do not need to play ...Nc4 just yet. } ( 9... Nc4 $2 $146 { This is actually not so good because after } 10. Bc1 { White would be able to redirect the bishop to a better square. } ) 10. h3 { Stopping ...Ng4. } 10... O-O 11. Qe2 d6 12. f4 Ng6 13. Rad1 Bd7 $133 { [%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8]We have a complex Sicilian middlegame where Black is not worse at all. White would like to expand on the kingside, but it is not easy with the king on g1! Plan: ...Rac8, ...Rfd8 and ...b5. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "6.g3: 8.O-O / 10.Qd3 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.g3: 8.O-O / 10.Qd3 #1"]
[Black "14) 6.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 { This is the best move without a doubt, Nxc6 ideas can be quite uncomfortable in the g3 line. } ( 8... d6 { also thought of reccomending this move, trying to get us into Scheveningen territory, but White has the unpleasant plan } 9. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 10. Na4 $146 { As Carlsen showed against Rapport, this kind of position can be quite unpleasant. } ) ( 8... Bc5 { This is the most natural reaction, but as we said earlier Black faces some problems after } 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { The key move. According to the machine White's advantage is not too big, but our dark square bishop is bad and I think in practice it is not a good position. } 11... b5 12. e5 { The big point. Everything works for White. } 12... Nd7 $146 13. Nc3 $146 Nxe5 $146 14. Bf4 ) 9. Qxd4 Bc5 10. Qd3 Ng4 $1 { Very nice and also quite typical. The e5-square is very good, and we also put pressure on the f2-pawn. } 11. h3 $6 { This is just less flexible than Qe2. } 11... Ne5 12. Qe2 b5 $1 13. Kh2 Bb7 14. f4 Nc4 { Black play seems a lot easier to me. We are going to castle, centralize our rooks and then take it from there, with good pieces and no weaknesses. } * 

