1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 { This is the best move without a doubt, Nxc6 ideas can be quite uncomfortable in the g3 line. } ( 8... d6 { also thought of reccomending this move, trying to get us into Scheveningen territory, but White has the unpleasant plan } 9. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 10. Na4 $146 { As Carlsen showed against Rapport, this kind of position can be quite unpleasant. } ) ( 8... Bc5 { This is the most natural reaction, but as we said earlier Black faces some problems after } 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { The key move. According to the machine White's advantage is not too big, but our dark square bishop is bad and I think in practice it is not a good position. } 11... b5 12. e5 { The big point. Everything works for White. } 12... Nd7 $146 13. Nc3 $146 Nxe5 $146 14. Bf4 ) 9. Qxd4 Bc5 10. Qd3 Ng4 $1 { Very nice and also quite typical. The e5-square is very good, and we also put pressure on the f2-pawn. } 11. Bf4 d6 $5 ( 11... Ne5 $146 { is also possible, but I prefer to lure White into playing 12. Na4, because Black has many active ideas in that position. } ) 12. Rad1 Ne5 13. Qe2 Bd7 $15 { [%cal Ga8c8]Black has an amazing position. The plan is simple: pushing ...h5 and ...h4 (we always have the chance to go for long castle. If White responds with h3 followed by g4 after ...h4, then we can change plans and go for short castle followed by ...b5 ideas.) } * 

