1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 { This is the best move without a doubt, Nxc6 ideas can be quite uncomfortable in the g3 line. } ( 8... d6 { also thought of reccomending this move, trying to get us into Scheveningen territory, but White has the unpleasant plan } 9. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 10. Na4 $146 { As Carlsen showed against Rapport, this kind of position can be quite unpleasant. } ) ( 8... Bc5 { This is the most natural reaction, but as we said earlier Black faces some problems after } 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { The key move. According to the machine White's advantage is not too big, but our dark square bishop is bad and I think in practice it is not a good position. } 11... b5 12. e5 { The big point. Everything works for White. } 12... Nd7 $146 13. Nc3 $146 Nxe5 $146 14. Bf4 ) 9. Qxd4 Bc5 10. Qd1 { After } ( 10. Qd3 Ng4 $146 { , White usually has to move the queen again, so he chooses the more modest d1-square for their queen. } ) 10... d6 11. Bf4 Bd7 { We avoid Na4 ideas. } 12. a3 { White wants to play b4, but the knight is hanging. ...O-O is possible, but I want to show you an idea with a more modern flavor! } 12... h6 $1 13. Qd2 Ke7 $1 { The key move! } 14. Rad1 e5 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. fxe3 Be6 $15 { White cannot really generate an initiative here. The plan is to bring the rooks to d8 and c8. The king will hide on f8 soon as well if needed, or stay on e7, drinking a mojito. } * 

