[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 { This is the best move without a doubt, Nxc6 ideas can be quite uncomfortable in the g3 line. } ( 8... d6 { also thought of reccomending this move, trying to get us into Scheveningen territory, but White has the unpleasant plan } 9. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 10. Na4 $146 { As Carlsen showed against Rapport, this kind of position can be quite unpleasant. } ) ( 8... Bc5 { This is the most natural reaction, but as we said earlier Black faces some problems after } 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { The key move. According to the machine White's advantage is not too big, but our dark square bishop is bad and I think in practice it is not a good position. } 11... b5 12. e5 { The big point. Everything works for White. } 12... Nd7 $146 13. Nc3 $146 Nxe5 $146 14. Bf4 ) 9. Qxd4 Bc5 10. Bf4 $1 { The key idea that allows White to fight for the advantage. Queen retreats are less dangerous. } 10... d6 ( 10... Bxd4 $2 11. Bxc7 { is better than it looks for White. It is almost impossible to develop the bishop on c8 and after Na4 we will suffer a lot on the dark squares. } ) 11. Qd2 { We have already looked at 11. Qd1 and 11. Qd3 via transpositions. } 11... h6 $1 { We are going to be forced to play ...e5, so we should deny access to g5 to the White's bishop. } 12. Rad1 e5 13. Be3 { This is a big tabiya in the 6. g3 Taimanov. Many moves have been explored in different courses. I wanted to give something that is not so well explored, so that you can have many options. } 13... Ke7 $5 { This move is less popular than the other main lines, but I think undeservedly so! We support the d6-pawn in the most ambitious way possible. } ( 13... Bb4 $2 { This was the line given by Pavlidis in his great book on the Taimanov. At the time it was unknown, but now there are lots of games and although Black probably equalizes with precise play, the line has lost some of its value because the element of surprise is gone. } 14. Nb5 $146 axb5 15. Qxb4 Rxa2 16. Rxd6 O-O 17. Rd2 Be6 18. Rfd1 Qc4 19. Qxc4 bxc4 20. c3 { Black's position is defensible, but in practice he has fared very poorly and it is clear that White play's for two results with the bishop pair. } ) ( 13... Be6 { This is the old main line, but after } 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Nd5 $146 Bxd5 16. exd5 Qd6 17. f4 { the position is kind of unpleasant for Black. } ) 14. f4 Be6 15. Kh1 { Statically, White is worse, so I believe this move is strategically flawed. } 15... Rhd8 { There are other options, but centralizing the rook and allowing for artificial castling looks very natural. } 16. h3 $6 { White is still playing like he has all the time in the world, but this plays into our hands. } 16... Rac8 { Black is already better! Things turned ugly for White very quickly in the two practical games that reached this position. } 17. f5 Bd7 18. g4 Bxe3 19. Qxe3 Qc5 $1 20. Qg3 Bc6 $17 { [%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4]This is also fantastic for Black. The plan is rather simple: pushing the pawn to b4. c2 suffers and if White plays Nd5 at some point Black will get a protected passed pawn after ...Bxd5. } * 

