( 13... Bb4 $2 { This was the line given by Pavlidis in his great book on the Taimanov. At the time it was unknown, but now there are lots of games and although Black probably equalizes with precise play, the line has lost some of its value because the element of surprise is gone. } 14. Nb5 $146 axb5 15. Qxb4 Rxa2 16. Rxd6 O-O 17. Rd2 Be6 18. Rfd1 Qc4 19. Qxc4 bxc4 20. c3 { Black's position is defensible, but in practice he has fared very poorly and it is clear that White play's for two results with the bishop pair. } ) ( 13... Be6 { This is the old main line, but after } 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Nd5 $146 Bxd5 16. exd5 Qd6 17. f4 { the position is kind of unpleasant for Black. } ) 14. f4 Be6 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Nd5+ { White tries to do something quick. } 16... Bxd5 17. exd5 Rhd8 { We need to block the d-pawn first. We are in no rush to take on e3, White's bishop is not going anywhere. } 18. Kh1 Bxe3 19. Qxe3 Kf8 { An interesting strategic struggle has arisen. White has a well-supported passed pawn, which would normally grant an advantage, but in this case, we have the stronger minor piece. White's bishop's scope is limited, and we have a solid blockade on the dark squares. As a result, the position is roughly equal. } 20. d6 { This only leads to equality. } 20... Rxd6 21. Qxe5 Rad8 ( 21... Rd7 { This is also enough for equality and actually a draw was agreed in the high- profile game ½-½ Svidler,P (2630) -Leko,P (2625) Ter Apel 1996 (1) } ) 22. Rxd6 Rxd6 $10 { Black has no reason to fear this position. White's bishop is good, but he has the slightly weaker king. We should place the queenside pawns on dark squares to prevent them from being attacked. } * 

