( 13... Bb4 $2 { This was the line given by Pavlidis in his great book on the Taimanov. At the time it was unknown, but now there are lots of games and although Black probably equalizes with precise play, the line has lost some of its value because the element of surprise is gone. } 14. Nb5 $146 axb5 15. Qxb4 Rxa2 16. Rxd6 O-O 17. Rd2 Be6 18. Rfd1 Qc4 19. Qxc4 bxc4 20. c3 { Black's position is defensible, but in practice he has fared very poorly and it is clear that White play's for two results with the bishop pair. } ) ( 13... Be6 { This is the old main line, but after } 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Nd5 $146 Bxd5 16. exd5 Qd6 17. f4 { the position is kind of unpleasant for Black. } ) 14. Bxc5 { The most dangerous move, intending to continue in a very concrete manner. White must play precisely, since he lacks a positional advantage due to their bad bishop on g2. } 14... Qxc5 15. Na4 $1 { White forces our queen off the active c5-square. } 15... Qc6 16. f4 a5 $1 { Stopping Qb4+ } 17. Qd3 { This is the most played move in the position. It introduces the idea of taking on e5 and playing Qa3+, so our next move is almost forced. } 17... b5 $1 { The point is now we can block a check with ...b4. } 18. Nc3 Qc5+ 19. Kh1 b4 $1 { [%cal Gc8a6]Now the game is very forced for the next few moves. } 20. fxe5 Qxe5 $1 ( 20... dxe5 $2 21. Nd5+ $146 Nxd5 $146 22. exd5 { We are not in time to play ...Ba6 because of d6+! and Black stands much worse } ) 21. Nd5+ Nxd5 22. exd5 Ba6 { We develop the bishop with a tempo intending to grab material. } 23. Qd2 Bxf1 $1 24. Re1 { White naturally tries to pick up our queen. } 24... Bxg2+ 25. Kxg2 Qxe1 26. Qxe1+ Kf8 $13 { We have a material advantage, but our pieces are not well-coordinated, so the position is around equal. Both sides need to be careful. A very important resource here for black is ...h5! In order to play ...Rh6. This way, the d6-pawn will not suffer. } * 

