1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 { This is the best move without a doubt, Nxc6 ideas can be quite uncomfortable in the g3 line. } ( 8... d6 { also thought of reccomending this move, trying to get us into Scheveningen territory, but White has the unpleasant plan } 9. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 10. Na4 $146 { As Carlsen showed against Rapport, this kind of position can be quite unpleasant. } ) ( 8... Bc5 { This is the most natural reaction, but as we said earlier Black faces some problems after } 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { The key move. According to the machine White's advantage is not too big, but our dark square bishop is bad and I think in practice it is not a good position. } 11... b5 12. e5 { The big point. Everything works for White. } 12... Nd7 $146 13. Nc3 $146 Nxe5 $146 14. Bf4 ) 9. Qxd4 Bc5 10. Bf4 $1 { The key idea that allows White to fight for the advantage. Queen retreats are less dangerous. } 10... d6 ( 10... Bxd4 $2 11. Bxc7 { is better than it looks for White. It is almost impossible to develop the bishop on c8 and after Na4 we will suffer a lot on the dark squares. } ) 11. Qd2 { We have already looked at 11. Qd1 and 11. Qd3 via transpositions. } 11... h6 $1 { We are going to be forced to play ...e5, so we should deny access to g5 to the White's bishop. } 12. Rad1 e5 13. Be3 { This is a big tabiya in the 6. g3 Taimanov. Many moves have been explored in different courses. I wanted to give something that is not so well explored, so that you can have many options. } 13... Bxe3 $5 { This move was thought to be quite bad, but Caruana resurrected the line in 2020 with a great win in over Tari. It is suggested by Khalifman, and it is also a perfectly good alternative to the line we are proposing. } 14. Qxe3 { This avoids creating any weaknesses, but it doesn't lead anywhere for White. } 14... Be6 15. h3 b5 { Clearly White has troubles on c2, so pushing the pawn to b4 makes sense. } 16. f4 O-O $133 17. fxe5 dxe5 18. Rxf6 b4 $5 { We can play this intermediate move. Taking on f6 is possible but dangerous. The idea with ...b4 is kicking the knight so we can take on f6 later and c2 is in the air as well. } * 

