1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, as } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 { This is the best move without a doubt, Nxc6 ideas can be quite uncomfortable in the g3 line. } ( 8... d6 { also thought of reccomending this move, trying to get us into Scheveningen territory, but White has the unpleasant plan } 9. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 10. Na4 $146 { As Carlsen showed against Rapport, this kind of position can be quite unpleasant. } ) ( 8... Bc5 { This is the most natural reaction, but as we said earlier Black faces some problems after } 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { The key move. According to the machine White's advantage is not too big, but our dark square bishop is bad and I think in practice it is not a good position. } 11... b5 12. e5 { The big point. Everything works for White. } 12... Nd7 $146 13. Nc3 $146 Nxe5 $146 14. Bf4 ) 9. Qxd4 Bc5 10. Bf4 $1 { The key idea that allows White to fight for the advantage. Queen retreats are less dangerous. } 10... d6 ( 10... Bxd4 $2 11. Bxc7 { is better than it looks for White. It is almost impossible to develop the bishop on c8 and after Na4 we will suffer a lot on the dark squares. } ) 11. Qd2 { We have already looked at 11. Qd1 and 11. Qd3 via transpositions. } 11... h6 $1 { We are going to be forced to play ...e5, so we should deny access to g5 to the White's bishop. } 12. Rad1 e5 13. Be3 { This is a big tabiya in the 6. g3 Taimanov. Many moves have been explored in different courses. I wanted to give something that is not so well explored, so that you can have many options. } 13... Bxe3 $5 { This move was thought to be quite bad, but Caruana resurrected the line in 2020 with a great win in over Tari. It is suggested by Khalifman, and it is also a perfectly good alternative to the line we are proposing. } 14. fxe3 $1 { The critical move, and once thought to be a refutation, because the only move that defends the d6-pawn, 14...Ke7, runs into Rxf6 and a big fork! But Caruana demonstrated that Black can actually sacrifice the d6-pawn. } 14... Be6 $1 15. Qxd6 Rc8 16. Qxc7 Rxc7 $13 { A very interesting position. The endgame is quite difficult to understand and it has many subtleties that are difficult to understand for both sides. Certainly a reasonable alternative if you do not like the main line proposed here. } * 

