[Black "15) 6.g3 (Alternative: 7...Bc5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Bc5 $5 { This is an interesting idea that is not so well known and that I also wanted to present to you in this course. ...Bc5 before taking on d4 has always been thought to be kind of dubious, but that's mainly due to the line } ( 7... Nf6 $146 8. O-O Bc5 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { , with a slight but persistent advantage for White. As we will see, playing ...Bc5 before allowing White to castle gives us some interesting possibilities! Although it probably doesn't fully equalize in the end, I think this line is worth having in your repertoire against the solid g3 line! } ) 8. Nb3 { This is a very natural move too. We get the small moral victory of avoiding the Nxc6 thematic idea that happens in the main line with ...Nf6 & ...O-O included. Now we get a complex game where all the pieces are on the board, something we should look forward to when playing this variation. } 8... Be7 9. Be3 { Delaying castling gives some options to White. } 9... Nf6 10. f4 d6 11. Qf3 { White can also make use of delaying castling and castle queenside. } 11... O-O 12. O-O-O Nd7 $133 { [%cal Ga8b8,Gb7b5]Again, a very interesting middlegame with chances for both sides. Black does not have many defenders on the kingisde, and with the bishop on d2 I would be quite afraid, but with the bishop on g2 I think White is quite slow, and we will get our counterplay going. The knight on d7 can be regrouped sometimes to c4 after ...b5. } * 

