1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Bc5 $5 { This is an interesting idea that is not so well known and that I also wanted to present to you in this course. ...Bc5 before taking on d4 has always been thought to be kind of dubious, but that's mainly due to the line } ( 7... Nf6 $146 8. O-O Bc5 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { , with a slight but persistent advantage for White. As we will see, playing ...Bc5 before allowing White to castle gives us some interesting possibilities! Although it probably doesn't fully equalize in the end, I think this line is worth having in your repertoire against the solid g3 line! } ) 8. Nb3 { This is a very natural move too. We get the small moral victory of avoiding the Nxc6 thematic idea that happens in the main line with ...Nf6 & ...O-O included. Now we get a complex game where all the pieces are on the board, something we should look forward to when playing this variation. } 8... Be7 9. O-O Nf6 10. f4 O-O 11. Be3 ( 11. e5 Ne8 $133 $146 { This does not bother Black at all, we are going to break with d6. } ) 11... d5 $5 ( 11... d6 { is more in Sicilian style, but I wanted to show this cool move too! Now that f4 has weakened White's position, accepting the sacrifice with exd5 is not very good, and } 12. e5 { leads to an acceptable French position for Black because the bishop is misplaced on g2. } ) 12. e5 Nd7 13. Ne2 Nb6 $13 { [%cal Gb6a4,Gb6c4,Gb7b5,Gc8d7,Gf7f6]With a big fight, White's goal in this kind of position is to play f5. That is not so easy to achieve in this position. Black's plan is to continue playing on the queenside and maybe attack the pawn chain with ...f6. } * 

