1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Bc5 $5 { This is an interesting idea that is not so well known and that I also wanted to present to you in this course. ...Bc5 before taking on d4 has always been thought to be kind of dubious, but that's mainly due to the line } ( 7... Nf6 $146 8. O-O Bc5 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { , with a slight but persistent advantage for White. As we will see, playing ...Bc5 before allowing White to castle gives us some interesting possibilities! Although it probably doesn't fully equalize in the end, I think this line is worth having in your repertoire against the solid g3 line! } ) 8. Be3 d6 { This is quite comfortable for Black. } 9. Qd2 Ne5 10. Nd1 Nf6 $133 { [%cal Ge5c4,Gb7b5,Ge8g8,Gf6g4]Already looks quite good for us, we have many active ideas, mainly on the queenside; for example, Black can play ...Nc4 to take the bishop pair or ...b5 to gain some space on the queenside. } * 

