1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Bc5 $5 { This is an interesting idea that is not so well known and that I also wanted to present to you in this course. ...Bc5 before taking on d4 has always been thought to be kind of dubious, but that's mainly due to the line } ( 7... Nf6 $146 8. O-O Bc5 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { , with a slight but persistent advantage for White. As we will see, playing ...Bc5 before allowing White to castle gives us some interesting possibilities! Although it probably doesn't fully equalize in the end, I think this line is worth having in your repertoire against the solid g3 line! } ) 8. Bf4 $5 { This looks like a blunder, but it actually leads to very sharp play! We should accept the challenge. } 8... Qb6 $1 9. Nf5 $5 { This is another curious idea suggested by the engine. It is typical of the Sicilian so we should check it. } 9... exf5 10. Nd5 Qa5+ 11. c3 d6 12. b4 Nxb4 13. cxb4 Bxb4+ 14. Nxb4 Qxb4+ 15. Bd2 Qd4 16. exf5 Qe5+ 17. Be3 ( 17. Qe2 Nf6 $146 { is also completely fine for us. } ) 17... Qc3+ { With a draw. We could also play on with ...Nf6, but there isn't much upside because White's strong bishops offer sufficient compensation. } * 

