1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Bc5 $5 { This is an interesting idea that is not so well known and that I also wanted to present to you in this course. ...Bc5 before taking on d4 has always been thought to be kind of dubious, but that's mainly due to the line } ( 7... Nf6 $146 8. O-O Bc5 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { , with a slight but persistent advantage for White. As we will see, playing ...Bc5 before allowing White to castle gives us some interesting possibilities! Although it probably doesn't fully equalize in the end, I think this line is worth having in your repertoire against the solid g3 line! } ) 8. Bf4 $5 { This looks like a blunder, but it actually leads to very sharp play! We should accept the challenge. } 8... Qb6 $1 9. Nxc6 Bxf2+ $1 10. Ke2 dxc6 11. Na4 Qd4 { To block the invasion of the white queen on d6. } 12. c3 Qxd1+ 13. Rhxd1 Ba7 14. Bc7 { This also looks dangerous and would be quite unpleasant to face in practice without any knowledge, but remain calm!!!!!!! } 14... Bd7 { We do not really have any problems. A nice defensive resource awaits. } 15. b4 { Trying to occupy the dark squares... } 15... c5 $1 16. Nxc5 Bc6 { [%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8]We have created a beautiful outpost for our bishop. Next, ...Nf6 and castling will leave us in a good position. Always consider giving back material when you are defending! } * 

