1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Bc5 $5 { This is an interesting idea that is not so well known and that I also wanted to present to you in this course. ...Bc5 before taking on d4 has always been thought to be kind of dubious, but that's mainly due to the line } ( 7... Nf6 $146 8. O-O Bc5 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { , with a slight but persistent advantage for White. As we will see, playing ...Bc5 before allowing White to castle gives us some interesting possibilities! Although it probably doesn't fully equalize in the end, I think this line is worth having in your repertoire against the solid g3 line! } ) 8. Bf4 $5 { This looks like a blunder, but it actually leads to very sharp play! We should accept the challenge. } 8... Qb6 $1 9. Nxc6 Bxf2+ $1 10. Ke2 dxc6 11. e5 { [%cal Bc3e4,Be4d6]Trying to infiltrate Black's camp with Ne4-Nd6. } 11... Ne7 { The knight is a very important defensive piece for us, the d5-square is quite important. } 12. Ne4 Bc5 13. b4 $1 { Very strong. White manages to open lines to fuel their attack. } 13... Qxb4 { We take the pawn which leads to a forcing line. } 14. Rb1 Qc4+ 15. Qd3 Qxd3+ 16. cxd3 Ba7 17. Nd6+ Kd7 18. Nxf7 Rf8 19. Nd6 b5 { [%cal Ge7d5,Ga7d4]White has compensation for the pawn, but once the knight comes to d5 and the bishop comes to d4 things can get ugly for him. } * 

