1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { g3 will never go out of fashion against the Taimanov. It is quite solid for White, and Bf4 can be an idea in some variations. } 6... a6 { It is important to start with this move, } ( 6... Nf6 $146 { gives White some extra Nb5 ideas. } ) 7. Bg2 Bc5 $5 { This is an interesting idea that is not so well known and that I also wanted to present to you in this course. ...Bc5 before taking on d4 has always been thought to be kind of dubious, but that's mainly due to the line } ( 7... Nf6 $146 8. O-O Bc5 9. Nxc6 $146 dxc6 10. Na4 $146 Ba7 11. c4 { , with a slight but persistent advantage for White. As we will see, playing ...Bc5 before allowing White to castle gives us some interesting possibilities! Although it probably doesn't fully equalize in the end, I think this line is worth having in your repertoire against the solid g3 line! } ) 8. Nxc6 dxc6 { We take with the d-pawn and in the near future play ...e5, reaching a familiar pawn structure where the c8-bishop has a life. } 9. Qe2 $1 { This modest-looking move is White's best try for an advantage. We still have some problems to solve due to our weak queenside. } 9... e5 10. Be3 Qa5 $1 { The engine favors White at lower depths, but it shifts to more modest evaluations after some thinking. To me, Black looks quite OK: we have managed to get ...e5 in and only concrete attempts can bother us. They are dangerous, but we are still quite OK. } 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. O-O-O ( 12. O-O Nf6 $146 { Black is not worse at all, and in the long run, our bishop is stronger and we have a plan of expansion in the queenside, so I think it is easier to play with Black. } ) 12... Nf6 13. Qd2 O-O $10 { [%cal Gc8e6,Gb7b5]The g3-pawn looks strange in this opposite castling position. } * 

