[White "6.Qd3: 7.Nxc6 #1"]
[Black "16) 6.Qd3  "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Qd3 { This is a tricky sideline. In general, all queen moves along the third rank in the opening or early middlegame are quite effective against the Taimanov because the Qg3 idea is difficult for Black to deal with. } 6... Nf6 7. Nxc6 dxc6 $5 { Generally, we do not choose this recapture in the Taimanov, but here is one of the few exceptions where this recapture is very playable. Plans with f4 & e5 lose strength with the queen on d3. It makes much more sense. } ( 7... bxc6 8. Qg3 Qxg3 9. hxg3 d5 10. Bd3 Bd6 { I think this endgame is also quite decent, Black is quite solid and has an improved version over some endgames that arise in the 7.Qf3 main line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). But 7...dxc6 is more ambitious. } ) 8. f4 { This also looks decent, but if we play actively we should not have any problems. } 8... e5 9. f5 b5 $1 { We play for counterplay. } 10. Be2 b4 $1 { Black can play more calmly, but White is not fully coordinated and it makes sense to bother White. } 11. Nd1 Bb7 12. O-O c5 13. Nf2 c4 $1 { Black stands completely fine. } * 

