1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Qd3 { This is a tricky sideline. In general, all queen moves along the third rank in the opening or early middlegame are quite effective against the Taimanov because the Qg3 idea is difficult for Black to deal with. } 6... Nf6 7. Nxc6 dxc6 $5 { Generally, we do not choose this recapture in the Taimanov, but here is one of the few exceptions where this recapture is very playable. Plans with f4 & e5 lose strength with the queen on d3. It makes much more sense. } ( 7... bxc6 8. Qg3 Qxg3 9. hxg3 d5 10. Bd3 Bd6 { I think this endgame is also quite decent, Black is quite solid and has an improved version over some endgames that arise in the 7.Qf3 main line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). But 7...dxc6 is more ambitious. } ) 8. Qg3 { The logical continuation of White's play. Other moves do not make much sense. } 8... e5 $5 ( 8... Qxg3 9. hxg3 e5 { and actually, it's quite normal to exchange queens, as White's queen appears more active than Black's one on c7. But appearances can be deceiving! } ) 9. Bc4 b5 $1 { We cannot allow White to gain access to its best square so easily. White is forced to leave the a2-g8 diagonal. } 10. Bd3 Be6 11. O-O g6 $1 { [%cal Gf6h5]The key move. Now White's queen on g3 is actually kind of misplaced! White cannot open lines with f3 because of ...Nh5, and we are in a comfortable position. } 12. Qh4 $6 Be7 13. Bg5 Nh5 $1 { This already gives Black an initiative because of our control of the dark squares. } * 

