1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Qd3 { This is a tricky sideline. In general, all queen moves along the third rank in the opening or early middlegame are quite effective against the Taimanov because the Qg3 idea is difficult for Black to deal with. } 6... Nf6 7. Bg5 { We should also take at this move because it has been played several times by Bartel (although mainly in rapid). It looks active, but it's not very threatening. } 7... a6 8. O-O-O h6 $1 { Forcing White to make a difficult decision. } 9. Bxf6 gxf6 { [%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7,Gf8e7]Black has the best Classical Sicilian in the World! The queen on d3 is misplaced, and White has not played useful moves like f4 & Kb1. } * 

