1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Qd3 { This is a tricky sideline. In general, all queen moves along the third rank in the opening or early middlegame are quite effective against the Taimanov because the Qg3 idea is difficult for Black to deal with. } 6... Nf6 7. Ndb5 { This is the main line by a large margin, but we should also look at Nxc6, which is always kind of playable. } 7... Qb8 8. Qg3 d6 9. Be3 { The only sensible move, which allows White's knight to safely retreat to d4. } ( 9. Bf4 $2 { fails to } 9... Nh5 $17 $146 ) 9... a6 10. Nd4 { The main tabiya in the 6.Qd3 complex. Our next move is crucial and something we should always keep in mind in these Sicilian positions where the queen is on g3. } 10... h5 $1 { Not only quite nice but also objectively best! } 11. Nf3 { White can also stop ...h4 like this, although with such passive play it is very difficult to fight for an advantage. } 11... b5 12. Bd3 Bb7 13. O-O Qc7 { Quite fine for us. } 14. Rad1 h4 $1 15. Nxh4 Ne5 $1 { [%cal Gf6g4,Gf8e7]A nice positional idea when Black is just too active. } 16. Nf3 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 b4 18. Ne2 d5 $1 { [%csl Rh2]And suddenly the bishop on b7 becomes a very strong piece after opening that main diagonal. } * 

