1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Qd3 { This is a tricky sideline. In general, all queen moves along the third rank in the opening or early middlegame are quite effective against the Taimanov because the Qg3 idea is difficult for Black to deal with. } 6... Nf6 7. Ndb5 { This is the main line by a large margin, but we should also look at Nxc6, which is always kind of playable. } 7... Qb8 8. Qg3 d6 9. Be3 { The only sensible move, which allows White's knight to safely retreat to d4. } ( 9. Bf4 $2 { fails to } 9... Nh5 $17 $146 ) 9... a6 10. Nd4 { The main tabiya in the 6.Qd3 complex. Our next move is crucial and something we should always keep in mind in these Sicilian positions where the queen is on g3. } 10... h5 $1 { Not only quite nice but also objectively best! } 11. h4 { This is a prudent reaction, but it also gives us the g4-square. } 11... Ng4 $1 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bd2 { Now, in the only game that has reached this position, Black chose to play it safe with d5, which is perfectly reasonable and equalizes the position. but we can also accept the challenge and capture the poisoned pawn. } 13... Qxb2 14. Rb1 Qa3 ( 14... Qxc2 $2 15. Bd3 { is not what we want! } ) 15. Be2 d5 $1 { The pawn on g4 is not so important: we strike in the center and want to develop our bishop on f6. } 16. Rb8 $4 Bd6 17. Rxa8 Bxg3 18. Rxc8+ Ke7 19. Rxh8 Nxf2 $19 { Black has a winning attack. } * 

