1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Re1 O-O { I prefer to keep things simple and play in the same way we play against 9.Qe2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 10. Nf3 { White threatens e5. Our reaction is the same as against 9.Qe2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN): we stop it mechanically! } 10... d6 $1 { [%cal Rd6e5]} 11. Nbd4 e5 $1 { I like this reaction, White's pieces are not well-placed to fight for the d5-square. } 12. Nb3 $6 h6 $15 { [%cal Gc8e6,Ga7a6,Gb7b5][%csl Ga7,Ga8]This would already be a very comfortable version of the Najdorf for Black: neither knight can fight for the d5-square. } * 

