1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Re1 O-O { I prefer to keep things simple and play in the same way we play against 9.Qe2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } 10. Nf3 { White threatens e5. Our reaction is the same as against 9.Qe2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN): we stop it mechanically! } 10... d6 $1 { [%cal Rd6e5]} 11. c4 { Playing for a Maroczy bind is the most critical attempt. } 11... Ne5 $5 { The same move as against the 9.Qe2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) main line. The doubled pawns control a lot of squares in case White takes. } 12. b3 ( 12. Nxe5 $146 dxe5 $37 { Now the d-file gets opened, and we have a fantastic square on d4 for our minor pieces or even the rook. } ) 12... a6 13. Nc3 Qc7 { [%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Gb7b5]As Nxe5 does not really bother us, we can keep developing and not make a decision about taking on d3 yet. Black has a very healthy Sicilian position and a very good version of the Hedgehog, because White's set-up does not have attacking potential with the pawn on f2. } * 

