1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. b3 { White signals he wants to develop their bishop to the more promising a1-h8 diagonal. We can counterbalance this plan in a nice way, by blocking the diagonal! } 9... a6 10. Nxc6 dxc6 $1 11. Nd4 e5 $1 { Blocking the diagonal with tempo! } 12. Nf5 $2 { Not possible. } 12... Bxf5 13. exf5 e4 $17 { [%cal Gb8e5]f5 falls after ...Qe5. } * 

