1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. f4 { This also prepares e5, but it is a little bit imprecise compared to Qe2 because it does not defend the e4-pawn (it is important as we will see!), and also it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal. } 9... a6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nd4 $6 { This would lead to an advantage with the pawn on f2 and the queen on e2, but here Black has a nice resource. } 11... c5 12. Nf3 c4 $1 { The key! We get a nice central pawn. } 13. Bxc4 Nxe4 $15 { [%cal Gd7d5,Gb8b6][%csl Rg1]} * 

