1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. f4 { Very natural, trying to immediately expand in the center. } 10... a6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nd4 $6 { This would be the best move with the king on h1, but now it runs into tactical problems. } 12... Qb6 $1 13. Be3 ( 13. c3 $2 c5 $19 ) 13... Bc5 14. c3 a5 $1 { [%cal Gc8a6]Black has a very comfortable game, White is overextended. } * 

