1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. f4 { Very natural, trying to immediately expand in the center. } 10... a6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Nc3 d5 { This typical Taimanov position is fine for Black. The main immediate plan is to try to exchange the bishop on d3, with moves like ...a5, ...Ba6 or/and ...Nd7-Nc5. } 13. e5 Nd7 14. Rf3 $6 f5 $1 { This stops White's attack on its tracks. } 15. exf6 Nxf6 { [%cal Ge7d6,Ga8a7,Ga7e7]Black is just much better. The idea ...Bd6, ...Ra7, ...e7-e5 looks quite strong! } * 

