1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. Nf3 { White tries to take advantage of the fact that we have been avoiding a6. } 10... d6 { We have to stop e5. } 11. Bg5 { This also looks natural, but it does not mesh so well with Nf3. } 11... h6 12. Bh4 a6 { Now it's time to expel White's knight. } 13. Nbd4 e5 $1 { An unexpected and strong reaction: White's pieces are suddenly in awkward positions. } 14. Nf5 $4 Bxf5 15. exf5 d5 $19 { [%cal Ge5e4][%csl Rd3,Rf3]The position is just winning for Black, White loses a piece. } * 

