1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. Nf3 { White tries to take advantage of the fact that we have been avoiding a6. } 10... d6 { We have to stop e5. } 11. c4 Ne5 $1 { I really like this idea, that you should keep in mind: the central doubled pawns are usually not a weakness in the Sicilian. } 12. Bc2 { This allows Black to immediately achieve the Hedgehog liberating break } 12... a6 13. Nc3 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 b5 $37 { White will probably take on b5 and play b4 to stop ...b4 from Black. Then a plan is to play ...Bb7, ...Rc8 and ...Nd7! } * 

