1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. Bg5 { This is actually a novelty, but it looks very natural and it is the first choice of the machine. } 10... h6 { This move does not hurt us and can help us avoid back-rank issues. } 11. Bh4 d6 { Stopping e5 is necessary. } ( 11... a6 12. Nxc6 $146 bxc6 13. e5 { is a trick we should be aware of. } 13... axb5 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qg4+ Kh8 17. Qh4 Kg7 18. Rae1 { Black will not survive this attack. } ) 12. f4 e5 $1 { A strong move, fighting for the center. } 13. fxe5 dxe5 { It looks quite scary for us, with so little pieces on the kingside, but it holds, and we have a very good pawn structure. } 14. Nf5 { The most critical idea, forcing us to take White's knight. } 14... Bxf5 15. Rxf5 a6 16. Bxf6 ( 16. Nc3 $2 $146 Nd4 $19 $146 { is an important point! The fork wins us material. } ) 16... Bxf6 17. Rxf6 $1 { White is going to lose the exchange no matter what, so he tries to weaken our pawn structure. } 17... axb5 $13 { An ambitious try: ...gxf6 would probably lead to some kind of perpetual check. We are going to push ...b4 next, fixing White's pawns on the queenside, and we should be OK with a good knight against a relatively weak bishop. } * 

