1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. c4 { This has been tried in two games. } 10... a6 11. Nxc6 dxc6 $1 { Now that the pawn is on c4, ...bxc6 does not make so much sense. } 12. Nd4 $6 ( 12. Nc3 $146 { This is better, although after } 12... e5 { Black don't have no problems. } ) 12... e5 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. exf5 { Now Black tried to force things with } 14... h6 $1 { I prefer playing prophylactically by avoiding Bg5 and slowing down possible g4-g5 attacks. Next we will put the bishop on c5 and will enjoy an advantage. This kind of position can easily arise in this variation, and the key point is we have a safe king and White's bishops are quite passive at the moment. A tactical point behind our play awaits... } ( 14... e4 { in the only game that has reached this position, but actually there is no need for that and we can play slowly. } ) 15. Re1 Bc5 16. Qxe5 $2 Bxf2+ $19 * 

