1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. Kh1 { This is what Vidit chose in one of the first games in this variation. Trying to get f4 in optimal conditions, but it is a tad slow. } 10... d5 $5 { This is the easiest solution in this position. } 11. e5 Nd7 12. f4 Nc5 { Now we will take on d3 and play ...f6 next, with a fantastic French-like position. } 13. Bxh7+ { The only dangerous try, but we can easily defend. } 13... Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Rf3 f6 $1 16. Rh3 Ne4 { White has nothing more than a perpetual at best. He only has two pieces attacking. } * 

