1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. Nxc6 $5 { A recent try by Nihal, also against Bacrot! This means we should take it seriously. White captures on c6 unprovoked and aims to develop the bishop from c1 to its best square, b2, without distractions. } 10... bxc6 11. Nd4 c5 12. Nf3 Bb7 13. e5 { This looks critical, but we are ready for it. } 13... Ng4 { [%cal Gb7f3]We threaten the pawn on e5. } 14. Be4 f6 $1 { Breaking White's center and allowing our knight to escape. } 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 { Black has no problems at all. A possible plan is ...Nd5 followed by ...Nf4. If White stops it by playing c4, then ...Ne4 followed by ...d5 is very interesting. } * 

