1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ncb5 Qb8 7. Bd3 { This is White's idea. It turns out this move was not possible on move 6, because the knight was hanging, but now it isn't! } 7... Nf6 $5 { I think this is a reasonable solution that is yet not so well explored. We argue that playing ...a6 is not necessary at the moment, as the knight on b5 is not really threatening our position, so we continue developing the kingside first. } 8. O-O Be7 { Now White has some options, the position is not of a forced nature. } 9. Qe2 { Maybe the most natural move, and was also played by Vidit against Bacrot in the World Cup. That game actually contributed a lot to popularizing Ncb5, and shortly after Nihal Sarin also played it against Bacrot. } 9... O-O { This is the main tabiya of the 6.Ncb5 variation. } 10. Nxc6 $5 { A recent try by Nihal, also against Bacrot! This means we should take it seriously. White captures on c6 unprovoked and aims to develop the bishop from c1 to its best square, b2, without distractions. } 10... bxc6 11. Nd4 c5 12. Nf3 Bb7 13. b3 { The move played by Nihal. } 13... d5 { Bacrot also got an interesting game after the more restrained 13...d6. This is more concrete, and Black is perfectly fine. I also like to surprise our opponents whenever possible! } 14. e5 c4 $5 { I could not resist showing this fancy (but typical!) idea by Stockfish. The point is opening the bishop on b7 and getting active squares for our pieces will more than compensate for the pawn deficit. } ( 14... Nd7 $146 15. Bg5 Qd8 { is also completely possible. } 16. a4 ) 15. bxc4 dxc4 16. Bxc4 Ne4 $45 { [%cal Gb8c7,Ga8c8,Gb7g2,Yc4d3,Ge4c5][%csl Yc2]Black has very nice compensation. The bishop on c4 is unstable, and if it retreats to d3 or b3 we can hit it with ...Nc5. The heavy artillery shall move to the c-file. } * 

