1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. a3 a6 7. Nxc6 $5 { This dangerous try was given by Miguel Santos in his fantastic Open Sicilian course. It is quite dangerous, and typical Taimanov play can quickly lead to bad positions, so we should be careful. Actually, I believe there is only one clear equalizer against this line, and it was already shown in his repertoire! } ( 7. f4 { This transposes to 6.f4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) ( 7. Be3 { This transposes to 6.Be3. } ) 7... bxc6 { The most reliable move, in accordance with our reaction to most of these early Nxc6 moves. } ( 7... dxc6 { Better than 7...bxc6 and quite playable, but it is not the best version of this pawn structure for us. } 8. Be3 $2 { There are other moves, but this looks like the most promising to me. } 8... b5 9. Qf3 e5 10. g4 $2 $36 { Black has still an acceptable position, but it looks very easy to play with White. } ) 8. Qg4 { White develops the queen to an active square and tries to exchange queens with Qg3. } 8... Nf6 9. Qg3 Qxg3 { We cannot avoid a queen exchange. } ( 9... e5 $2 10. Be2 g6 $2 11. f4 $16 { highly dangerous for Black. } ) 10. hxg3 d5 11. exd5 $6 cxd5 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gf8d6,Ge8e7,Ga8b8,Gh8c8]It is a positional mistake for White to release the tension in the center. It makes our play very easy: we will try to carefully complete development and push our central pawns. We also have good files for our rooks on the queenside. } * 

