1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. a3 a6 7. Nxc6 $5 { This dangerous try was given by Miguel Santos in his fantastic Open Sicilian course. It is quite dangerous, and typical Taimanov play can quickly lead to bad positions, so we should be careful. Actually, I believe there is only one clear equalizer against this line, and it was already shown in his repertoire! } ( 7. f4 { This transposes to 6.f4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) ( 7. Be3 { This transposes to 6.Be3. } ) 7... bxc6 { The most reliable move, in accordance with our reaction to most of these early Nxc6 moves. } ( 7... dxc6 { Better than 7...bxc6 and quite playable, but it is not the best version of this pawn structure for us. } 8. Be3 $2 { There are other moves, but this looks like the most promising to me. } 8... b5 9. Qf3 e5 10. g4 $2 $36 { Black has still an acceptable position, but it looks very easy to play with White. } ) 8. Qg4 { White develops the queen to an active square and tries to exchange queens with Qg3. } 8... Nf6 9. Qg3 Qxg3 { We cannot avoid a queen exchange. } ( 9... e5 $2 10. Be2 g6 $2 11. f4 $16 { highly dangerous for Black. } ) 10. hxg3 d5 11. Bd3 { The most natural move, developing the bishop to a good square while defending the pawn. } 11... Bd6 $1 { This is arguably the most important move in the entire line for us! From d6, we avoid White's most natural plan, which consists of playing f3-g4 and usually grants him a comfortable edge. } 12. f4 { Quite natural, but not very dangerous: White significantly weakens the g3-pawn and we can counterattack on the center. } 12... e5 $1 13. exd5 { White has nothing better than to liquidate tension. } 13... cxd5 14. fxe5 Bxe5 15. Bf4 Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 O-O { [%cal Gf8e8,Gc8d7]The bishop pair is compensated by our better pawn structure and dominance on the light squares. The endgame is very probable to end in a draw after White exchanges the d3-bishop on e4 after Ne4+ at some moment. } * 

