1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. a3 a6 7. Nxc6 $5 { This dangerous try was given by Miguel Santos in his fantastic Open Sicilian course. It is quite dangerous, and typical Taimanov play can quickly lead to bad positions, so we should be careful. Actually, I believe there is only one clear equalizer against this line, and it was already shown in his repertoire! } ( 7. f4 { This transposes to 6.f4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) ( 7. Be3 { This transposes to 6.Be3. } ) 7... bxc6 { The most reliable move, in accordance with our reaction to most of these early Nxc6 moves. } ( 7... dxc6 { Better than 7...bxc6 and quite playable, but it is not the best version of this pawn structure for us. } 8. Be3 $2 { There are other moves, but this looks like the most promising to me. } 8... b5 9. Qf3 e5 10. g4 $2 $36 { Black has still an acceptable position, but it looks very easy to play with White. } ) 8. Qg4 { White develops the queen to an active square and tries to exchange queens with Qg3. } 8... Nf6 9. Qg3 Qxg3 { We cannot avoid a queen exchange. } ( 9... e5 $2 10. Be2 g6 $2 11. f4 $16 { highly dangerous for Black. } ) 10. hxg3 d5 11. Bd3 { The most natural move, developing the bishop to a good square while defending the pawn. } 11... Bd6 $1 { This is arguably the most important move in the entire line for us! From d6, we avoid White's most natural plan, which consists of playing f3-g4 and usually grants him a comfortable edge. } 12. Bf4 $1 { The most critical move, also suggested by Santos. If we exchange White gets another pawn in the center, and if we play 12...e5, which seems very natural and is actually our choice, we slightly weaken the d5 light square. White will try to play on the light squares with this move. } 12... e5 { The most ambitious and the move that leads to clear-cut equality. } ( 12... Bxf4 13. gxf4 a5 { is also playable if you want to cut the theory, but I am not sure Black has equalizes completely now that White has more pawns controlling the center. } 14. f3 Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. O-O-O $14 ) 13. Bg5 Be6 { This is technically a novelty, it was already given by Santos in his 1.e4 course! It is a very natural one: we should not weaken the light squares in the center with 13...d4 unprovoked. } ( 13... d4 $2 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Na4 $146 Be6 16. f3 c5 17. b3 $16 ) 14. exd5 { In general, we are happy to see this move happen because now our center is more mobile. White usually has a concrete idea in mind when they play this kind of move. } 14... cxd5 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. O-O-O Bc5 $1 { A very important theme that appears numerous times in this line is that White finds it awkward to defend the f2-pawn. } 17. Rhf1 $6 { Too passive. } 17... Ke7 $15 { We have a very strong pawn center and the bishop pair. } * 

