k has equalizes completely now that White has more pawns controlling the center. } 14. f3 Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. O-O-O $14 ) 13. Bg5 Be6 { This is technically a novelty, it was already given by Santos in his 1.e4 course! It is a very natural one: we should not weaken the light squares in the center with 13...d4 unprovoked. } ( 13... d4 $2 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Na4 $146 Be6 16. f3 c5 17. b3 $16 ) 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. O-O-O Bc5 $1 { We have seen this move already in other lines. The pawn on f2 is on a dark square, and the dark squares are very weak after the move 14.Bxf6 } 16. f3 h5 $5 { There are other approaches, like leaving the pawn on h6, but even this aggressive pawn advance is possible. It looks like the pawn falls... } 17. g4 h4 18. g3 h3 19. Rh2 { White's pieces are now distracted and Black is fine. } 19... Bd4 20. Ne2 $2 { This feels very natural, but White is almost losing. } 20... Be3+ 21. Kb1 dxe4 $1 22. Bxe4 Rd8 $1 23. Bxc6+ Ke7 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 { [%cal Gd8d1][%csl Gh3]An enormous initiative in the endgame. White needs to avoid mate with } 25. Nc3 $146 { , after which we defend the pawn on h3 and stand nearly winning because the pawn is very strong, and the bishops can support it. } * 

