k has equalizes completely now that White has more pawns controlling the center. } 14. f3 Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. O-O-O $14 ) 13. Bg5 Be6 { This is technically a novelty, it was already given by Santos in his 1.e4 course! It is a very natural one: we should not weaken the light squares in the center with 13...d4 unprovoked. } ( 13... d4 $2 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Na4 $146 Be6 16. f3 c5 17. b3 $16 ) 14. f4 $1 { The most critical move. White continues to play actively and puts us under pressure. } 14... d4 $1 { Now that there is a lot of tension in the center this advance gains strength. } ( 14... exf4 { This should equalize in the end, but it leads to dry play. } ) ( 14... exf4 { This should equalize in the end, but it leads to dry play. } ) 15. Na4 exf4 { Now we have to be ready for both captures: both are decent and testing! } 16. gxf4 Ng4 $1 { A strong move, getting out of e5 and improving the knight to better squares. } 17. e5 Be7 $1 { Now exchanging the dark-squared bishops is not bad, the bishop on g5 is becoming quite unpleasant, and we gain access to the e3-square. } 18. Bxe7 Kxe7 19. Be4 Ne3 20. Nc5 Bd5 $133 { Both sides have strong positions, so the position is complex and around equal. } * 

