k has equalizes completely now that White has more pawns controlling the center. } 14. f3 Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. O-O-O $14 ) 13. Bg5 Be6 { This is technically a novelty, it was already given by Santos in his 1.e4 course! It is a very natural one: we should not weaken the light squares in the center with 13...d4 unprovoked. } ( 13... d4 $2 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Na4 $146 Be6 16. f3 c5 17. b3 $16 ) 14. f4 $1 { The most critical move. White continues to play actively and puts us under pressure. } 14... d4 $1 { Now that there is a lot of tension in the center this advance gains strength. } ( 14... exf4 { This should equalize in the end, but it leads to dry play. } ) ( 14... exf4 { This should equalize in the end, but it leads to dry play. } ) 15. Na4 exf4 { Now we have to be ready for both captures: both are decent and testing! } 16. gxf4 Ng4 $1 { A strong move, getting out of e5 and improving the knight to better squares. } 17. f5 f6 $1 { [%cal Ge6c4][%csl Yc4]Another key move to remember! We need the bishop on the g8-a2 diagonal to control the weak white squares. } 18. Bd2 Bf7 19. Bb4 $1 { White insists on exchanging dark-squared bishops on their own terms. } 19... Ke7 20. Be2 Ne3 21. Kd2 { We have to be careful now, because White wants to remove support from our e3-knight with c3. We have to play very energetic chess. } 21... a5 $1 22. Bc5 $5 { The main move suggested by Santos, which still forces us to make a couple of precise moves and correctly evaluate a tricky position. } 22... Bxc5 23. Nxc5 Rhb8 $1 { Note that now } 24. b4 $5 { White keeps putting pressure. Now he sacrificies a pawn, but his idea is that he gets the a-file for his rooks. We should still take the pawn; the rook is not so scary, and a pawn is a pawn is a pawn is a pawn is a PAWN! } ( 24. Rab1 { fails to . } ) 24... axb4 25. axb4 Rxa1 26. Rxa1 Rxb4 27. Ra7+ Ke8 28. Nb7 $5 { The last try White has. The check on a8 leads to an immediate repetition. } 28... Bc4 $1 { Getting the bishop on c4 out of trouble. } 29. Nd6+ Kf8 { Santos already arrived at this position in his course! I still think this is best play and the game ends in a logical draw. } 30. Ra8+ Ke7 31. Nxc4 Nxc4+ 32. Bxc4 Rxc4 33. Ra7+ Kf8 $10 * 

