k has equalizes completely now that White has more pawns controlling the center. } 14. f3 Ba6 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. O-O-O $14 ) 13. Bg5 Be6 { This is technically a novelty, it was already given by Santos in his 1.e4 course! It is a very natural one: we should not weaken the light squares in the center with 13...d4 unprovoked. } ( 13... d4 $2 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Na4 $146 Be6 16. f3 c5 17. b3 $16 ) 14. f4 $1 { The most critical move. White continues to play actively and puts us under pressure. } 14... d4 $1 { Now that there is a lot of tension in the center this advance gains strength. } ( 14... exf4 { This should equalize in the end, but it leads to dry play. } ) ( 14... exf4 { This should equalize in the end, but it leads to dry play. } ) 15. Na4 exf4 { Now we have to be ready for both captures: both are decent and testing! } 16. Bxf4 Be7 $1 { It is of paramount importance to keep the bishops on the board: otherwise the c5 square would be very weak and our queenisde would begin to suffer. Also, we do not want to fix White's structure on the kingisde. } 17. Be5 { The critical move, threatening our pawn on d4 and leaving us only one option. } 17... c5 18. Nb6 { Bringing the knight to better squares like d5 or c4 makes sense too. } 18... Ra7 19. Nc4 $6 h6 $1 { [%cal Gf6g4]A strong move. We want to play ...Ng4, and then ....Bxg7, ...Rg8. The pawn on h7 will not be hanging. Black is more than fine. } * 

