1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 $36 { . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Be3 b5 8. Nxc6 { This is not too dangerous with the bishop on e3. Usually, when White wants to take on c6 in this line, they play Bd3, Qe2, & Nd5. } 8... Qxc6 9. Bd3 { In general, f4, Be3, & Bd3 do not fit together so well. } 9... Bb7 10. Qe2 Nf6 11. e5 Qxg2 $1 { We should not believe White! } 12. Qxg2 Bxg2 13. Rg1 Nd5 $1 { The key point, we are not losing a piece. } 14. Rxg2 Nxe3 $13 { White has some compensation, but only enough for equality. } * 

