1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 $36 { . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Be3 b5 8. Nxc6 { This is not too dangerous with the bishop on e3. Usually, when White wants to take on c6 in this line, they play Bd3, Qe2, & Nd5. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Ba3 $1 { This strong typical resource has been played by none other than Ivanchuk. } 10. Bd4 $2 { This has been tried quite a bit, but it is very bad for White. } 10... Bxb2 $1 11. Nxb5 Bxa1 $1 12. Bxa1 axb5 13. Bxg7 Nf6 $1 14. Bxh8 ( 14. Bxf6 $2 Rg8 $19 ) 14... Nxe4 { White's position is full of weaknesses. The pawn on a2 is likely to fall soon, and the king on e1 could become vulnerable after we bring our bishop to the grand diagonal with ...Bb7. } * 

