1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 $36 { . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Be3 b5 8. Nxc6 { This is not too dangerous with the bishop on e3. Usually, when White wants to take on c6 in this line, they play Bd3, Qe2, & Nd5. } 8... Qxc6 9. Be2 Ba3 $1 { This strong typical resource has been played by none other than Ivanchuk. } 10. Na4 $5 { An interesting suggestion by Stockfish. It is kind of thematic against this ...Ba3 resource, although it has only been seen in practice once before. } 10... Qxe4 { This is an easy improvement over } ( 10... bxa4 { 11\. bxa3↑; ½-½ Neugebauer, M -Haba, P Austria, 2021. } ) 11. Qd4 { White's idea, otherwise he would lose material for nothing. } 11... Qxd4 12. Bxd4 Bf8 $1 { All the way back! There was no other way to defend the g7-pawn. } 13. Nb6 Rb8 14. Nxc8 Rxc8 15. a4 { White needs to open the queenside to generate counterplay. } 15... Nf6 16. axb5 axb5 17. Bxb5 Bd6 $13 { [%cal Ge8e7,Gc8b8,Gh8c8,Gd6c5,Gh7h6,Gg7g5][%csl Rf4]Black has sufficient play in the queenside as compensation for the bishop pair. After bringing the rooks to the queenside, we can also create weaknesses in the other flank with a ...h6 & ...g5 plan. White's bishop pair is not so strong. } * 

