1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 $36 { . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Be3 b5 8. Nb3 { This avoids the idea we have after 8.Bd3, but it isn't particularly threatening } 8... Bb7 9. Bd3 Na5 $5 { [%cal Ga5c4]This is thematic, but it is surprising to do it so soon. I like to get counterplay on the queenside as quickly as possible. } 10. Nxa5 Qxa5 11. O-O b4 $1 12. Nb1 Bc5 { Exchanging dark-squared bishops is almost always to our advantage. } 13. Qe2 Qb6 $10 { Black has no problems at all in this typical Taimanov position. } * 

