1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 $36 { . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Be2 Nxd4 { The easiest, not allowing White to take on c6 anymore. } 8. Qxd4 b5 9. Be3 Bb7 10. Bf3 Rc8 $1 { Developing the queenside first is a typical theme. } 11. a3 { White cannot castle long because of ...b4, so this move looks logical. } 11... Ne7 12. O-O-O Nc6 13. Qb6 { This is White's idea, Black's position looks a little cramped. } 13... Na5 $1 { This looks like a blunder, but tactics work out in our favor. } 14. Qxc7 Rxc7 15. Bb6 Rxc3 $1 16. Bxa5 Rc4 17. Rhe1 g5 $1 { A strong move, getting counterplay on the kingside. } 18. fxg5 h6 19. gxh6 Rxh6 { An easy novelty. } 20. h3 Rh4 $10 { [%cal Gb7e4]We get back our pawn with at least an equal endgame that I would prefer to play as Black with the central pawn mass. } * 

