1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 $36 { . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Be2 Nxd4 { The easiest, not allowing White to take on c6 anymore. } 8. Qxd4 b5 9. Be3 Bb7 10. O-O Rc8 { It is quite easy to remember this move because we play it against everything on move 10! } 11. a4 $5 { Although rarely played, this is maybe the most critical idea White has. } 11... b4 12. Na2 Bc5 $1 { We are not losing a pawn, and exchanging queens is good for us in this system. } 13. Qxg7 { This looks good for White, but our initiative proves to be substantial. } 13... Bxe3+ $1 14. Kh1 Qxc2 $1 15. Qxh8 $2 { Black gets a decisive attack here. } 15... Ke7 $1 { [%cal Gg8f6,Gc8g8][%csl Re2]} 16. Bf3 Nf6 17. Qg7 Rg8 18. Qh6 Bxe4 $19 { [%cal Ge4g2,Gf6e4][%csl Rg2]All of our pieces coordinate beautifully to deliver checkmate to White's king. } * 

