1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 $36 { . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Be2 Nxd4 { The easiest, not allowing White to take on c6 anymore. } 8. Qxd4 b5 9. Be3 Bb7 10. O-O Rc8 { It is quite easy to remember this move because we play it against everything on move 10! } 11. a4 $5 { Although rarely played, this is maybe the most critical idea White has. } 11... b4 12. Na2 Bc5 $1 { We are not losing a pawn, and exchanging queens is good for us in this system. } 13. Qxc5 Qxc5 14. Bxc5 Rxc5 15. Bd3 { This defends c2, but gives us time to defend b4. 15.Nxb4 does not win a pawn after 15...a5=. } 15... a5 16. Nc1 $1 { A good positional move, improving the knight to the b3-square. } 16... Rc8 $1 17. Nb3 Ra8 { [%cal Gg8e7,Ge7c6,Ge8e7,Gh8c8,Gb7a6]This may look passive for us, but we have managed to hold our position, and after developing the kingside, we will have a perfectly fine setup. It is not easy for White to make further progress on the kingside. } * 

