1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 $36 { . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nf3 { This is sometimes played by some lazy players who want to avoid theory. It cannot be good to move the centralized knight so soon. } 7... Bc5 8. Bd3 b5 9. Qe2 Nd4 $5 { There are alternatives, but one good move is enough against a sideline. } 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 $13 { [%cal Gc8b7,Ga8c8,Gg8e7]Black has a very comfortable Taimanov middlegame. } * 

