1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Be3 d5 9. Bd3 { Usually Bd3 and Be3 do not go so well together. } ( 9. Qf3 { transposes to 8.Qf3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 9... Nf6 10. O-O Be7 11. e5 Nd7 12. Qg4 g6 { White looks more active, but their attack is difficult to develop further, while we are going to initiate our play on the queenside with moves like ...a5 & ...Ba6. Black is fine in this kind of Taimanov position if White doesn't have anything very concrete, which he doesn't. } * 

