1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Qf3 { This is the most important independent move on move 8, apart from 8. Bd3, and has been tried by the likes of Cheparinov, Volokitin, and Adams. } 8... d5 9. Be3 Nf6 10. O-O-O Be7 11. g4 { Another tricky idea. Normally, we don't develop the bishop to b7 when White's king goes to the queenside, but here, it is the right choice because White has weakened the a8-h1 diagonal. } ( 11. Bd4 { transposes to 10.Bd4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 11... Bb7 $1 12. g5 dxe4 13. Qg3 Nd5 14. Nxe4 c5 $133 { [%cal Gc5c4]Our knight on c5 is strong and we can push try to push the c-pawn for counterplay. } * 

