1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Qf3 { This is the most important independent move on move 8, apart from 8. Bd3, and has been tried by the likes of Cheparinov, Volokitin, and Adams. } 8... d5 9. Be3 Nf6 10. Bd4 { The most critical move, White improves their bishop to a better square. } 10... Be7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Bd3 { We have to be quite careful here because White is playing in a very logical and principled way, and if we don't get immediate counterplay, we could find ourselves in a world of pain. } 12... Qb7 $1 { The b-file is the main source of counterplay. } ( 12... Bb7 $2 { stops our counterplay on the b-file, and Adams had a big advantage after } 13. Rhe1 $36 { ½-½ Adams, M - Villiers, T. } ) 13. e5 { The most concrete move. } 13... Nd7 14. Bxh7+ $5 { This looks dangerous, but we have sufficient defensive resources. } 14... Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Rd3 f6 $1 { Giving air to our king. } 17. Rh3 fxe5 18. fxe5 Qb4 $13 { Trying to bring our queen to the defense. The position is quite complex, but White has nothing better than a repetition and he is the one that has to search for it. } * 

