1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. Kh1 { A useful move for White in this line. } 10... Be7 11. Qf3 { 11.Qe2 transposes to 10.Qe2. } 11... O-O 12. Bd2 a5 $1 { Trying to exchange White's best bishop with ...Ba6. White would prefer to have the queen on e2 here. White can try to go for a direct attack, but we have sufficient resources. } 13. e5 Nd7 14. Qh5 f5 $1 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Qe2 Bd7 $15 { [%cal Ga8e8,Gf8f7,Ge7d6][%csl Of4]This would not be so good if White had played with b3 & Bb2, but here we can go for the ...e5 push and we are even better. } * 

