[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. e5 Nd7 11. Na4 { The first time we look at this idea. White wants to push c4 to make our pawn majority in the center less mobile. We always play the same move here, so it is quite easy to remember. } 11... Nb6 $1 12. Nxb6 Qxb6+ 13. Kh1 Be7 { Black has no problems in this kind of position. Our main plan is to exchange White's bishop on d3 with ...a5 & ...Ba6, and we can always stop any potential kingside initiative White might have with ...g6. } 14. f5 exf5 15. Bxf5 Bxf5 16. Rxf5 O-O $10 { Black had no problems, although he eventually lost. 1-0 Bocharov, I - Rublevsky, S Sochi, 2018. } * 

