1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. Qe2 { The most logical square for White's queen. } 10... Be7 { The main tabiya of the 6.f4-7.Nxc6 line. Now, Black has several decent moves. } 11. b3 { With this move, White signals their intentions to develop the bishop to b2. } 11... Bb7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Rae1 { White's setup looks quite harmonious, and if we give them a few moves, they can develop a dangerous attacking position after e5 and Qh5. The normal reaction would be to open the center with ...f6, but then both of White's bishops would be on very strong squares. Fortunately, we have a very strong response that has only been played in 2 of the 20 games that have reached this position. } 13... c5 $1 14. e5 c4 $1 { Black could also retreat, but here it is very easy for White to get into a very bad position. } 15. exf6 { This is better, but Black is comfortably better. } 15... cxd3 16. cxd3 Bxf6 $15 { [%csl Gb7,Gf6]} * 

