1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. Qe2 { The most logical square for White's queen. } 10... Be7 { The main tabiya of the 6.f4-7.Nxc6 line. Now, Black has several decent moves. } 11. Kh1 { A useful move in general. Black can easily equalize with normal moves like ...O-O, ...Bb7, and ...c5 because White's attack isn't very strong in these lines. However, I want to present a powerful novelty here. } 11... h5 { I like this move a lot. The idea is that after our knight goes to g4, we can sometimes sacrifice it after h3, because with the king on h1 and the open g1-a7 diagonal, we get a lot of play. } 12. Bd2 c5 $1 { Going after the d3-bishop, even with the king on e8! } 13. exd5 exd5 14. Rae1 Kf8 $37 { [%cal Ge7d6,Gc8b7,Gh5h4][%csl Yh1]A typical theme in this line. Black's attack is very dangerous. A simple move like ...h4 already poses many problems for White: if he answers with h3, we can improve our knight with ...Nh5-Ng3, while if he doesn't stop us, ...h3 becomes very unpleasant. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "6.f4 - 7.Nxc6 Main Line: 8.Bd3 / 9.O-O / 10.Qe2 #6"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.f4 - 7.Nxc6 Main Line: 8.Bd3 / 9.O-O / 10.Qe2 #6"]
[Black "20) 6.f4 - 7.Nxc6 Main Line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. Qe2 { The most logical square for White's queen. } 10... Be7 { The main tabiya of the 6.f4-7.Nxc6 line. Now, Black has several decent moves. } 11. Kh1 { A useful move in general. Black can easily equalize with normal moves like ...O-O, ...Bb7, and ...c5 because White's attack isn't very strong in these lines. However, I want to present a powerful novelty here. } 11... h5 { I like this move a lot. The idea is that after our knight goes to g4, we can sometimes sacrifice it after h3, because with the king on h1 and the open g1-a7 diagonal, we get a lot of play. } 12. Bd2 c5 $1 { Going after the d3-bishop, even with the king on e8! } 13. e5 Ng4 $37 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gc5c4][%csl Rh1]Black has a clear initiative against White's king. } * 

