1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. Qe2 { The most logical square for White's queen. } 10... Be7 { The main tabiya of the 6.f4-7.Nxc6 line. Now, Black has several decent moves. } 11. e5 Nd7 12. Na4 { We have already seen this typical idea. We have seen that ...c5-c4 is a big counterplay we have, so it makes sense for White to put a pawn on c4. But in reality we can get simple equality in many ways. The simplest to me looks... } 12... Nb6 $5 13. Nxb6 Qxb6+ 14. Kh1 c5 $1 15. c4 d4 { Black has a choice: he can play } ( 15... dxc4 { and get a more open game or just create a passed pawn with ...d4. It is clear that Black is fine in both cases. } ) * 

