1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. Qe2 { The most logical square for White's queen. } 10... Be7 { The main tabiya of the 6.f4-7.Nxc6 line. Now, Black has several decent moves. } 11. Bd2 c5 $1 { I like to immediately push our center, our main asset. } 12. b3 Bb7 $1 13. Rae1 { This was played by Carlsen in the game that made this antidote to 6.f4 very well-known. } 13... c4 $1 { Very strong. We free our pieces with this strong pawn sacrifice. } 14. bxc4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Rc8 { The point is White cannot really maintain their pawn advantage. To the naked eye, it would appear they still have the initiative. } 18. f5 Qxc4 19. fxe6 f6 $1 { It's an illusion: both the pawns on e6 and c2 are weak and we are going to recover one of them. } 20. c3 Bc5+ 21. Kh1 Qxe4 22. Rxe4 Ke7 $10 { [%cal Gh8d8,Gc8c6,Gd8d6]Black ain't worse! } * 

