[Black "20) 6.f4 - 7.Nxc6 Main Line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. Qe2 { The most logical square for White's queen. } 10... Be7 { The main tabiya of the 6.f4-7.Nxc6 line. Now, Black has several decent moves. } 11. Bd2 c5 $1 { I like to immediately push our center, our main asset. } 12. b3 Bb7 $1 13. exd5 exd5 14. Rae1 { At first glance, this looks unpleasant for Black because he cannot castle. But the good news is, we don't need to castle! } 14... Kf8 $1 { The king is not so badly placed on f8 and we have many improvement moves: ...Re8, ...h5, ...Bd6, and ...c4 is always in the air opening the b7-bishop. } 15. Nd1 h5 $5 ( 15... Bd6 16. Ne3 $146 Re8 $13 { Black was also completely fine and actually soon better in a complex fight in 1-0 Alexakis, D - Anand, B Belgrade, 2022. } ) 16. Ne3 c4 $1 { You should always be very attentive to this move. } 17. bxc4 Bc5 $1 { Black has very good counterplay, as some sample lines show. } 18. cxd5 Nxd5 19. Kh1 Re8 20. Bxa6 Ba8 $133 { Black gets material back on f4 with a great position. } * 

