1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. f4 { An old line. 6.f4 looks flexible and aggressive, supporting e5 or a pawn storm, but it weakens the g1-a7 diagonal too much, and we should be very happy to see it. } 6... a6 ( 6... Nxd4 $146 7. Qxd4 b6 { was an interesting suggestion by Pavlidis to confuse the White player, but it is now quite well-known and has lost some of its charm. One of the most dangerous setups for White is } 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Qf2 $2 { ↑ . White's position is very easy to play, and it's fairly clear that we would prefer the queenside pawns on a6 and b5 rather than a7 and b6. } ) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 { This is the most reliable move in my opinion, although } ( 7... Qxc6 { is also possible. } ) 8. Bd3 { The most natural move and the most commonly played one. } 8... d5 9. O-O ( 9. Be3 { transposes to 8.Be3. (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 9... Nf6 10. Qe2 { The most logical square for White's queen. } 10... Be7 { The main tabiya of the 6.f4-7.Nxc6 line. Now, Black has several decent moves. } 11. Bd2 c5 $1 { I like to immediately push our center, our main asset. } 12. b3 Bb7 $1 13. f5 { This move looks logical, as it puts more pressure on the e6-square now that the bishop has left c8 and our king is still on e8. } 13... c4 $1 { The same idea as in the 13. Rae1 line. } 14. bxc4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 O-O $1 { Putting our king to safety and defending our rook on a8. } 18. fxe6 Qb6+ { The point of our play. } 19. Kh1 Qxe6 20. Rae1 Qxe4 21. Rxe4 Bc5 { White's extra pawn is not very meaningful because it's doubled and isolated. We need to be aware of what happens if White tries to bring the king to defend this pawn, but we can manage to get sufficient counterplay. } 22. Bc3 { The move that was tried in the only game that reached this position. Black had no issues. } 22... f6 23. g4 Rfc8 24. Rd1 Rc6 25. Kg2 Rac8 26. h3 Bb6 $10 { ½-½ Frolyanov, D - Lazavik, D 2022. } * 

