1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Ndb5 { This is a funny line. White will win our queen in a few moves from now! But don't worry, we will get three minor pieces in return. } 6... Qb8 { Here most moves transpose to other lines, and the only line that does not transpose is nearly winning for us! } 7. Be3 ( 7. g3 a6 8. Nd4 $146 Qc7 { \- 6.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) ( 7. f4 a6 8. Nd4 $146 Qc7 { \- 6.f4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) ( 7. Be2 a6 8. Nd4 $146 Qc7 { \- 6.Be2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 7... a6 8. Bb6 $2 { This line enjoyed some popularity in the past, before the engines were so strong, but now it is quite clear that it is just terrible for White. } ( 8. Nd4 $146 Qc7 { -6.Be3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 8... axb5 9. Nxb5 Bb4+ $1 { Initiating a well-known defensive maneuver. } 10. c3 Ba5 11. Nc7+ Qxc7 $1 { No need to be greedy and give White an attack: we get three very strong pieces for the queen. } 12. Bxc7 Bxc7 13. Qg4 g6 $17 { [%cal Gh7h5,Gg8f6,Ge8f8,Gf8g7]White does not have any weaknesses to attack, and slowly but surely, we will complete development and launch an attack on White's king. Our pieces are much more useful than the queen. } * 

