1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Bg5 $5 { A strange idea that has been tried a couple of times by Paravyan, a dangerous theoretician. We don't need to know much, but it is useful to be aware of the pawn sacrifice in the main line. } 6... Nf6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Be7 { This is a very theoretical position with the bishop on e3, but the bishop on g5 is slightly misplaced here. We have many ...Nxe4 tricks, and we have an advantageous version of the Classical Sicilian because the pawn is still on d7. In practice, White usually continues in Rauzer style. } 9. f4 $2 ( 9. Kb1 b5 $133 { we can punish White. } ) 9... Nxd4 $1 10. Qxd4 h6 11. Bxf6 Qxf4+ $19 { Winning a clean pawn and the game. } * 

