1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Bg5 $5 { A strange idea that has been tried a couple of times by Paravyan, a dangerous theoretician. We don't need to know much, but it is useful to be aware of the pawn sacrifice in the main line. } 6... Nf6 7. Be2 a6 { We play our usual moves. Apparently, the idea of the line is to play... } 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qd4 { White appears to have some pressure over f6, } 9... Bd6 $1 ( 9... Be7 { would run into e5, and if we play } ) ( 9... e5 { ourselves, our structure in the center becomes a bit static, giving White a slight advantage. However, we have an elegant solution. } ) 10. Bxf6 { The critical move; otherwise, we play ...Be5, ...d5, ...Rb8 and get a very pleasant position. } 10... gxf6 11. Qxf6 Be5 12. Qf3 d5 { [%cal Ga8b8,Gh8g8]Black has full compensation for the pawn due to the strong bishop on e5 and control of the center. It's like we have a Benko Gambit on both flanks, with good semi-open lines for our rooks! White cannot immediately castle kingside because we can capture the pawn on h2, and castling queenside is too dangerous. A logical line that illustrates our resources is: } 13. g3 Rb8 14. Rb1 f5 $5 { Not the only way, but interesting. } 15. exf5 O-O $1 16. O-O Rxf5 17. Qd3 Qg7 $133 { [%cal Ge5c7,Ge6e5,Ge5e4]Black's position looks easier to play in practice. } * 

