1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Nb3 { A sideline that we have not yet covered. White's idea is to develop normally with Bd3, Be3, f4, O-O & Qf3 in some order and try to initiate a kingside attack. We do not really need to know concrete theory, but it is interesting to look at it to understand typical Taimanov middlegames. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. f4 b5 $5 { We can be a bit tricky and hold off on playing ...d6 for now. } 9. g4 $6 { Premature. We can immediately react in the center with } 9... d5 $1 10. exd5 Nb4 $1 { We do not mind sacrificing a pawn to keep opening the position. } 11. dxe6 Bxe6 $37 { [%cal Ga8d8][%csl Re1,Rg4]Black has a very dangerous initiative for the pawn. White's king is completely open. } * 

