1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Nb3 { A sideline that we have not yet covered. White's idea is to develop normally with Bd3, Be3, f4, O-O & Qf3 in some order and try to initiate a kingside attack. We do not really need to know concrete theory, but it is interesting to look at it to understand typical Taimanov middlegames. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. f4 b5 $5 { We can be a bit tricky and hold off on playing ...d6 for now. } 9. Be3 d6 { Now White has two main approaches: either try to castle kingside and prepare an attack in a slow, methodical way, or opt for a more direct approach with plans of castling queenside. } 10. g4 Bb7 11. g5 Nd7 { White has several options now, but in general, our plan remains the same: stay flexible with moves like ...Be7, ...Rc8, ...Nc5, ...Nb4, and try to generate counterplay on the queenside. Long castling is also a possibility in some lines. } 12. Qd2 Nc5 $5 { I like how GM Bologan handled this position. White cannot tolerate the knight on c5. } 13. Nxc5 dxc5 14. Qf2 Nb4 $133 { Black clearly has sufficient counterplay. ...Nb4 is quite uncomfortable for White to deal with in these lines. } * 

