1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Nb3 { A sideline that we have not yet covered. White's idea is to develop normally with Bd3, Be3, f4, O-O & Qf3 in some order and try to initiate a kingside attack. We do not really need to know concrete theory, but it is interesting to look at it to understand typical Taimanov middlegames. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. f4 b5 $5 { We can be a bit tricky and hold off on playing ...d6 for now. } 9. Be3 d6 { Now White has two main approaches: either try to castle kingside and prepare an attack in a slow, methodical way, or opt for a more direct approach with plans of castling queenside. } 10. O-O Be7 11. Qf3 O-O 12. g4 { White's main idea in this system. Otherwise their set-up does not make too much sense. } 12... g6 $5 { This is a rare move that makes a lot of sense. Now we are not so afraid of g5/f5 attacks, because the knight on g6 enables ...Nh5 as a defensive resource, stalling White's attack on the kingside. Once g5 is not possible, White's plan is actually not so clear! We will try to get typical counterplay on the queenside. } 13. g5 $6 Nh5 14. f5 { This is just too primitive. White leaves a lot of weak squares behind with their pawn advances, like Nh5 and Ne5. } 14... Ne5 15. Qh3 b4 $1 { Counterattacking. Before taking on f5, we force the knight off c3, so that it does not make contact with the d5-square. } 16. Ne2 exf5 17. exf5 Re8 $17 { [%cal Ge7d8][%csl Rg1]Activating another piece before striking White. They are just too overextended, and they do not have an attack to show for it: after removing the bishop from e7, White will have a very hard time not losing material. } * 

