1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Nb3 { A sideline that we have not yet covered. White's idea is to develop normally with Bd3, Be3, f4, O-O & Qf3 in some order and try to initiate a kingside attack. We do not really need to know concrete theory, but it is interesting to look at it to understand typical Taimanov middlegames. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. f4 b5 $5 { We can be a bit tricky and hold off on playing ...d6 for now. } 9. Be3 d6 { Now White has two main approaches: either try to castle kingside and prepare an attack in a slow, methodical way, or opt for a more direct approach with plans of castling queenside. } 10. O-O Be7 11. Qf3 O-O 12. g4 { White's main idea in this system. Otherwise their set-up does not make too much sense. } 12... g6 $5 { This is a rare move that makes a lot of sense. Now we are not so afraid of g5/f5 attacks, because the knight on g6 enables ...Nh5 as a defensive resource, stalling White's attack on the kingside. Once g5 is not possible, White's plan is actually not so clear! We will try to get typical counterplay on the queenside. } 13. Rae1 b4 { There are other possibilities, but this looks very natural. } 14. Na4 Bb7 15. Bb6 { This is not very problematic: we can simply move the queen. } 15... Qd7 16. Be3 Rae8 $5 { We do not take the draw and play on. The bishop can go to d8 next. After that, with all of the pieces well placed, we will try to strike in the center either with ...e5 or ...d5. Black's more than fine. } * 

