1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Nb3 { A sideline that we have not yet covered. White's idea is to develop normally with Bd3, Be3, f4, O-O & Qf3 in some order and try to initiate a kingside attack. We do not really need to know concrete theory, but it is interesting to look at it to understand typical Taimanov middlegames. } 6... a6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. f4 b5 $5 { We can be a bit tricky and hold off on playing ...d6 for now. } 9. Be3 d6 { Now White has two main approaches: either try to castle kingside and prepare an attack in a slow, methodical way, or opt for a more direct approach with plans of castling queenside. } 10. O-O Be7 11. Qf3 O-O 12. g4 { White's main idea in this system. Otherwise their set-up does not make too much sense. } 12... g6 $5 { This is a rare move that makes a lot of sense. Now we are not so afraid of g5/f5 attacks, because the knight on g6 enables ...Nh5 as a defensive resource, stalling White's attack on the kingside. Once g5 is not possible, White's plan is actually not so clear! We will try to get typical counterplay on the queenside. } 13. Rae1 b4 { There are other possibilities, but this looks very natural. } 14. Na4 Bb7 15. Qh3 Rae8 $37 { Getting out of Nb6 ideas. White still does not have a clear breakthrough on the kingside. We have a lot of possible ideas, but the main one is pushing ...d5 and opening the center. ...Nb8-Nbd7 can be a nice regrouping before doing so, controlling the b6-square and leaving more room for the b7-bishop. } * 

