1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nb5 { This is just too slow. } 6... e5 7. Be3 Nf6 8. N1c3 a6 9. Na3 { This has actually transposed into a variation that can arise from many Sicilian openings and was already covered in my Kalashnikov course! } 9... Rb8 $5 { I see no reason to refrain from recommending the same thing! I still believe this is quite strong, and there hasn't been much news in this area. } 10. Bg5 { This is also possible, but White has lost too many tempos with their bishop to fight for an advantage. } 10... b5 11. Nd5 Be7 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. c3 Bg5 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f5,Gc8e6,Gc6e7,Gg7g6]Black has a fantastic Kalashnikov- Pelikan type of game. } * 

