[Black "22) 5.Bf4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Bb5 { This is also quite decent and has been tried by Paravyan, a renowned theoretician. } 6... Bd7 7. Nxc6 { White's point! } 7... bxc6 8. Bd3 { White could take on c6 on move 6 and play Bd3, but the argument is that our bishop is worse on d7 rather than on c8, because it makes it harder for us to execute the plan of ...a5 and ...Ba6, exchanging the light-squared bishops. } 8... e5 $1 { [%csl Rb2]The best reaction, forcing White's bishop to make a decision. } ( 8... Rb8 { This is our reaction when the bishop stands on c8, but here it is not so good because the pawn on d6 lacks protection. } 9. Nd2 $146 { It turns out Black cannot take the pawn. } 9... Rxb2 $2 10. Nc4 $16 $146 ) 9. Bd2 { This is the strangest retreat in my opinion: White neither protects b2 nor brings it to its most natural square on e3. } 9... Rb8 $1 10. Bc3 ( 10. b3 d5 11. O-O Nf6 $146 { is also completely fine for us. } ) 10... Nf6 11. O-O Be7 $10 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gd7e6,Gf6d7,Gd7c5]White's set up looks a little bit artificial, but he has done nothing wrong yet and the game is around equal. A good plan is to castle, put the bishop and try to improve our knight to the c5-square and later push ...f5. } * 

