[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Bb5 { This is also quite decent and has been tried by Paravyan, a renowned theoretician. } 6... Bd7 7. Nxc6 { White's point! } 7... bxc6 8. Bd3 { White could take on c6 on move 6 and play Bd3, but the argument is that our bishop is worse on d7 rather than on c8, because it makes it harder for us to execute the plan of ...a5 and ...Ba6, exchanging the light-squared bishops. } 8... e5 $1 { [%csl Rb2]The best reaction, forcing White's bishop to make a decision. } ( 8... Rb8 { This is our reaction when the bishop stands on c8, but here it is not so good because the pawn on d6 lacks protection. } 9. Nd2 $146 { It turns out Black cannot take the pawn. } 9... Rxb2 $2 10. Nc4 $16 $146 ) 9. Be3 { The most natural retreat, but White's bishop is more exposed on e3. } 9... d5 $1 { Immediately going after White's central bishops. } 10. O-O Nf6 11. exd5 cxd5 12. c4 { The only independent try. Now Black has a very instructive response that highlights that the bishop on e3 is vulnerable. } ( 12. Bg5 { This transposes to the 9.Bc1 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) main line. } ) 12... Ng4 $1 { We play in a very active way! } 13. Bc1 Bc5 $1 { We keep developing pieces to their optimal squares. } 14. h3 Nxf2 $1 { Quite dangerous for White. } 15. Rxf2 O-O $1 16. cxd5 e4 $1 17. Bf1 f5 $37 { [%cal Gc5f2,Gf5f4][%csl Rb1,Rc1]Black has a dangerous initiative in the kingside and White's queenside is still quite undeveloped. } * 

