1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Bb5 { This is also quite decent and has been tried by Paravyan, a renowned theoretician. } 6... Bd7 7. Nxc6 { White's point! } 7... bxc6 8. Bd3 { White could take on c6 on move 6 and play Bd3, but the argument is that our bishop is worse on d7 rather than on c8, because it makes it harder for us to execute the plan of ...a5 and ...Ba6, exchanging the light-squared bishops. } 8... e5 $1 { [%csl Rb2]The best reaction, forcing White's bishop to make a decision. } ( 8... Rb8 { This is our reaction when the bishop stands on c8, but here it is not so good because the pawn on d6 lacks protection. } 9. Nd2 $146 { It turns out Black cannot take the pawn. } 9... Rxb2 $2 10. Nc4 $16 $146 ) 9. Bc1 Nf6 10. c4 { This leads to more calm play. } 10... d5 $1 { Of course, it makes sense to open the position and avoid the bind while the king is still on e1. } 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. exd5 Bb4+ 13. Nc3 Nxd5 14. O-O { White gets compensation for the pawn thanks to our king on e8, but nothing more. } 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bxc3 16. Rb1 O-O $1 { It is best to not be greedy and complete development. } 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Qc2+ Kg8 19. Qxc3 Bf5 $10 { [%cal Gd8d5]White has regained a pawn, but Black has no difficulties. The opposite-colored bishops typically lead to drawish tendencies, and this position is no exception. } * 

