1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 { This is also a very serious attempt. } 7... Rb8 $1 { We keep things simple and play the same move we play against 7.c4. This move makes a lot of sense in this line where White's bishop leaves c1 early. } 8. Qc1 { This is quite passive. Normal developing with ...Ne7, ...c5, ...Nc6 leads to approximately equal play, but Stockfish also points out a very active and attractive way to play. } 8... f5 $1 9. exf5 e5 { Black temporarily sacrifices a pawn to roll the central pawns up the board. } 10. Be3 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7f5]} 11. g4 $2 { This is too risky with the king still on e1. } 11... h5 12. f3 hxg4 13. fxg4 Nd5 $19 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge7h4]White is going to get mated! } * 

