1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 { This is also a very serious attempt. } 7... Rb8 $1 { We keep things simple and play the same move we play against 7.c4. This move makes a lot of sense in this line where White's bishop leaves c1 early. } 8. Nd2 $1 e5 ( 8... Rxb2 { Do not fall for White's trick! } 9. Nb3 $146 { +- } ) 9. Be3 d5 $5 { I think this is a good practical move. 9...Qc7 is also around equal, but gives leads to more controlled play and gives less chances to unbalance the game. } 10. exd5 cxd5 { [%cal Gd5d4]} 11. Bxa7 $4 { Too greedy. } 11... Rb7 12. Be3 d4 $19 * 

