1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 { This is also a very serious attempt. } 7... Rb8 $1 { We keep things simple and play the same move we play against 7.c4. This move makes a lot of sense in this line where White's bishop leaves c1 early. } 8. Nd2 $1 e5 ( 8... Rxb2 { Do not fall for White's trick! } 9. Nb3 $146 { +- } ) 9. Be3 d5 $5 { I think this is a good practical move. 9...Qc7 is also around equal, but gives leads to more controlled play and gives less chances to unbalance the game. } 10. exd5 cxd5 { [%cal Gd5d4]} 11. Qe2 { A precise move! Now d4, which was a threat to win a piece, does not work. } 11... Bd6 ( 11... d4 $2 12. Bf4 { is White's trick. } ) 12. f4 { This is also critical, trying to destabilize our center before taking on a7. } 12... e4 $1 13. Bxa7 Rb4 $1 { Extremely strong. The position is quite interesting, and in general White needs to be quite careful. The rook on b4 is vulnerable, but a lot is hanging, and we have many tactical tricks. } ( 13... Rxb2 $2 14. Bd4 ) 14. a3 Qa5 $1 15. Rd1 ( 15. Bf2 $2 Ne7 $19 $146 ) 15... Qxa7 16. axb4 Kf8 17. Bb5 Nf6 { White cannot castle and Black has great compensation in the form of bishop pair and dark square domination for the exchange. ...Bg4 is an immediate threat and if White tries to avoid this with } 18. h3 $6 ( 18. h3 $2 { , he gets crushed. } ) 18... g5 $1 19. fxg5 Bg3+ 20. Kf1 Nh5 $19 { [%cal Gh5f4,Gg3h4,Gh5g3][%csl Rf1]Crushed. } * 

