1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qd2 $2 { This looks natural, but it is a mistake that immediately gives Black the initiative. The queen should be on c2, stopping the ...f5 break. } ( 8. b3 $2 { This looks terrible and is immediately refuted by } 8... Qf6 $19 ) 8... e5 $1 9. Bg3 h5 $1 { Asking the bishop some questions. } 10. h4 { This is also possible, but then the pawn on h4 will be weaker than its counterpart on h5. } 10... Ne7 $37 { [%cal Ge7g6,Gf8e7,Gf7f5]g6 is a very good square for the knight. Black has a fantastic position. } * 

