1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qd2 $2 { This looks natural, but it is a mistake that immediately gives Black the initiative. The queen should be on c2, stopping the ...f5 break. } ( 8. b3 $2 { This looks terrible and is immediately refuted by } 8... Qf6 $19 ) 8... e5 $1 9. Bg3 h5 $1 { Asking the bishop some questions. } 10. h3 h4 11. Bh2 Qb6 12. b3 Nf6 13. Nc3 Rh6 $1 { [%cal Gh6g6,Gc8e6,Gf8e7]An original idea to activate the rook. Our king is safe in the center, and with the pawn on h4 we were not going to castle. Black is currently dominating on both sides of the board. } * 

