1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qd2 $2 { This looks natural, but it is a mistake that immediately gives Black the initiative. The queen should be on c2, stopping the ...f5 break. } ( 8. b3 $2 { This looks terrible and is immediately refuted by } 8... Qf6 $19 ) 8... e5 $1 9. Be3 f5 $1 10. f4 Nf6 11. Nc3 Ng4 { The most ambitious, going after White's bishop. 11 ...Nxe4!? 12.Nxe4 fxe4 } 12. O-O-O ( 12. fxe5 d5 $15 { is quite simple and also good for an advantage. } ) 12... Nxe3 13. Qxe3 Be7 14. c5 exf4 { White cannot take the pawn. } 15. Qe1 Bh4 { The most precise from an engine point of view, although it is far from trivial for us humans! } 16. Qd2 dxc5 17. Qxf4 Qg5 $17 { After exchanging queens the danger dissapears and we are left with an extra pawn and the bishop pair. } * 

