1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qc2 Ne7 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5,Ge7c6]The best move in the position. Black's knight would have no future on f6: by developing it to e7, we are immediately putting our eye on the weak d4-square. } ( 8... Qf6 { This is tempting, but it is not clear how Black should proceed after the ugly } 9. Bc1 $14 ) 9. c5 { White plays very actively to avoid the c5, Nc6-Nd4 plan, but he does it with almost no pieces developed and the king still on e1, so it is a risky move for him. } 9... e5 10. Bg3 { White threatens e5, so we cannot push ...d5. } 10... h5 $1 { Very precise, bothering the bishop. This is a very typical theme in this variation once the bishop goes to g3. } 11. h3 Ng6 $37 { This is even a better version for us. } * 

