1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qc2 Ne7 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5,Ge7c6]The best move in the position. Black's knight would have no future on f6: by developing it to e7, we are immediately putting our eye on the weak d4-square. } ( 8... Qf6 { This is tempting, but it is not clear how Black should proceed after the ugly } 9. Bc1 $14 ) 9. Nc3 c5 10. Rd1 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d4]} 11. Qd2 { This has also been tried, but it is not too critical because it allows Black's knight to immediately occupy the d4-square. } 11... Nd4 $1 12. Bd3 Be7 13. e5 { At first, this looks quite promising for White, but we have a diabolical tactical trick. } 13... Bb7 14. O-O Bf3 $1 { This move breaks White's coordination. } 15. Rde1 { This looks normal, but it can lead to problems for White. } 15... dxe5 16. Bxe5 $6 { This looks strong, but with strong tactical play we can refute it. } 16... Bg5 $1 { Winning a tempo by attacking the queen that does not have squares! } 17. Bf4 Rxb2 $3 { Deflection. The dark-squared bishop will be very important! } 18. Qxb2 Bxf4 { [%cal Gd8h4,Ge8g8][%csl Gd4,Gf3,Gf4]Now the black queen is coming to the attack with fatal consequences for White. Black has a nearly decisive attack. An incredible tactical line that justifies our play awaits.. } 19. Ne2 Bxe2 20. Bxe2 Bd2 $3 { A subtle touch! The bishop is untouchable since ...Nf3+ is in the air. } 21. Rd1 Bc3 $17 { Winning material. } * 

