1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qc2 Ne7 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5,Ge7c6]The best move in the position. Black's knight would have no future on f6: by developing it to e7, we are immediately putting our eye on the weak d4-square. } ( 8... Qf6 { This is tempting, but it is not clear how Black should proceed after the ugly } 9. Bc1 $14 ) 9. Nc3 c5 10. Bd3 { White can develop normal, but things look already more pleasant for Black after normal play. } 10... Nc6 11. O-O Be7 { [%cal Ge6e5,Ge8g8,Gc6d4,Ge7f6]Black has the initiative thanks to the weakness of the d4-square. } * 

