1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qc2 Ne7 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5,Ge7c6]The best move in the position. Black's knight would have no future on f6: by developing it to e7, we are immediately putting our eye on the weak d4-square. } ( 8... Qf6 { This is tempting, but it is not clear how Black should proceed after the ugly } 9. Bc1 $14 ) 9. Nc3 c5 10. O-O-O { The most natural and in my opinion the most critical. } 10... Nc6 11. e5 $1 { White goes for the throat. 11. Nb5?! allows 11...e5, so it's a now-or-never moment for him. } 11... g5 $1 { The most active move available. I also checked } ( 11... Bd7 { and } ) ( 11... Nd4 $146 { , and they should equalize in the end, but White seemed to be pressing from a human point of view. After this pawn launch, the game becomes a three-result affair. Our bishop can come to g7 and start to pressure White's queenside. } ) 12. Bg3 h5 $1 { We expand on the kingside and harass White's bishop. } 13. h4 g4 14. Rxd6 $1 { White's best chance is depriving us of our dark-squared bishop. } 14... Bxd6 15. exd6 e5 $13 { [%cal Gd8f6,Gc8f5,Gc6d4]White has some compensation, but I think it is much easier to play this crazy position with Black in practice. ...Nd4, ...Bf5, and ...Qf6 are all easy and good moves that can be played without much thought in the following moves. } * 

