1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 $5 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! Most notably, Duda tried this against Rapport in the FIDE Candidates in 2022. } 5... d6 ( 5... Nf6 $146 { This is natural, but } 6. Nb5 $146 e5 7. Bg5 { is an improved version of the Pelikan for White. } ) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 $1 { Immediately asking a question to White: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qc2 Ne7 $1 { [%cal Gc6c5,Ge7c6]The best move in the position. Black's knight would have no future on f6: by developing it to e7, we are immediately putting our eye on the weak d4-square. } ( 8... Qf6 { This is tempting, but it is not clear how Black should proceed after the ugly } 9. Bc1 $14 ) 9. Nc3 c5 10. O-O-O { The most natural and in my opinion the most critical. } 10... Nc6 11. e5 $1 { White goes for the throat. 11. Nb5?! allows 11...e5, so it's a now-or-never moment for him. } 11... g5 $1 { The most active move available. I also checked } ( 11... Bd7 { and } ) ( 11... Nd4 $146 { , and they should equalize in the end, but White seemed to be pressing from a human point of view. After this pawn launch, the game becomes a three-result affair. Our bishop can come to g7 and start to pressure White's queenside. } ) 12. Be3 Nd4 $1 { Very strong. } 13. Rxd4 $1 { The most critical, keeping control of the dark squares. } 13... cxd4 14. Bxd4 Bg7 { Developing and pinning! } 15. Bxa7 Ra8 { A natural improvement over a recent game that Black won in this line, which you can review in the model games (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) section. } 16. Bd4 Qa5 $1 { We need to cover the c5-square before taking back on e5. } ( 16... dxe5 $2 17. Bc5 { This would be quite dangerous for us. For example: } 17... Qc7 18. b4 Bf8 19. Bxf8 Kxf8 20. Kb2 { And White's king is surprisingly safe, and their queenside pawns are ready to roll. } ) ( 16... Bxe5 $2 17. Bxe5 dxe5 18. Qe4 ) 17. Qe4 { White can also sacrifice the e5-pawn and try to recover the exchange, but Black gets a very good position. } 17... dxe5 18. Bb6 { White's point. } 18... Qxb6 19. Qxa8 O-O 20. Qf3 Bd7 $13 { [%cal Gf7f5,Ge5e4,Gf8a8]We have a very strange position. Black is a pawn down, but cannot be worse with their strong bishop pair and the central pawn mass. } * 

