1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. Bf4 e5 7. Be3 { This line has been played by lots of strong players in the past, but it has now fallen out of favor. And for good reason! Black gets easy play in the main lines. } 7... Nf6 8. Bg5 Be6 9. Bxf6 { This is a slightly better move order for White compared to the main line, but it is still quite good for us. } 9... gxf6 10. Nd2 a6 11. Nc3 f5 $1 { We exchange one of our doubled pawns, opening the position for our bishops. } 12. exf5 Bxf5 { Black's position is just great with their central dominance and the central pawns. A possible instructive line is: } 13. Nc4 Be6 14. Qh5 Qc7 $1 { The point is that our king will feel very safe on the queenside. } 15. O-O-O O-O-O $15 * 

