1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 { Now both developing knight moves are possible, although developing the b1-knight is much more common. } 7. N5c3 Be7 8. g3 Bd7 $5 { I like the idea of vacating the c8-square for our rook quickly: White is behind in development, and we can generate a lot of counterplay. } 9. Bg2 Ne5 { This move is already a novelty. I think it makes a lot of sense: White is playing quite slowly, so we immediately try to generate initiative. } 10. b3 h5 $1 { The same idea as against 10.Qe2 is once again quite strong. This typical pawn push aims to create weaknesses in White's camp. } 11. h3 a6 $1 { Going for the ...b5 break, one of our main sources of counterplay. It makes sense to go for quick counterplay, because White is not full developed yet. } 12. Qe2 b5 $1 { A strong Benko-like pawn sacrifice. } 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Qa5+ { There are many other possible alternatives, like } ( 14... O-O { which leads to less forced play, but this looks the most natural to me. } ) 15. N1c3 O-O { We could not take on b5 winning a piece because Qxb5+: now it is a threat. } 16. Bd2 Rfb8 { Activating our worst-placed piece with tempo. } 17. Nd4 Qc5 { White cannot move the knight back due to ...Rxb3, and Be3 is not possible, so he is forced to make an awkward move. } 18. Qe3 h4 $1 { Generating some weaknesses on the kingside. } 19. g4 Bd8 $1 { [%cal Gd8b6]Very instructive play by Black, as we once again improve our worst-placed piece. } 20. f4 $2 { This is asking for trouble as White. } 20... Bb6 $1 { Active play works perfectly. } 21. fxe5 Qxe5 $1 { The pressure on d4 is too much for White to handle. } 22. Nce2 Bb5 { White loses material. } 23. Bc3 { LOSER!!! } 23... Nd5 $19 * 

