1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 { Now both developing knight moves are possible, although developing the b1-knight is much more common. } 7. N5c3 Be7 8. g3 Bd7 $5 { I like the idea of vacating the c8-square for our rook quickly: White is behind in development, and we can generate a lot of counterplay. } 9. Bg2 Ne5 { This move is already a novelty. I think it makes a lot of sense: White is playing quite slowly, so we immediately try to generate initiative. } 10. b3 h5 $1 { The same idea as against 10.Qe2 is once again quite strong. This typical pawn push aims to create weaknesses in White's camp. } 11. h3 a6 $1 { Going for the ...b5 break, one of our main sources of counterplay. It makes sense to go for quick counterplay, because White is not full developed yet. } 12. a4 { Trying to stop ...b5 manually. } 12... b5 $1 { We play it anyway. } 13. f4 $5 { This leads to very forced play. } 13... Ng6 14. e5 $1 { White's tricky idea. } 14... dxe5 15. fxe5 { Of course, White would be completely lost if he took on a8 with their vulnerable king. He has another idea in mind: he plans to respond to } 15... b4 $1 ( 15... Nxe5 $146 { with } 16. axb5 { , when we wouldn't be able to recapture. Fortunately, we have a fantastic defensive resource here, typical of the Taimanov. } ) 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Qf3 { White's best move, defending the third rank and putting pressure on a8. It also introduces some new tactical ideas, which we'll explore shortly. } 17... Rc8 18. Ne4 { White's idea! } 18... Bxa1 19. Nd6+ Ke7 20. Nxf7 ( 20. Qxf7+ Kxd6 { looks dangerous, but in reality, Black is just winning: their king will be sufficiently safe on the queenside, and he is up material. } ) 20... Bc6 $1 { Counterattacking! } 21. Qf2 Qd3 22. Nxh8 Nxh8 $17 { This position is very good for Black: we are not down in material, and White's king is weaker. Their knight on b1 is also a very problematic piece, difficult to defend. } * 

