1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 { Now both developing knight moves are possible, although developing the b1-knight is much more common. } 7. N5c3 Be7 8. Be2 { The main move, simply completing development. } 8... O-O 9. O-O b6 { We prepare the development of our bishop. } 10. f4 $6 { This is generally quite weak in these lines: it doesn't contribute much to the position, as e5 is not really feasible, and White is still significantly behind in development. } 10... Bb7 11. Bf3 Rc8 12. Be3 Ba6 $1 { Black has developed all their pieces and is already prepared to strike at White's center. } 13. Nd2 d5 $1 14. exd5 exd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Nb4 $1 { White cannot maintain their material advantage. } 17. Be4 Bxc4 18. Nxc4 Rxc4 $15 { White would be playing for an advantage with the pawn on f2, but here he is under some pressure: all of Black's pieces are very active, and White's bishops lack good outposts where they are well-defended. } * 

