1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 { Now both developing knight moves are possible, although developing the b1-knight is much more common. } 7. N5c3 Be7 8. Be2 { The main move, simply completing development. } 8... O-O 9. O-O b6 { We prepare the development of our bishop. } 10. Bf4 { To the untrained eye the bishop looks more naturally placed on e3, but it is better on f4; it helps defuse the ...d5 break in some variations because now White can advance with e5. } 10... Bb7 11. Nd2 Qd7 { There are other moves, but connecting the rooks looks natural enough. I have a concrete idea for Black, which has already been demonstrated in practice, and we can execute it through various move orders. } ( 11... d5 $2 { Here we cannot break with ...d5 as in the 10.Be3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) line, because the bishop on f4 supports e5. } 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e5 $36 ) 12. Re1 Rfd8 13. Rc1 { White can also play more than one move, but our plan is still the same. I do not want to reveal it yet! } 13... Rac8 14. Bg3 Qe8 $5 { This move looks innocent enough, vacating the d7-square and preparing ...d5 by retreating the queen. But it has another idea in mind! } 15. Bf1 h6 16. a3 Qf8 $5 17. Kh1 g5 $1 { [%cal Gf8g7,Gh6h5,Gc6e5]The big point! Stockfish loves this idea, and it was already played by none other than Fischer in similar positions! In fact, he wanted to play it as early as move 15. The key is that White cannot punish us for our boldness because their pieces are not well positioned for a kingside attack, and we can seize a lot of space on that flank. Our queen, which has been passive, will also gain significant range from a square like g7. } 18. f4 gxf4 19. Bxf4 Ne5 $15 { [%cal Gf8g7,Ge5g6]Great play for Black. } * 

