1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 { Now both developing knight moves are possible, although developing the b1-knight is much more common. } 7. N1c3 a6 8. Nd4 { A very solid line, but it lacks much venom, as White loses control over the d5-square, which allows us to liberate our position. } 8... Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O d5 $5 { There are other moves that try to keep more tension, but this is a very clear equalizer. } ( 10... Ne5 $2 $146 { is also playable , keeping more pieces on the board. The idea is to bring the knight to g6 after f4. } ) 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. e5 Nd7 14. f4 { This has been tried to unbalance the game a bit more, but Black has good control of the light squares and cannot be worse. } 14... Rb8 $1 { Putting pressure on the b-file makes White's queenside development difficult. } 15. Kh1 Nc5 $13 { [%cal Gc8f5,Gb8b2]Black has a very harmonious position with their light square control. } 16. f5 $2 d4 17. Na4 $2 $146 d3 18. Bf3 Nxa4 $146 19. Qxa4 d2 $19 { is an example of what can happen if White gets too ambitious. } * 

