1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 { Now both developing knight moves are possible, although developing the b1-knight is much more common. } 7. N1c3 a6 8. Nd4 { A very solid line, but it lacks much venom, as White loses control over the d5-square, which allows us to liberate our position. } 8... Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O d5 $5 { There are other moves that try to keep more tension, but this is a very clear equalizer. } ( 10... Ne5 $2 $146 { is also playable , keeping more pieces on the board. The idea is to bring the knight to g6 after f4. } ) 11. cxd5 exd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Nxd5 cxd5 { [%cal Ge7f6,Gc8f5]White has managed to give us an isolated pawn, but the knights are off the board, and both our bishops will find good squares on f6 and f5, targeting White's queenside. } 15. Be3 Bf5 { This has never been played, but this is very logical. It is slightly more active than playing with the bishop on e6. } 16. Bf3 Bf6 17. Qxd5 Qxd5 18. Bxd5 Rad8 $10 { [%cal Gd8d5,Gf6b2]After taking on b2 the game is completely equal. } * 

