1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 { Now both developing knight moves are possible, although developing the b1-knight is much more common. } 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 Qa5 $5 { This is a good way to avoid the theory that arises after 8...b6. It is also quite tricky for White if he has never seen it before, we put immediate pressure on their position. } 9. Bd2 Be7 { We do not need to fear any white knight jump. } 10. Bd3 { This move provides extra support to the e4-pawn, but the bishop is slightly more exposed on d3 in some variations. I have a curious move in mind now. } 10... Qb6 $5 11. Nc2 O-O { Now we could not take on b2, so we simply complete development. } 12. O-O Ne5 13. Be2 Bd7 { We have a typical Sicilian position, where once again White's pieces are not ideally placed. Our main idea in the short run is to bring the rooks to the center, and in the long run, aim to push either ...b5 or ...d5. } 14. Rc1 Qc7 15. Ne3 Ng6 16. Bd3 Qc5 17. Kh1 b5 $133 { Black achieved one of the key breaks and stood fine in a correspondence game. Note that cxb5 does not win a pawn because we can threaten the bishop on d3 with ...Qd4. } * 

