1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nb5 { The 2nd most popular move, } ( 5. Nb5 $146 { , is played with one of two ideas after } 5... d6 { . The first is } 6. Bf4 { , provoking } 6... e5 { and reaching a Sveshnikov-style structure after . But this version favors Black—the bishop sits passively on e3 instead of g5, and White enters a tamer Sveshnikov that few players are excited about these days. The second idea is 6... d6 6.c4 , aiming for a Maroczy Bind. White grabs central space but wastes time maneuvering the awkward knights. Modern theory sees these Hedgehogs as dynamic rather than passive, and Black gets easy development with plenty of counterplay. } ) 5... d6 6. c4 Nf6 { Now both developing knight moves are possible, although developing the b1-knight is much more common. } 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 Qa5 $5 { This is a good way to avoid the theory that arises after 8...b6. It is also quite tricky for White if he has never seen it before, we put immediate pressure on their position. } 9. Bd2 Be7 { We do not need to fear any white knight jump. } 10. Nc2 O-O 11. Be2 Qc7 { Now 11...Qe5 is not possible, as the d4-square is covered. However, the c4-square is less defended now that the knight has moved, making c7 an ideal square for our queen. } 12. O-O Ne5 { The move chosen by Firoujza in one of the first games that attracted my attention to this variation. The immediate 12...b6 is also possible and quite similar. } 13. Ne3 b6 14. f4 Ng6 $13 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gf8d8,Ga8c8]We have a complex Hedgehog middlegame. White's pieces are not on optimal squares: both bishops are not very active, and the rooks have yet to enter the game. Black, as always, will focus on their two pawn breaks: ...b5 and ...d5. } * 

