1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ( 3. Nc3 $146 { has little independent value, as } 3... Nc6 $146 4. d4 { transposes to the Open Sicilian, while 4... Nc6 4.Bb5 leads to harmless Rossolimo lines without c3. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 Nd4 $1 { The strongest move, forcing White to decide how to handle the bishop. } 5. O-O { The most critical move, recommended by British Grandmaster Gawain Jones in his Coffeehouse Repertoire series. We need to know our response by heart because it is not so intuitive. } 5... a6 6. Bd3 Nc6 $1 7. Nd5 $5 Bd6 $5 { The simplest move. Before exploring this course, I thought } ( 7... g5 { was very strong, but things are not so straightforward there. With } ) ( 7... Bd6 { , we intend to take the knight on d5 because after exd5 and ...Nce7, the bishop is no longer blocked on f8, allowing us to castle. } ) ( 7... g5 { This leads to some complications, but they are good for Black. } 8. Nxg5 $146 exd5 9. Qh5 $13 { The machine manages to repel the attack, but as a human it is difficult and I prefer avoiding such an attack in a sideline. } ) 8. Ne3 Bc7 $1 9. b3 Nf6 10. Bb2 d6 { Stopping e5. } 11. Ne1 $5 O-O 12. f4 b5 $13 { [%cal Ga8b8,Gd6d5,Gc5c4]We have a complex position where Black is not worse. White has some prospects on the kingside, but our counterplay on the queenside with ideas like ...Rb8, ...c4, or ...d5 followed by ...c4 is also interesting. } * 

