1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ( 3. Nc3 $146 { has little independent value, as } 3... Nc6 $146 4. d4 { transposes to the Open Sicilian, while 4... Nc6 4.Bb5 leads to harmless Rossolimo lines without c3. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 Nd4 $1 { The strongest move, forcing White to decide how to handle the bishop. } 5. O-O { The most critical move, recommended by British Grandmaster Gawain Jones in his Coffeehouse Repertoire series. We need to know our response by heart because it is not so intuitive. } 5... a6 6. Bd3 Nc6 $1 7. Nd5 $5 Bd6 $5 { The simplest move. Before exploring this course, I thought } ( 7... g5 { was very strong, but things are not so straightforward there. With } ) ( 7... Bd6 { , we intend to take the knight on d5 because after exd5 and ...Nce7, the bishop is no longer blocked on f8, allowing us to castle. } ) ( 7... g5 { This leads to some complications, but they are good for Black. } 8. Nxg5 $146 exd5 9. Qh5 $13 { The machine manages to repel the attack, but as a human it is difficult and I prefer avoiding such an attack in a sideline. } ) 8. Ne3 Bc7 $1 9. c3 { White intends to copy us and improve the outlook of their d3-bishop. } 9... Nf6 10. Bc2 d5 { We manage to get the central break before the white player does. } 11. exd5 exd5 12. d4 cxd4 13. Nxd4 O-O $10 { Black is perfectly fine because the bishop on c1 cannot easily improve its position. } * 

