1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ( 3. Nc3 $146 { has little independent value, as } 3... Nc6 $146 4. d4 { transposes to the Open Sicilian, while 4... Nc6 4.Bb5 leads to harmless Rossolimo lines without c3. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 Nd4 $1 { The strongest move, forcing White to decide how to handle the bishop. } 5. O-O { The most critical move, recommended by British Grandmaster Gawain Jones in his Coffeehouse Repertoire series. We need to know our response by heart because it is not so intuitive. } 5... a6 6. Bd3 Nc6 $1 7. b3 { It is logical to develop the bishop to the diagonal, but we counter it. } 7... g6 $1 { The easiest. Our bishop on g7 will neutralize the bishop on b2. } 8. Ne2 Bg7 9. c3 d5 10. Bc2 dxe4 { Not mentioned by Gawain in his 1.e4 book. This looks like a simple equalizer to me. } 11. Bxe4 Bd7 $10 { [%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8][%csl Yb3,Yc3,Yd2]The position seems very easy to play as black. White's pawn structure is very strange. } * 

