1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 ( 3. Nc3 $146 { has little independent value, as } 3... Nc6 $146 4. d4 { transposes to the Open Sicilian, while 4... Nc6 4.Bb5 leads to harmless Rossolimo lines without c3. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 Nd4 $1 { The strongest move, forcing White to decide how to handle the bishop. } 5. O-O { The most critical move, recommended by British Grandmaster Gawain Jones in his Coffeehouse Repertoire series. We need to know our response by heart because it is not so intuitive. } 5... a6 6. Bd3 Nc6 $1 7. b3 { It is logical to develop the bishop to the diagonal, but we counter it. } 7... g6 $1 { The easiest. Our bishop on g7 will neutralize the bishop on b2. } 8. Bb2 Bg7 9. Re1 g5 { [%cal Gg5g4]} 10. e5 $5 { An inventive piece sacrifice, but it fails if we know the correct response. } ( 10. e5 $2 { This is a tricky idea, and although Black should be fine, I prefer to play in a more active way and spring a surprise on White. } ) 10... d5 $1 ( 10... g4 { this looks natural, but after } 11. Ne4 $146 { White invades our position via the d6-square. } ) 11. exd6 g4 $1 { Now the d6-square is no longer available for White's knight. White can get some compensation for the piece. } 12. Be4 gxf3 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qxf3 Nh6 $15 { [%cal Ge8g8,Rf3c6,Gc8d7]It is certainly not enough. We manage to castle, even at the cost of giving up some pawns, and the extra piece should matter a lot more in the long run. } * 

