1. e4 c5 2. c3 { [%cal Gd2d4]We'll cover the Alapin via the move order } ( 2. Nf3 $146 e6 3. c3 { , as this is a popular response to 2...e6. Christoph Sielecki also recommended it in Keep It Simple: 1.e4 \- 2.0. It's a particularly logical choice for those who play Bb5 systems against 2\. Nf3 2...Nc6 and 2...d6 (the Rossolimo and the Moscow). } ) 2... Nf6 { [%csl Re4]} 3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 { White can play Nf3 and d4 in any order. } ( 4. Nf3 $146 e6 { is the starting point (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) of chapter 26. } 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Be7 { transposes. } ) 4... cxd4 5. Nf3 { Or } ( 5. cxd4 d6 6. Nf3 $146 e6 7. Bc4 Be7 { . } ) 5... e6 { You could also start with } ( 5... d6 { , and reach the same position after } 6. cxd4 e6 7. Bc4 Be7 { . } ) 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Be7 { This is the starting position of the Alapin main line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), which we'll study in chapters 26 and 27. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "Alapin: 4.Bd3 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alapin: 4.Bd3 #1"]
[Black "25) 3.c3 Alapin: Rare 4th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. Bd3 { This looks strange, but we should know what we're doing because White's plan is fundamentally sound: he wants to put the bishop on c2 and then get great control of the center with d4. } 4... d5 5. e5 Nfd7 6. O-O c4 $1 { The key move. Now, after d4, we always have the option to capture en passant. } 7. Bc2 Nc6 8. Re1 Qc7 9. Qe2 g5 $1 { A very strong move, very typical of French structures. We pile up pressure on the e5-pawn. } 10. Nxg5 Qxe5 $13 { I prefer Black in this complex position, if we do not get mated then our extra central pawn should make a difference. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "Alapin: 4.Bd3 #2"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alapin: 4.Bd3 #2"]
[Black "25) 3.c3 Alapin: Rare 4th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. Bd3 { This looks strange, but we should know what we're doing because White's plan is fundamentally sound: he wants to put the bishop on c2 and then get great control of the center with d4. } 4... d5 5. e5 Nfd7 6. O-O c4 $1 { The key move. Now, after d4, we always have the option to capture en passant. } 7. Bc2 Nc6 8. Re1 Qc7 9. Qe2 g5 $1 { A very strong move, very typical of French structures. We pile up pressure on the e5-pawn. } 10. b3 { Roiz's recommendation in his Modern Chess course. We must respond with great accuracy, but the reward is a great position. } 10... g4 $1 11. Nd4 Ncxe5 12. bxc4 dxc4 13. d3 { White tries to open the position as much as possible. } 13... cxd3 14. Bxd3 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Nc5 16. Qe2 { Roiz stops here, saying White has sufficient compensation for the pawn and an interesting middlegame. I agree with him, Black is still a pawn up and has the pair of bishops, so once the surprise factor is gone, this should not be too dangerous. } 16... b6 $1 { [%cal Gc8b7,Ge8c8]My favorite move, trying to develop the bishop and bring the king to the queenside. Black cannot be worse. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "Alapin: 4.Bd3 #3"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alapin: 4.Bd3 #3"]
[Black "25) 3.c3 Alapin: Rare 4th Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. Bd3 { This looks strange, but we should know what we're doing because White's plan is fundamentally sound: he wants to put the bishop on c2 and then get great control of the center with d4. } 4... d5 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bc2 c4 7. d4 { If White plays } ( 7. b3 { , trying to undermine Black's queenside, then we can proceed with } 7... Nc6 $146 8. Qe2 Qc7 { the e5-pawn falls! And remember that a central pawn is always more important! } ) 7... cxd3 { If not for this little move, we would be in great trouble! } 8. Bxd3 ( 8. Qxd3 { is also possible, but after } 8... Qc7 9. Bf4 Nc6 $146 10. Qe2 f6 { , play is very similar to 8.Bxd3. } ) 8... Nc6 9. Bf4 ( 9. Qe2 { transposes to 7.Qe2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 9... Be7 { The position resembles a French Defense where White has played dxc5 prematurely. } 10. O-O $2 { Very natural, but a big mistake. } 10... g5 $1 11. Be3 g4 $17 { Next, we will take on e5 and enjoy a clean extra pawn. } * 

