1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. Bd3 { This looks strange, but we should know what we're doing because White's plan is fundamentally sound: he wants to put the bishop on c2 and then get great control of the center with d4. } 4... d5 5. e5 Nfd7 6. Bc2 c4 7. d4 { If White plays } ( 7. b3 { , trying to undermine Black's queenside, then we can proceed with } 7... Nc6 $146 8. Qe2 Qc7 { the e5-pawn falls! And remember that a central pawn is always more important! } ) 7... cxd3 { If not for this little move, we would be in great trouble! } 8. Bxd3 ( 8. Qxd3 { is also possible, but after } 8... Qc7 9. Bf4 Nc6 $146 10. Qe2 f6 { , play is very similar to 8.Bxd3. } ) 8... Nc6 9. Bf4 ( 9. Qe2 { transposes to 7.Qe2 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 9... Be7 { The position resembles a French Defense where White has played dxc5 prematurely. } 10. h4 { Avoiding ...g5, but now that White has not castled so quickly, we can immediately fight for the center. } 10... f6 11. exf6 gxf6 $13 { [%cal Gd7c5,Ge6e5,Gc8e6,Gd8d7,Ge8c8]The most ambitious recapture. With the pawn on h3 instead of h4, this would be dangerous because of Nh4/Qh5+, but here, White struggles to take advantage of our weak king, and we are going to push our center and try to castle long in the next few moves. } * 

