1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. g3 { A solid system, which is not very dangerous for us. } 5... d6 { It is also possible to delay this move, but it's simplest to play it right away. } 6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Bg2 Nc6 { We continue with standard developing moves. } 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Qc7 $1 { A good move. White is not really threatening the d5-pawn. } 12. c4 ( 12. Bxd5 $2 exd5 13. Qxd5 $2 Bh3 $19 { is suicidal for White. } ) 12... Nf6 13. Nc3 Bd7 { Everything has been quite natural up to this point, and there are quite a few options from this position. White can try different approaches, but Black manages to neutralize the g2-square and equalizes comfortably. } 14. Rd1 Bc5 $1 ( 14... Be5 { is also possible, but the bishop looks more active in the a7-g1 diagonal. } ) 15. Qh4 Bc6 $1 16. Bg5 Be7 $10 { This forces us to part with our light-squared bishop, but it compromises White's pawn structure, and we gain the d5-square as an outpost for our knight. } * 

