1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Nc3 { This removes our knight from d5, but White accepts some weaknesses. } 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Qc7 { In general, if we manage to stabilize and develop normally, our position will be promising: in the long run, the hanging pawns become a weakness. } 9. Bd2 Nd7 10. Bd3 $5 { The most interesting move, sacrificing the e5-pawn for quick development. } 10... dxe5 11. O-O Bd6 $1 { We should not be greedy: we complete development. } 12. Re1 O-O 13. Qe2 Rd8 $1 { Precise till the end. We vacate the f8-square for the knight and avoid taking on d4. } ( 13... exd4 14. cxd4 $40 { Now the a1-rook can also enter the attack. I prefer to avoid this. } ) 14. Bg5 f6 $1 15. Bh4 exd4 $1 { The correct moment to release the tension in the center. } 16. cxd4 $6 Nf8 17. Rac1 Qf7 $15 { Black's queen and knight are perfectly placed for defense now. } * 

