1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 { This is the second most dangerous move in my opinion. } 9... dxe5 $5 { This is quite rare, but it fits quite well with our repertoire. We also take on e5 after Qe2, so it makes it easy to memorize. } ( 9... Nc6 $146 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Nc3 $146 { White's position looks easier to play. } ) ( 9... Bd7 { is not bad, but White has some initiative after } 10. Nc3 $146 Nxc3 $146 11. bxc3 Bc6 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. Ne5 $36 $146 { The rook on e1 is very useful, because we do not force a queen exchange with ...Bxe5. } ) 10. dxe5 Na6 $5 { Our idea! It has only been played in one game back in 2008. ...Bd7 is not really possible right now, because the pawn on d5 hangs. So, we should develop the other queenside piece! However, we do not love the c6-square for our knight, because then our light-squared bishop would be limited. So we play ...Na6, intending to play ...Nc5. } ( 10... Bd7 11. Bxd5 exd5 12. Qxd5 { is the problem! With the queen on e2, this would not be possible. } 12... Bc6 13. Qb3 $14 { Black has some compensation, but I am not completely sure it is enough for equality. } ) 11. h4 $5 { An aggressive attempt that makes some sense, because we do not have many defenders on the kingside. } 11... Nc5 { I prefer to avoid taking the pawn, White gets quite a dangerous initiative with a beautiful rook lift! } ( 11... Bxh4 12. Nxh4 $146 Qxh4 13. Nd2 $146 Nc5 $146 14. a4 $2 ) 12. h5 h6 { [%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6]White has made progress on the kingside, but it is difficult for him to bring pieces there. Our plan is to develop our light-squared bishop first and then initiate play on the queenside. } 13. Qd4 $5 { White is aiming to transfer the queen to g4 at some point. } 13... b6 { Protecting c5 and more importantly, getting ready to develop the bishop to b7. } 14. Qg4 { White threatens Bxh6. } 14... Kh8 15. Bd2 Ba6 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 $13 { [%cal Ga6b4,Ga8c8]Black is solid. A plan is to play ...Rc8 and ...Nab4. } * 

