1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { This is clearly the most testing move. It is not easy for White to develop the minor pieces on the queenside to good squares, so he decides to improve the queen and the rook to its best available squares: e2 for the queen and d1 for the rook. } 9... dxe5 $5 { There are other moves, but I like to play in a forcing way against this variation. First, we release tension in the center and force White to decide if he wants to take with the knight or the pawn. } 10. Nxe5 Nc6 $1 { We have already seen this theme in the sidelines. } 11. Nxc6 bxc6 { [%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Gd8a5,Gc8a6]This structure is very comfortable for us, with a strong d5-pawn and the plan of expanding on the queenside while trying to exchange the light-squared bishops. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "Alapin Main Line: 11.Bxd5 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alapin Main Line: 11.Bxd5 #1"]
[Black "27) 3.c3 Alapin: 9.Qe2 Main Line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { This is clearly the most testing move. It is not easy for White to develop the minor pieces on the queenside to good squares, so he decides to improve the queen and the rook to its best available squares: e2 for the queen and d1 for the rook. } 9... dxe5 $5 { There are other moves, but I like to play in a forcing way against this variation. First, we release tension in the center and force White to decide if he wants to take with the knight or the pawn. } 10. dxe5 Bd7 $1 { The key move in our system against the Alapin is to develop the bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal. It's important to avoid the natural move ...b6, for both concrete and positional reasons. the concerete reason is } ( 10... b6 $2 11. Rd1 Bb7 12. Nc3 $146 { and after 13...Bxf3? 14.Qxf3 , our rook on a8 is hanging! The positional reason is that the bishop will be protected on c6 by a pawn, which can be quite useful. } ) 11. Bxd5 { This is a serious alternative. } 11... exd5 12. Nc3 Be6 13. Be3 { Here, Ganguly and Rustam stop in their fantastic Alapin course, stating that after Rad1 and Nd4, White should be slightly better due to f4 plans. In my opinion, Black has enough counterplay thanks to the bishop pair, and with precise play, we can avoid getting steamrolled by f4-f5 plans. Already some games have been played in this territory and I have tried to be exhaustive, because this looks like a critical position for the whole line. } 13... Nc6 14. Rad1 Qd7 { Nd4 is not so easy to achieve for White because the e5-pawn is hanging. Our plan is to centralize the rooks and break in the center with ...f6. } 15. Rfe1 Bb4 $1 { The easiest way to achieve full equality in this position is by exchanging White's knight when it is appropriate. } 16. h3 Rfe8 17. Qd2 Rac8 18. a3 Bxc3 19. Qxc3 Bf5 $10 { [%cal Gf5e4]White cannot put more pressure on d5 and the position is equal. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "Alapin Main Line: 11.Bxd5 #2"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Alapin Main Line: 11.Bxd5 #2"]
[Black "27) 3.c3 Alapin: 9.Qe2 Main Line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { This is clearly the most testing move. It is not easy for White to develop the minor pieces on the queenside to good squares, so he decides to improve the queen and the rook to its best available squares: e2 for the queen and d1 for the rook. } 9... dxe5 $5 { There are other moves, but I like to play in a forcing way against this variation. First, we release tension in the center and force White to decide if he wants to take with the knight or the pawn. } 10. dxe5 Bd7 $1 { The key move in our system against the Alapin is to develop the bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal. It's important to avoid the natural move ...b6, for both concrete and positional reasons. the concerete reason is } ( 10... b6 $2 11. Rd1 Bb7 12. Nc3 $146 { and after 13...Bxf3? 14.Qxf3 , our rook on a8 is hanging! The positional reason is that the bishop will be protected on c6 by a pawn, which can be quite useful. } ) 11. Bxd5 { This is a serious alternative. } 11... exd5 12. Nc3 Be6 13. Be3 { Here, Ganguly and Rustam stop in their fantastic Alapin course, stating that after Rad1 and Nd4, White should be slightly better due to f4 plans. In my opinion, Black has enough counterplay thanks to the bishop pair, and with precise play, we can avoid getting steamrolled by f4-f5 plans. Already some games have been played in this territory and I have tried to be exhaustive, because this looks like a critical position for the whole line. } 13... Nc6 14. Rad1 Qd7 { Nd4 is not so easy to achieve for White because the e5-pawn is hanging. Our plan is to centralize the rooks and break in the center with ...f6. } 15. Bd4 { This stops ...f6, but the bishop is not very well placed on d4. We can play some useful moves and White's plan is not so clear. For example: } 15... Rfe8 16. h3 h6 17. Rfe1 Rac8 18. Qe3 Bb4 $13 { [%cal Ge6f5,Gb4a5]After a3 the bishop can come to a5 and later to c7, where we cover the d6-square and also put pressure against e5. } * 

