1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { This is clearly the most testing move. It is not easy for White to develop the minor pieces on the queenside to good squares, so he decides to improve the queen and the rook to its best available squares: e2 for the queen and d1 for the rook. } 9... dxe5 $5 { There are other moves, but I like to play in a forcing way against this variation. First, we release tension in the center and force White to decide if he wants to take with the knight or the pawn. } 10. dxe5 Bd7 $1 { The key move in our system against the Alapin is to develop the bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal. It's important to avoid the natural move ...b6, for both concrete and positional reasons. the concerete reason is } ( 10... b6 $2 11. Rd1 Bb7 12. Nc3 $146 { and after 13...Bxf3? 14.Qxf3 , our rook on a8 is hanging! The positional reason is that the bishop will be protected on c6 by a pawn, which can be quite useful. } ) 11. Rd1 { The mainline, putting pressure on the d5-knight and centralizing the rook. } 11... Bc6 12. Nd4 Bc5 $1 { The strongest move, in my opinion. We improve the bishop and make contact with White's knight, which reduces White's mobility. } 13. Nc3 { The most critical move, aside from the main line. } 13... Qb6 $1 ( 13... Nxc3 $146 { is a desirable move from a positional point of view, but is not easy to develop the knight on b8. For example: } 14. bxc3 Qh4 15. Be3 $36 { . } ) 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Nf5 $5 { A tricky attempt, but if we remain calm and play the logical (and only) defensive moves, we will be fine. } 15... dxc4 16. Qg4 g6 17. Nh6+ Kh8 $1 ( 17... Kg7 { is bad because } 18. Bg5 f5 19. exf6+ ) 18. Bg5 f5 19. Qxc4 { The strongest move, keeping an eye on g8 and f7. } 19... Bxf2+ 20. Kh1 Nd7 21. Rxd7 Bxd7 22. Nf7+ Kg8 $10 { Now White does not have anything better than to force a draw with } 23. Nd6+ $146 Kh8 24. Nf7+ $146 { . } * 

