1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Delayed Alapin. White argues that we lost some options with ...e6, while Nf3 was a useful developing move. But we don't mind transposing to the Alapin with } 3... Nf6 ( 3... Nf6 $146 4. e5 Nd5 $146 { , while White's other 4th moves aren't dangerous. } ) 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { This is clearly the most testing move. It is not easy for White to develop the minor pieces on the queenside to good squares, so he decides to improve the queen and the rook to its best available squares: e2 for the queen and d1 for the rook. } 9... dxe5 $5 { There are other moves, but I like to play in a forcing way against this variation. First, we release tension in the center and force White to decide if he wants to take with the knight or the pawn. } 10. dxe5 Bd7 $1 { The key move in our system against the Alapin is to develop the bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal. It's important to avoid the natural move ...b6, for both concrete and positional reasons. the concerete reason is } ( 10... b6 $2 11. Rd1 Bb7 12. Nc3 $146 { and after 13...Bxf3? 14.Qxf3 , our rook on a8 is hanging! The positional reason is that the bishop will be protected on c6 by a pawn, which can be quite useful. } ) 11. Rd1 { The mainline, putting pressure on the d5-knight and centralizing the rook. } 11... Bc6 12. Nd4 Bc5 $1 { The strongest move, in my opinion. We improve the bishop and make contact with White's knight, which reduces White's mobility. } 13. Bxd5 $5 { This move looks a bit counterintuitive at first, as our knight on d5 was very strong, but now White's knight on b1 can come to c3 without allowing a trade. } 13... Bxd5 14. Nf5 $5 Qc7 $1 { The easiest. We are threatening to win a piece with ...Bc4 & ...exf5. } 15. Nc3 Bc4 16. Nh6+ $1 Kh8 ( 16... gxh6 { is dubious because of } 17. Qf3 Qxe5 18. Bxh6 Rc8 19. Qg4+ { and White gets material back and is better due to a better king. } 19... Kh8 20. Qxc4 $14 { the whole poing is that } 20... Bxf2+ { does not work } 21. Kxf2 Rxc4 22. Rd8# { Black gets it in the back rank! } ) 17. Qh5 gxh6 18. Qxh6 Qxe5 { White can force a draw with precise play according to the computer. It is clear he is the one who has to find it! } 19. Bg5 f6 20. Rd8 $3 { White has to find this brilliant move to draw the game. } 20... Qxg5 21. Rxf8+ Bxf8 22. Qxf8+ Qg8 23. Qxf6+ Qg7 $10 { With a perpetual check. } * 

