1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Nc6 4. Nc3 ( 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 $146 { transposes to 3.d4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 4... Nd4 $1 { We stop d4 by force. This already gives Black the easier game. } ( 4... g5 $2 { is worse than against 4.e2, because now after gxf3, the bishop on e2 is not hanging. } 5. d4 g4 6. d5 $14 { . } ) 5. Nxd4 ( 5. d3 Ne7 $146 { We plan to play ...Nec6 to strengthen our control over d4. White should take, leading to similar positions as against 5. Nxd4. } ) 5... cxd4 6. Ne2 e5 { We need to defend the pawn. These positions are very good for Black, but we should know the plans. In general, we want to exchange our bad bishop on f8. After that, White will usually try to untangle their kingside with either g3 & Bg2 or Ng3/Be2. In both cases, going for ...h5 and a kingside expansion is very good. In the first case, it is good because if White stops it with h4, then achieving f4 will be more difficult for them. If the knight is on g3, then ...h5 is a typical move to play against the knight. } 7. d3 Bb4+ $1 { It makes sense to exchange our bad bishop. } 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 d6 10. Ng3 h5 $1 { A explained above this is very strong. } 11. h4 g6 $15 { [%csl Rg3]We are clearly better: we have more space and our minor pieces are better. } * 

