1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nxc6 { This is rarely played, but it is actually a little tricky against our repertoire. } 6... dxc6 $5 { I feel this is worth the risk. } ( 6... bxc6 { is much more solid, but this move gives us good chances, because White has to walk a narrow path not to be worse. } ) 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. e5 ( 8. Nc3 $2 $146 e5 $15 { The d4-weakness gives us a better game. } ) 8... Ng4 9. f4 Bc5 { [%cal Gg4f2,Gg4e3]} 10. Nd2 $1 { [%cal Gg4f2,Bd2b3,Bb3c5][%csl Rc5]A strong novelty. The point is that ...Nf2 is met with Nb3. I feel this is difficult to see over the board. } 10... Ne3 $1 { We still go for this. } ( 10... Nf2 $2 $146 11. Nb3 $16 $146 ) 11. Ne4 $1 Bd4 { Now White has some computer-like lines they can try, but even then Black is fine. I give them as examples, but we do not really need to memorize them. } 12. Ke2 $1 ( 12. Rb1 Ke7 $13 { . } ) 12... Nxc4 13. Rb1 { We have some problems with our minor pieces. } 13... Nb6 14. Kd3 c5 15. b4 $1 { Undermining our bishop on d4. } 15... Nd7 16. bxc5 Bxc5 { We manage to save the piece, but we have to give the bishop pair. } 17. Nxc5 Nxc5+ 18. Ke3 Na4 $13 { [%cal Ga4b6,Gb6d5]An important move. We want to blockade the position with our knight on d5. White has compensation for the pawn, but not enough for an advantage. } * 

