1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 { The main move, defending the pawn on e4. } 6... Bc5 $5 { A much rarer move. 6...Bb4 is the most played by a large margin, but I feel this is a lesser-known alternative that is not worse and can also surprise our opponents. } 7. Nb3 { This is very natural, but it allows Black to get a better version of the 6...Bb4 line, because now White can no longer take on c6. } 7... Bb4 8. Bd3 d5 $1 { A key move, liberating our position. } 9. exd5 exd5 10. cxd5 Qxd5 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O { [%cal Gc8f5]Now we have a better pawn structure and intend to develop with ...Bf5, exchanging White's bishop pair, so White should act quickly. } 13. c4 Qd7 $1 { This looks strange, but it is the best square for the queen. We should not allow Bxh7+ tricks involving Qd6, and we can put pressure on the d3-bishop with ...Rd8. } 14. Bb2 Rd8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Be4 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Be6 $10 { The game was completely level in ½-½ Tari, A - Narayanan, S, 2023. } * 

