1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 { The main move, defending the pawn on e4. } 6... Bc5 $5 { A much rarer move. 6...Bb4 is the most played by a large margin, but I feel this is a lesser-known alternative that is not worse and can also surprise our opponents. } 7. Nc2 { A solid move, and probably White's best. } 7... Qb6 $1 { [%csl Rf2]Putting pressure on White's position since the start. } 8. Qd2 $1 { White's best. Now we do not have checks on b4, so Na4 is a threat. } 8... Ng4 $1 { We keep putting pressure on White's position. There are only two games in the database, and both were played by the rising star Lazavik. } 9. f3 Nf2 $1 10. Na4 Qc7 11. Nxc5 Nxh1 { A very interesting position. We are up an exchange, but our knight is stranded on h1. I feel that with good preparation, this is very interesting for us, in an already rare line. } 12. g3 Ne5 $1 { [%csl Rc5]} 13. Qe3 { Only move. } 13... O-O 14. b3 b5 $1 { Very strong play by Lazavik, further opening White's position. } 15. Bb2 { White cannot take on b5. } ( 15. cxb5 $2 d6 $17 ) 15... bxc4 16. O-O-O cxb3 17. axb3 d6 { There are alternatives, but there is nothing wrong with Lazavik's move. } 18. Bxe5 ( 18. Nd3 $2 $146 a5 $17 ) 18... dxe5 { A very complex position arose in 0-1 Pap, G - Lazavik, D, 2024. Black can give back material with Nxg3, getting two pieces against rook and two pawns kind of position. I like our chances because White's king is open. Objectively, it is around equal. } * 

