1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 { It looks a little bit strange to develop this bishop before the bishop on c1 after playing b3, but we also have to check it. } 4... Nge7 { The simplest, preparing to recapture with the knight on c6. } 5. O-O a6 ( 5... b6 $2 { This is also quite decent and should lead to similar play as the main lines. I give 5...a6 as the main line because it is more forcing and easier to remember, as it is more in the spirit of the Taimanov. } ) 6. Bxc6 Nxc6 7. Bb2 $6 { What could be more natural than this? But in fact, it is a mistake that hands over the initiative to Black. } 7... b5 $1 { [%cal Gc8b7]} 8. d3 Bb7 9. Nbd2 f6 $15 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8]Black has a comfortable position with their bishop pair. } * 

