1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb5 { It looks a little bit strange to develop this bishop before the bishop on c1 after playing b3, but we also have to check it. } 4... Nge7 { The simplest, preparing to recapture with the knight on c6. } 5. O-O a6 ( 5... b6 $2 { This is also quite decent and should lead to similar play as the main lines. I give 5...a6 as the main line because it is more forcing and easier to remember, as it is more in the spirit of the Taimanov. } ) 6. Bxc6 Nxc6 7. d4 { The best move, opening the center and avoiding the typical ...Qf6 pin. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qc7 { Taimanov style! } ( 8... Qf6 $2 { This is the way to go with the bishop on b2, but here White can play more actively and avoid the pin with } 9. Be3 $36 ) 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 ( 9... dxc6 10. Ba3 $2 { looks a little bit unpleasant. We should also equalize with a little bit of care. White's point is that after } 10... c5 11. Bb2 { we can no longer push ...e5 so freely, because the knight on b1 gets the d5-square. } ) 10. Re1 b5 { We first develop the queenside bishop. } 11. Bb2 Bb7 12. Nd2 Qb6 $5 { Threatening ...Bc5, developing with tempo. } 13. Qf3 f6 $1 { [%cal Gf8e7]We finally block White's bishop on b2. White should act quickly because in the long run we have the better odds with our bishop pair. A sample line goes: } 14. c4 Be7 15. Qh5+ g6 16. Qh6 Bf8 17. Qh4 e5 $13 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8f7,Gb6e6]Black has no problems in this complex position. Our plan is simple: protect everything, keep our position compact, and try to complete development under favorable conditions. } * 

