1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb2 a6 { Preparing ...d5 under better circumstances. } ( 4... d5 $2 5. Bb5 { Taking on e4 is quite bad and Black's position is unpleasant. } ) 5. d4 $6 { This is maybe the most natural, but we can exploit the fact that the bishop on b2 is undefended. } 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qf6 $1 { The key move. White cannot develop comfortably with the pin. } 7. Be2 Bc5 8. c3 Nge7 { There is no need to enter the complications that arise after 8...Qg6. } 9. O-O O-O $37 { It is not easy for White to develop the b1-knight, and their pieces look strange. We can play ...b5 or ...d5, depending on what White does, and our position looks nice. } * 

