1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb2 a6 { Preparing ...d5 under better circumstances. } ( 4... d5 $2 5. Bb5 { Taking on e4 is quite bad and Black's position is unpleasant. } ) 5. Bd3 { This move is typical in these systems. Here it is not very good, and the refutation is actually quite instructive. } 5... d6 $1 6. O-O e5 $3 { The key move for Black. We stop e5 for once and for all, and the bishop on d3 is quite misplaced now. Also, we see that we can generate a lot of play on the kingside now that the center is closed. } 7. Nc3 g6 { White is more developed, but the problem for him is that the position is closed and their pieces are actually not standing on good squares. Our last move is quite instructive: we move again another pawn, because we want to develop our pieces to their optimal squares! This will actually save time and it is White who is playing for equality in this position. } 8. Ne1 Bg7 9. Nd5 Nge7 10. f4 O-O $15 { Black's position is great, White's activity is optical. } * 

