1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb2 a6 { Preparing ...d5 under better circumstances. } ( 4... d5 $2 5. Bb5 { Taking on e4 is quite bad and Black's position is unpleasant. } ) 5. Be2 Nf6 $1 { The most critical move, forcing White to make a decision in the center. } 6. e5 { The critical move, but this reduces the scope of the b2 bishop. } 6... Nd5 { [%cal Gd5f4]} 7. O-O Nf4 $1 8. Re1 d5 $1 ( 8... Nxe2+ $2 $146 9. Qxe2 { Taking on e2 would be a mistake, the bishop on e2 was not a great piece and we are slightly cramped. } ) 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. Bf1 { Taking on g7 was obviously not possible because of ...Rg8. } 10... O-O $10 { Black has a very playable position. If White pushes d4 we can take and go ...Be5, and if he does not play d4 then e5 is coming, with a nice position with more space in the center. This is not a pawn sacrifice, for example: } 11. Na3 e5 12. Nxe5 $2 ( 12. Nc4 $146 f5 $10 ) 12... Qg5 $19 { [%cal Gf4h3][%csl Re5]} * 

