1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb2 a6 { Preparing ...d5 under better circumstances. } ( 4... d5 $2 5. Bb5 { Taking on e4 is quite bad and Black's position is unpleasant. } ) 5. c4 { The main move, stopping ...d5. } 5... Nf6 $1 { We have already seen this idea. It makes sense to provoke e5, because it limits the scope of the bishop on b2. } 6. e5 Ng4 7. h3 Nh6 8. Nc3 $5 { [%cal Gc3e4]This allows us to bring the knight to d4, but White also has Ne4 ideas to target our d6 weak square. } 8... Nf5 9. Bd3 Nfd4 10. Ne4 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 d5 12. exd6 f5 $1 13. Nxc5 Qxd6 { Our idea is that White's knight is trapped! Unfortunately, White can save it. } 14. b4 $1 Nxb4 15. a3 Nc6 16. Nb3 { White has managed to save the piece, but we can win the dark-squared bishop with } 16... Ne5 $1 17. Bxe5 Qxe5+ 18. Be2 Bd6 19. d4 Qf4 $10 { Black is fine in the endgame. Our structure is a little bit weak, but the bishop pair compensates. } * 

