1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb2 a6 { Preparing ...d5 under better circumstances. } ( 4... d5 $2 5. Bb5 { Taking on e4 is quite bad and Black's position is unpleasant. } ) 5. c4 { The main move, stopping ...d5. } 5... Nf6 $1 { We have already seen this idea. It makes sense to provoke e5, because it limits the scope of the bishop on b2. } 6. e5 Ng4 7. h3 Nh6 8. g4 $5 { The most ambitious move. White wants to leave our knight out of the game. But we have enough counterplay. } 8... d5 $1 { Our threat is ...d4, leaving White's bishop out of the game, so White has to take. } 9. exd6 f6 $1 { An important immediate move. We want to take on d6 with the bishop, not the queen. } 10. d4 { Otherwise Black can play ...e5 and lead White with a very strange pawn structure. } 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd6 { Now it makes sense to take with the queen to avoid wrecking our pawn structure. } 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Rg1 Bd7 $13 { [%csl Re1]We're going to castle long. We have a better pawn structure, and the knight can re-enter the game via f7. White's king can also become very vulnerable. While the engine may call it equal, in practice, I think this is already quite dangerous for White. } * 

