1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... Nc6 4. Bb2 a6 { Preparing ...d5 under better circumstances. } ( 4... d5 $2 5. Bb5 { Taking on e4 is quite bad and Black's position is unpleasant. } ) 5. c4 { The main move, stopping ...d5. } 5... Nf6 $1 { We have already seen this idea. It makes sense to provoke e5, because it limits the scope of the bishop on b2. } 6. e5 Ng4 7. g3 { White resists the temptation to threaten our knight and instead prepares the development of the bishop. } 7... d6 $1 { I like this move, immediately challenging the pawn on e5. } ( 7... Qc7 { is also playable, but we have to be prepared against both the dangerous pawn sacrifice } 8. Bg2 $2 { , a specialty of Niemann, and 8.Qe2, the main line. } ) 8. exd6 Bxd6 $1 { 8...f6 is also possible, but I think this pawn sacrifice is very strong. It gives us a good initiative for the pawn and changes the character of the game. } ( 8... f6 $2 9. d4 { The most dangerous move. } 9... Bxd6 10. h3 Nh6 $146 11. Nc3 $146 Nf5 $146 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qxd8+ Nxd8 $146 14. Bg2 { The endgame looks a little bit more pleasant to play as white. } ) 9. Bxg7 { The only critical move. } 9... Rg8 10. Bb2 b6 { This is the way to go. We develop the light-squared bishop to its best possible square, which also allows for a quick ...O-O-O. } ( 10... e5 $2 11. Nc3 $146 f5 $2 12. d3 $16 { White has a significant advantage, our center is not mobile at all. } ) 11. Bg2 Bb7 12. Qe2 { White intends to castle long with this move. } 12... Qd7 $1 { We prepare to castle long ourselves. } 13. O-O O-O-O $133 { [%cal Gd6c7,Gh7h5,Gc6d4]In general, Black has very good compensation for the pawn with their active pieces and the open g-file. } * 

