1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 { This is the King's Indian Attack, or KIA. White develops with g3, Bg2, O-O and Re1, and often e4-e5, Bf4 and Nbd2. They want to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5 and Nd2-f1-h2-g4. We'll take all the space we can on the queenside and spoil the fun for White! } ( 3. g3 d5 4. d3 { is looked at under the 3.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) file. } 4... Nc6 $146 { This is another move order that can lead to this line. } ) 3... Nc6 { I like to start with this natural move. } 4. Qe2 { Trying to avoid ...d5 is possible, but not very dangerous from an objective point of view. The queen is misplaced on e2 when there is no pawn on d5. } 4... g6 $1 { Note that this move is possible because the queen has left d1 and there is no d4 idea. } 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 d6 7. O-O e5 $1 { [%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8,Gf7f5]Stopping any active possibility White could have in the center. We have a very nice position and already are playing for an advantage. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "3.d3: 4.g3 / 5.Bg2"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.d3: 4.g3 / 5.Bg2"]
[Black "30) 3.d3 (King's Indian Attack)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 { This is the King's Indian Attack, or KIA. White develops with g3, Bg2, O-O and Re1, and often e4-e5, Bf4 and Nbd2. They want to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5 and Nd2-f1-h2-g4. We'll take all the space we can on the queenside and spoil the fun for White! } ( 3. g3 d5 4. d3 { is looked at under the 3.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) file. } 4... Nc6 $146 { This is another move order that can lead to this line. } ) 3... Nc6 { I like to start with this natural move. } 4. g3 d5 5. Bg2 $6 { This is very soft and actually, just quite bad for White. } 5... dxe4 $1 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 b6 $15 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gc8a6,Gg8f6,Ge8c8]Black already has an initiative. The normal plan for White would be to play c3 & Kc2, but this is not possible in this position because it weakens the d3-square too much and Black can take advantage of it with a quick ...Ba6 & ...O-O-O. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "3.d3: 4.g3 / 5.Nbd2 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.d3: 4.g3 / 5.Nbd2 #1"]
[Black "30) 3.d3 (King's Indian Attack)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 { This is the King's Indian Attack, or KIA. White develops with g3, Bg2, O-O and Re1, and often e4-e5, Bf4 and Nbd2. They want to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5 and Nd2-f1-h2-g4. We'll take all the space we can on the queenside and spoil the fun for White! } ( 3. g3 d5 4. d3 { is looked at under the 3.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) file. } 4... Nc6 $146 { This is another move order that can lead to this line. } ) 3... Nc6 { I like to start with this natural move. } 4. g3 d5 5. Nbd2 { This is the traditional way to play the King's Indian Attack. There are many ways of equalizing here: for example, the ...Nf6, ...Be7 set-up that we play against Qe2 is now even better. But as everything equalizes, I want to give an idea that does not give White the typical King's Indian Attack initiative in the kingside White players enjoy. } 5... Bd6 $5 { I quite like this set-up. e5 loses meaning and we have f6-ideas to break White's center in case that happens. We plan to develop harmoniously with ...Nge7, ...O-O, ...b6, ...Bb7. } 6. Bg2 Nge7 { As we said, we enjoy good control over e5 and White will find it difficult to generate any play on the kingside now that the knight on the kingside is not a target. } 7. O-O O-O 8. c3 a5 $5 ( 8... b6 { and developing more modestly with ...Bb7 is also possible, but I like the bishop on a6. } ) 9. a4 b6 10. Re1 Ba6 11. exd5 Nxd5 $1 { [%cal Ga8a7,Ga7d7,Gd6c7]It is very important to take with the knight on d5, and it is actually a difficult positional decision because we give up a lot of juicy squares like c4. But we need to keep putting pressure on d3 and our knight on d5 is very strong too. } 12. Nc4 { [%csl Gc4]} 12... h6 { [%cal Gd6c7,Gd8d7,Ga8d8,Gf8e8][%csl Gf8]Avoiding Ng5 ideas. } 13. Na3 ( 13. Nfd2 $146 Ra7 { with counterplay. } ) 13... Ra7 $1 { This is the idea I wanted to show you. The rook on a8 was not doing too much, and instead of developing more normally with ...Qd7 & ...Rd7, it makes quite a lot of sense to put the rook in front of the queen! } 14. Nb5 Rd7 { [%cal Gd6b8,Ge6e5,Gf8e8,Gc6a7]The position is complex but I would take Black in a practical game. } * 

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Cuenca's Taimanov Sicilian"]
[Site "3.d3: 4.g3 / 5.Nbd2 #2"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.d3: 4.g3 / 5.Nbd2 #2"]
[Black "30) 3.d3 (King's Indian Attack)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 { This is the King's Indian Attack, or KIA. White develops with g3, Bg2, O-O and Re1, and often e4-e5, Bf4 and Nbd2. They want to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5 and Nd2-f1-h2-g4. We'll take all the space we can on the queenside and spoil the fun for White! } ( 3. g3 d5 4. d3 { is looked at under the 3.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) file. } 4... Nc6 $146 { This is another move order that can lead to this line. } ) 3... Nc6 { I like to start with this natural move. } 4. g3 d5 5. Nbd2 { This is the traditional way to play the King's Indian Attack. There are many ways of equalizing here: for example, the ...Nf6, ...Be7 set-up that we play against Qe2 is now even better. But as everything equalizes, I want to give an idea that does not give White the typical King's Indian Attack initiative in the kingside White players enjoy. } 5... Bd6 $5 { I quite like this set-up. e5 loses meaning and we have f6-ideas to break White's center in case that happens. We plan to develop harmoniously with ...Nge7, ...O-O, ...b6, ...Bb7. } 6. Bg2 Nge7 { As we said, we enjoy good control over e5 and White will find it difficult to generate any play on the kingside now that the knight on the kingside is not a target. } 7. O-O O-O 8. Nh4 { Trying to play f4 is common, but our knight on e7 is perfectly placed in such positions. } 8... Rb8 9. f4 b5 { [%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Gc8a6]White lacks constructive ideas in the kingside. For example: } 10. f5 $6 exf5 11. exf5 f6 { [%cal Gc6d4,Ga7a5]White's attack has come to a dead end. } * 

