1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 { This is the King's Indian Attack, or KIA. White develops with g3, Bg2, O-O and Re1, and often e4-e5, Bf4 and Nbd2. They want to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5 and Nd2-f1-h2-g4. We'll take all the space we can on the queenside and spoil the fun for White! } ( 3. g3 d5 4. d3 { is looked at under the 3.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) file. } 4... Nc6 $146 { This is another move order that can lead to this line. } ) 3... Nc6 { I like to start with this natural move. } 4. g3 d5 5. Nbd2 { This is the traditional way to play the King's Indian Attack. There are many ways of equalizing here: for example, the ...Nf6, ...Be7 set-up that we play against Qe2 is now even better. But as everything equalizes, I want to give an idea that does not give White the typical King's Indian Attack initiative in the kingside White players enjoy. } 5... Bd6 $5 { I quite like this set-up. e5 loses meaning and we have f6-ideas to break White's center in case that happens. We plan to develop harmoniously with ...Nge7, ...O-O, ...b6, ...Bb7. } 6. Bg2 Nge7 { As we said, we enjoy good control over e5 and White will find it difficult to generate any play on the kingside now that the knight on the kingside is not a target. } 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 { The most natural and most played move. } 8... b6 9. e5 ( 9. c3 { is also possible, but after } 9... a5 { the ideas are very similar to the ones we saw in the 8.c3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) line. } ) 9... Bc7 10. c3 { Forced, as Nf1 runs into ...Ng6. } 10... a5 $1 { [%cal Gc8a6][%csl Rd3]Similarly to the 8.c3 line,we immediately exploit White's last move and try to get a grip on the light-squares in the queenside. } 11. Nf1 a4 12. h4 b5 13. N1h2 f6 $1 { I want you to remember this idea, stopping White's attack in its tracks and giving air to our king. } 14. exf6 gxf6 $13 { [%cal Gf8f7,Gg8h8,Ge7f5]White does not have a mating attack and we can even think of generating some kingside play. } * 

