1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 { This is the King's Indian Attack, or KIA. White develops with g3, Bg2, O-O and Re1, and often e4-e5, Bf4 and Nbd2. They want to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5 and Nd2-f1-h2-g4. We'll take all the space we can on the queenside and spoil the fun for White! } ( 3. g3 d5 4. d3 { is looked at under the 3.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) file. } 4... Nc6 $146 { This is another move order that can lead to this line. } ) 3... Nc6 { I like to start with this natural move. } 4. g3 d5 5. Qe2 { This is the most testing move. White avoids the queen exchange and places their queen on its best square in this positions, e2, from where it supports the e5-pawn push. } 5... Be7 { Avoiding exd5 ideas. } 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. a4 $5 { A recent tried idea that has enjoyed some popularity, being played by players like Giri and Grandellius. White stops ...b5 mechanically! It slows down our counterplay in the queenside in many positions and the a3-knight is an interesting square for White's knight. } 7... dxe4 $1 { A radical solution! We do not want to allow e5 if it is not under our conditions, that is, if we do not get quick counterplay on the queenside with ...b5. } 8. dxe4 e5 $1 { Stopping e5 is necessary. } 9. O-O Nd4 10. Nxd4 cxd4 $15 { [%cal Ge8g8][%csl Rc2,Rg2]is completely fine for Black. The pawn on c2 can end up being week in this kind of position, and the bishop on g2 is passive. } * 

