1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 { This is the King's Indian Attack, or KIA. White develops with g3, Bg2, O-O and Re1, and often e4-e5, Bf4 and Nbd2. They want to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5 and Nd2-f1-h2-g4. We'll take all the space we can on the queenside and spoil the fun for White! } ( 3. g3 d5 4. d3 { is looked at under the 3.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) file. } 4... Nc6 $146 { This is another move order that can lead to this line. } ) 3... Nc6 { I like to start with this natural move. } 4. g3 d5 5. Qe2 { This is the most testing move. White avoids the queen exchange and places their queen on its best square in this positions, e2, from where it supports the e5-pawn push. } 5... Be7 { Avoiding exd5 ideas. } 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O b5 $1 { A very important move! I think the positions in the main King's Indian Attack can be dangerous when White gets their pawn to c4, incrementing their influence over the light squares in the center. } ( 7... O-O 8. e5 Nd7 $146 9. c4 d4 10. h4 $36 { This kind of position can get dangerous for us. It is not clear how to generate queenside counterplay with the pawn on c4, and White is perfectly placed for a possible ...f6 break. } ) 8. Nc3 { This looks strange to me. } 8... b4 9. exd5 exd5 10. Na4 O-O { [%cal Gc8f5,Gf8e8,Gd8a5]All of White's pieces seem kind of misplaced, it is actually surprising for me that the machine says this is still equal. ...Qa5, ...Bf5, ...Re8 are three good moves we can play on semi-autopilot. } * 

