1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 { This is the King's Indian Attack, or KIA. White develops with g3, Bg2, O-O and Re1, and often e4-e5, Bf4 and Nbd2. They want to launch a kingside attack with h4-h5 and Nd2-f1-h2-g4. We'll take all the space we can on the queenside and spoil the fun for White! } ( 3. g3 d5 4. d3 { is looked at under the 3.g3 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) file. } 4... Nc6 $146 { This is another move order that can lead to this line. } ) 3... Nc6 { I like to start with this natural move. } 4. g3 d5 5. Qe2 { This is the most testing move. White avoids the queen exchange and places their queen on its best square in this positions, e2, from where it supports the e5-pawn push. } 5... Be7 { Avoiding exd5 ideas. } 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O b5 $1 { A very important move! I think the positions in the main King's Indian Attack can be dangerous when White gets their pawn to c4, incrementing their influence over the light squares in the center. } ( 7... O-O 8. e5 Nd7 $146 9. c4 d4 10. h4 $36 { This kind of position can get dangerous for us. It is not clear how to generate queenside counterplay with the pawn on c4, and White is perfectly placed for a possible ...f6 break. } ) 8. exd5 { The critical move, trying to punish us for playing ...b5 without castling. } 8... exd5 9. c4 bxc4 10. dxc4 Ba6 11. Na3 O-O { [%cal Gd8b6,Gf8e8,Ga8d8]The position is quite tense and around equal. Next we plan to activate our major pieces. } * 

