1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. e5 { This advance cannot be dangerous. There are many ways to equalize, but since this is a Taimanov and not a French course, I recommend playing in a very concrete way. } 4... Nc6 5. Bg2 f6 $1 { The simplest approach. } 6. Qe2 fxe5 7. Nxe5 Nd4 { A nice novelty. It seems Black has blundered, but it is White who has miscalculated! } 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Nxg6 $2 { 9.Qd1 should be preferred. } 9... Nf6 10. Qh4 hxg6 11. Qxh8 Nxc2+ $19 * 

