1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. e5 { This advance cannot be dangerous. There are many ways to equalize, but since this is a Taimanov and not a French course, I recommend playing in a very concrete way. } 4... Nc6 5. Bg2 f6 $1 { The simplest approach. } 6. exf6 Nxf6 7. O-O Bd6 8. d4 O-O $133 { [%cal Ge6d5][%csl Rg2]Black's position looks really comfortable in this French structure. The bishop on g2 looks quite odd. } * 

