1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bg2 Qe7+ $1 { A key moment. This check is quite unpleasant for White. } 6. Kf1 Nc6 7. d4 Be6 { This has not been played but I find it fairly natural and the machine likes it. We develop the bishop and prepare to put our queen on d7, a better square. } 8. Nc3 Qd7 { The position is not forced, so it is difficult to analyze in more detail. In practice, I think Black's position is a lot easier to play. Our intentions are not so clear, and actually we can castle both sides. } * 

