1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bg2 Qe7+ $1 { A key moment. This check is quite unpleasant for White. } 6. Qe2 Nc6 $5 { Taking on e2 is also possible, but after Re1 White will castle artificially and it is not clear who has lost tempos. I think developing to c6 immediately is slightly more precise. } 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. O-O d4 9. Qxe7+ Bxe7 10. Nb5 O-O { Black has no weaknesses and stands completely fine. } * 

