1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bg2 Qe7+ $1 { A key moment. This check is quite unpleasant for White. } 6. Qe2 Nc6 $5 { Taking on e2 is also possible, but after Re1 White will castle artificially and it is not clear who has lost tempos. I think developing to c6 immediately is slightly more precise. } 7. Qxe7+ Ngxe7 $5 { Also decent, but I think the f5-square is good for our knight. } 8. O-O Be6 { [%cal Ge8c8,Gh7h6]Black has completely equalized. White's position is cramped and we do not have any weaknesses, again I think that we have already the better side of equality. } * 

