1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 { The only critical move. } 5... cxd4 $5 { The modern approach, recently played by top players such as Nepomniachtchi, Gelfand, and Dubov. 5...Nc6 and 5...Nf6 are also decent, but it is interesting to open the center and play very concretely. } 6. Bg2 $6 { This clever move has been seen in practice, but it hands over the initiative to Black. } ( 6. Bb5+ Nc6 $146 7. Nxd4 $146 { transposes to 6.Nxd4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) } ) 6... Bb4+ $1 7. Nbd2 Qe7+ 8. Qe2 ( 8. Kf1 Nc6 $146 { Black had the initiative in 0-1 Belenkaya, D \- Arabidze, M Germany, 2023. } ) 8... Nc6 9. Qxe7+ Ngxe7 10. O-O Bf5 $15 { White does not manage to recover their pawn! } * 

