1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 { The only critical move. } 5... cxd4 $5 { The modern approach, recently played by top players such as Nepomniachtchi, Gelfand, and Dubov. 5...Nc6 and 5...Nf6 are also decent, but it is interesting to open the center and play very concretely. } 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bb5 { A decent try, although it has only been played once. White plays energetically to capitalize on our king still being on e8. } 7... Bd7 8. O-O Nf6 9. c4 { The best move—White wants to make the most of their development advantage. } 9... Be7 10. Nc3 a6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Ba4 O-O { Black is fine and the position should end in a draw after mass exchanges. } 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 15. Bxd7 Qxd7 $10 { [%cal Ge7f6][%csl Rb2,Rd5]} * 

