1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 { The only critical move. } 5... cxd4 $5 { The modern approach, recently played by top players such as Nepomniachtchi, Gelfand, and Dubov. 5...Nc6 and 5...Nf6 are also decent, but it is interesting to open the center and play very concretely. } 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 $5 { A very interesting try by Shankland. By overprotecting the d4-knight, White avoids our concrete play. } 7... Nf6 8. Bg2 Bg4 { Gelfand actually started with } ( 8... Bb4+ { check in his game, but it actually does not make much of a difference. } ) 9. Qd3 { The best move. } ( 9. f3 $2 { would unnecessarily break White's coordination. } ) 9... Bb4+ $1 { The start of a strong maneuver. The b6-square is better than the d6-square, because it is fighting for the d4-square and it allows our queen to defend the d5-pawn. } 10. c3 Ba5 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2 { Both sides are playing very logically, completing development. } 12... Bb6 13. Rfe1 Re8 { We also bring the rook to the only open file. } 14. N2f3 Qd7 $5 { I think this is a small improvement over Gelfand's game. We just connect the rooks, and now All of our pieces are on good squares as compensation for the isolated d5-pawn. } ( 14... Bh5 15. Bg5 Rxe1+ 16. Rxe1 h6 17. Be3 { also fine, but Black later faced some problems in ½-½ Shankland,S (2711)-Gelfand,B (2668) Prague Masters 5th 2023. } ) 15. Rad1 ( 15. Bg5 { can be met with . } ) 15... Na5 $13 { I wanted to show this idea. The c4-square would be excellent for our knight, and after 15... Qd7 15.a4 Na5= Again the same idea. Black has a perfectly healthy position. } 16. b3 Rac8 { , we have managed to provoke a small weakness in White's camp. } * 

