1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 { The only critical move. } 5... cxd4 $5 { The modern approach, recently played by top players such as Nepomniachtchi, Gelfand, and Dubov. 5...Nc6 and 5...Nf6 are also decent, but it is interesting to open the center and play very concretely. } 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Nc3 { Another tricky attempt designed against or move order, because 7... Bc5 does not work. } 7... Nf6 ( 7... Bc5 $2 { a human move but after } 8. Be3 { we are in trouble } 8... Qb6 $2 9. Nxd5 $146 { . } ) 8. Bg2 Bg4 $1 { A typical and strong move, developing with tempo and forcing a concession by White. } 9. Nde2 Bb4 10. h3 Bxc3+ { We give up the bishop pair, but destroy White's pawn structure. } 11. bxc3 Bf5 $1 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxd5 Bxc2 $10 { We recover the pawn and have a fine position. We even have the better pawn structure, though White's slight initiative compensates for it. } * 

