1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 { The only critical move. } 5... cxd4 $5 { The modern approach, recently played by top players such as Nepomniachtchi, Gelfand, and Dubov. 5...Nc6 and 5...Nf6 are also decent, but it is interesting to open the center and play very concretely. } 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 { The most natural move and the one that has been played the most. } 7... Bc5 { Now White has many moves again. } 8. Nxc6 { This is, of course, possible, but it is difficult to believe that White can fight for an advantage without us having an isolated pawn on d5. } 8... bxc6 9. O-O Nf6 10. c4 $6 { This looks standard, but it can become very dangerous for White with their undeveloped queenside, as we will see. } 10... O-O 11. cxd5 $6 { White's idea, but it is another slight mistake. } 11... Ba6 $1 12. Re1 cxd5 13. Nc3 Qb6 $1 { All of our pieces are in fantastic squares. In the two practical games that reached this position, White miscalculated. } 14. Be3 $2 d4 $1 15. Na4 dxe3 $3 { A beautiful queen sacrifice! } 16. Nxb6 exf2+ 17. Kh1 fxe1=Q+ 18. Qxe1 Bxb6 19. Bxa8 Rxa8 { Black is completely winning, because we have a mating attack against White's king. The game will soon finish. } 20. h3 Re8 21. Qc3 ( 21. Qd1 Re2 { 0-1 McShane, L - Lagarde, M London, 2021. } ) 21... Bb7+ * 

