1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 { The only critical move. } 5... cxd4 $5 { The modern approach, recently played by top players such as Nepomniachtchi, Gelfand, and Dubov. 5...Nc6 and 5...Nf6 are also decent, but it is interesting to open the center and play very concretely. } 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 { The most natural move and the one that has been played the most. } 7... Bc5 { Now White has many moves again. } 8. Nb3 { The most natural-looking move, attacking the bishop and the d5-pawn simultaneously. } 8... Qe7+ $1 { The point! We are not losing material. } 9. Qe2 Bb6 10. Be3 $5 { White's most interesting try, in my opinion. } 10... Bxe3 11. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 12. fxe3 { White has ruined their pawn structure, but he gains more control of the dark squares. } 12... Be6 13. Nc3 O-O-O $1 { This is the idea. I think it makes sense to castle queenside, because the rook defends d5 and we can push on the kingside for counterplay. } 14. O-O-O Nf6 15. Nd4 h5 $1 { Executing our idea! We don't just sit back as White maneuvers around our isolated pawn; instead, we actively seek counterplay on the kingside. } 16. h3 Rh6 $10 { Very nice! We have sufficient counterplay, and Black was soon slightly better, although the position is balanced at the moment. } * 

