1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4 { A slightly different version of the Wing Gambit with 2. b4 that we should take a look at because we play with a quick ...d5 there. I like a different approach, taking advantage that the pawn on b4 is now defended. } 3... cxb4 4. a3 Nf6 $1 { A strong move. The knight will be safe on d5 momentarily, because the pawn on b4 helps avoid c4. If White takes on b4, then we can develop our bishop with tempo. } 5. e5 { The only decent move to try and develop an initiative. } 5... Nd5 6. axb4 Nxb4 $5 { This looks strange. It looks much more normal to take with the bishop, but this has a point: we can play ...d6 and challenge White's center. With ...Bxb4, it is more difficult to play ...d6 because the bishop is in an awkward spot. } ( 6... Bxb4 { is uncomfortable for Black: } 7. Na3 $146 d6 $2 8. c3 Bc5 9. d4 ) 7. Ba3 { Trying to play c3 and prevent us from castling, but we can easily avoid this. } 7... Be7 $1 8. d4 a5 $5 { I like this move, giving more support to our knight. } 9. Be2 b6 $1 { The bishop on b7 will be a strong piece, and it will also defend our rook on a8. } 10. O-O Bb7 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d6]Now that the rook is defended, we have an easy plan to castle and play ...d6, challenging White's center. We are a pawn up meanwhile. } * 

