1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b4 { A slightly different version of the Wing Gambit with 2. b4 that we should take a look at because we play with a quick ...d5 there. I like a different approach, taking advantage that the pawn on b4 is now defended. } 3... cxb4 4. a3 Nf6 $1 { A strong move. The knight will be safe on d5 momentarily, because the pawn on b4 helps avoid c4. If White takes on b4, then we can develop our bishop with tempo. } 5. e5 { The only decent move to try and develop an initiative. } 5... Nd5 6. axb4 Nxb4 $5 { This looks strange. It looks much more normal to take with the bishop, but this has a point: we can play ...d6 and challenge White's center. With ...Bxb4, it is more difficult to play ...d6 because the bishop is in an awkward spot. } ( 6... Bxb4 { is uncomfortable for Black: } 7. Na3 $146 d6 $2 8. c3 Bc5 9. d4 ) 7. c3 ( 7. d4 d6 { should lead us to the main line, because White's best follow up is . } ) 7... Nd5 8. d4 d6 $1 { We again see this key theme. It is very important to challenge White's center. } 9. Ba3 dxe5 $1 { Now that our knight cannot reach the b4-square, I like this move better than ...Be7. } 10. Bxf8 Kxf8 { We lose our right to castle, but we are still a pawn up, and White is not able to generate enough initiative to compensate for their pawn deficit. } 11. dxe5 Bd7 $1 { White was threatening c4, which we avoid with this move. } 12. Be2 g6 $15 { [%cal Gf8g7,Gd7c6,Gb8d7]We are slowly consolidating and White is going to struggle to prove compensation for their pawn. } * 

