1. e4 c5 2. b4 { A very dubious gambit. } 2... cxb4 3. d4 d5 $1 { Fighting for the central squares. } 4. e5 { With our pawn on e6, this would be decent, but here we can bring the bishop out. } 4... Nc6 5. a3 Qb6 { Defending the pawn on b4 and putting pressure on d4. } 6. Be3 Bf5 { This is the key move. If we play } ( 6... e6 { , then White can claim they have some compensation in this French-like position, but with the bishop out of the pawn chain, White does not have anything to show for the pawn. } ) * 

