1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 { This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central d4-square. This chapter is also given in my Kalashnikov Sicilian Lifetime Repertoire. } 3. f4 { The Grand Prix attack is decent when Black has already played ...d6, but the possibility of playing ...d5 in one go makes a big difference. I think Black is already playing for an advantage here. } ( 3. Nf3 $146 e6 { transposes to other chapters. } ) 3... g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 { This is the old-fashioned continuation. White wants to provoke ...e6 and then try to mate us with f5, but fortunately for us, it is not going to happen. } 5... e6 6. f5 { The thematic pawn push, but it just does not work when the pawn is on d7. } 6... gxf5 ( 6... Nge7 $146 { If you do not want to remember anything. This move forces White to take on e6 and also gives Black an advantage. } ) 7. d3 { The most common continuation. } 7... Nge7 8. O-O O-O { Not seeing any ghosts. We are a pawn up, and our kingside is solid enough. } 9. Qe1 fxe4 10. dxe4 d5 11. exd5 exd5 12. Bd3 Ng6 { White does not have sufficient compensation for the pawn. } * 

