1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 { This move is going to be our recommendation. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central d4-square. This chapter is also given in my Kalashnikov Sicilian Lifetime Repertoire. } 3. f4 { The Grand Prix attack is decent when Black has already played ...d6, but the possibility of playing ...d5 in one go makes a big difference. I think Black is already playing for an advantage here. } ( 3. Nf3 $146 e6 { transposes to other chapters. } ) 3... g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 { Tari has been playing this move a lot (even in classical chess against Duda), so we should pay attention. } 5... Nd4 { This is our standard reaction when White plays Bb5 with a knight on c3. } 6. O-O { The modern move. } 6... a6 { Duda took on b5, which is the main move, but refraining from taking the bishop is easier. } 7. Bc4 { This plays into Black's hands. } 7... b5 8. Bd5 Rb8 9. d3 e6 10. Bb3 Bb7 { Surprisingly, there are over 100 games in this position. Black is just much better, as we have more control of the center and better development. } * 

