1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 { This move is going to be our recommendation. This material is recycled from my Kalashnikov Sicilian Lifetime Repertoire. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central d4-square. } 3. g3 { The Closed Sicilian is not dangerous from a theoretical point of view, and there are many ways to equalize, but it is important to know one good set-up. } ( 3. Nf3 $146 e6 { transposes. } ) 3... g6 { I really like the fianchetto versus the Closed Sicilian. The bishop on g7 will be our best minor piece. } 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 Rb8 $1 { One of the advantages of playing ...Nc6 on move 2 (something Najdorf players cannot do!) is having this quick ...Rb8. I have always felt that gaining space on the queenside as quickly as possible is one of the strongest ways to meet these fianchetto set-ups. } 6. Be3 b5 $1 { We do not need to defend the c5-pawn just yet. } 7. Bxc5 Qa5 $1 { [%cal Gb5b4]} 8. Be3 b4 9. Nce2 Bxb2 { We gain back our pawn. } 10. Rb1 b3+ $1 { There are alternatives, but this makes things clearer. We should remember the following forced sequence. } 11. Bd2 bxc2 12. Qxc2 Nb4 $1 { We keep playing powerful active moves. } 13. Qb3 Qa3 $1 14. Nf4 Qxb3 15. axb3 Be5 { [%cal Ge5f4,Gb4d3,Ge7e6,Gc8a6]The position is symmetrical, but we have a small initiative. } * 

