1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 { This move is going to be our recommendation. This material is recycled from my Kalashnikov Sicilian Lifetime Repertoire. It is a great square for the knight, controlling the important central d4-square. } 3. g3 { The Closed Sicilian is not dangerous from a theoretical point of view, and there are many ways to equalize, but it is important to know one good set-up. } ( 3. Nf3 $146 e6 { transposes. } ) 3... g6 { I really like the fianchetto versus the Closed Sicilian. The bishop on g7 will be our best minor piece. } 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 Rb8 $1 { One of the advantages of playing ...Nc6 on move 2 (something Najdorf players cannot do!) is having this quick ...Rb8. I have always felt that gaining space on the queenside as quickly as possible is one of the strongest ways to meet these fianchetto set-ups. } 6. f4 b5 7. Nf3 b4 8. Ne2 d6 9. O-O Nf6 10. h3 { White's typical attack in the Closed Sicilian is to launch an attack on the kingside. } 10... Nd7 $1 { It is a good idea to postpone castling; this way, White's attack loses strength. } 11. g4 Qb6 12. Kh1 Bb7 13. f5 { The logical continuation, but White relinquishes on the central dark squares with this move. } 13... Nce5 $1 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 { [%cal Gc5c4,Gh7h5,Gb7a6]Black position looks very good, we can keep the king on e8 because it is very safe there and play on both sides of the board. } * 

