[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.g3 Lasker-Dunne Attack #1"]
[Black "35) Rare 2nd Moves"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. g3 { White wants to play a closed Sicilian structure with the knight on b1. This opens up some c3 & d4 possibilities, but it is not very scary, as we will see. } 2... Nc6 ( 2... d5 { is a more concrete alternative. } ) 3. Bg2 g6 4. Ne2 ( 4. d3 { We examine this from the 2.d3 move order (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 4... Bg7 5. O-O d6 6. c3 e5 $1 { The key move. We stop d4 and plan to develop with ...Nge7, ...O-O, & ...Be6 next. } 7. Na3 { White wants to play d4 in one go, but we are ready to meet this. } 7... Nge7 8. Nc2 d5 $1 { A nice move, fighting for the center before White plays d4. } 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. d4 { Now we can just trade everything, and the position is equal. } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. Nexd4 O-O 13. Nxc6 bxc6 { This was seen in Onischuk, V -Sarana, A, 2020. We have compensation for the pawn on c6 because we have pressure on b2 with our monster bishop on g7, which makes it difficult for White to develop the c1-bishop. } * 

