1. e4 c5 2. g3 { White wants to play a closed Sicilian structure with the knight on b1. This opens up some c3 & d4 possibilities, but it is not very scary, as we will see. } 2... Nc6 ( 2... d5 { is a more concrete alternative. } ) 3. Bg2 g6 4. Ne2 ( 4. d3 { We examine this from the 2.d3 move order (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 4... Bg7 5. O-O d6 6. c3 e5 $1 { The key move. We stop d4 and plan to develop with ...Nge7, ...O-O, & ...Be6 next. } 7. d3 Nge7 { We develop the kingside knight without blocking the view of the g7-bishop. } 8. Be3 O-O 9. d4 { We can equalize in various ways here. } 9... exd4 $5 { The most ambitious way. } 10. cxd4 Bg4 $1 { We have already seen this idea in similar positions arising from 2.c4. } 11. f3 Bd7 12. d5 Ne5 { [%cal Gb7b5,Gf7f5,Ge5c4][%csl Rg2]We have lots of counterplay here. } * 

