1. e4 c5 2. g3 { White wants to play a closed Sicilian structure with the knight on b1. This opens up some c3 & d4 possibilities, but it is not very scary, as we will see. } 2... Nc6 ( 2... d5 { is a more concrete alternative. } ) 3. Bg2 g6 4. Ne2 ( 4. d3 { We examine this from the 2.d3 move order (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 4... Bg7 5. O-O d6 6. c3 e5 $1 { The key move. We stop d4 and plan to develop with ...Nge7, ...O-O, & ...Be6 next. } 7. d3 Nge7 { We develop the kingside knight without blocking the view of the g7-bishop. } 8. Be3 O-O 9. f4 { Very complex. } 9... exf4 $1 { ...Be6, ...Qd7, ...Rae8, & ...f5 another decent set-up, but this gives White more chances to go wrong and is more concrete. } 10. Nxf4 { White keeps dreaming about d4 } 10... b5 { We start our counterplay on the queenside. } 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4 b4 $1 { A really nice move, directed against the knight on b1. Nd2 hangs the d4-pawn, so it will stay on its initial square for a while. We can keep developing with moves like ...Ba6, ...Rc8, & ...Qb6. } * 

