1. e4 c5 2. Be2 { Probably the most interesting line in this chapter. White signals their intention to play f4-d3 set-ups. } 2... Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. d3 { This is White's idea, now if we exchange queens, White does not lose the right to castle. } 4... e6 ( 4... g6 { is also possible, but this looks even simpler. We want to go ...Bd6, ...Nge7, ...f6, ...O-O next. } ) 5. Nf3 Bd6 6. O-O Nge7 ( 6... f6 $2 { A decent move if you want to avoid the e5 line, White should probably play c3, transposing to lines that we are going to look at. } ) 7. e5 Bc7 8. c3 O-O 9. Na3 $5 { This is Simon Williams' (Big Si) recommendation. } 9... f6 { White has employed a couple of options from here. } 10. exf6 Rxf6 $1 { The idea is naturally to put pressure against f4. } 11. g3 h6 12. Nc2 d4 $15 { [%cal Ge7f5,Gf6f8]Stopping d4 and Black was slightly better in: 1/2-1/2 Kindermann, S - Vocaturo, D Germany, 2019. } * 

