[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Be2 { Probably the most interesting line in this chapter. White signals their intention to play f4-d3 set-ups. } 2... Nc6 3. f4 d5 4. d3 { This is White's idea, now if we exchange queens, White does not lose the right to castle. } 4... e6 ( 4... g6 { is also possible, but this looks even simpler. We want to go ...Bd6, ...Nge7, ...f6, ...O-O next. } ) 5. Nf3 Bd6 6. O-O Nge7 ( 6... f6 $2 { A decent move if you want to avoid the e5 line, White should probably play c3, transposing to lines that we are going to look at. } ) 7. e5 Bc7 8. c3 O-O 9. Na3 $5 { This is Simon Williams' (Big Si) recommendation. } 9... f6 { White has employed a couple of options from here. } 10. d4 { the best move, reinforcing the pawn chain. } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Bd7 $1 { Our light-squared bishop is a bad piece for the moment, so we want to change that! The idea is to bring it to e8 and then activate it via g6 or h5. } 12. Nc2 Be8 13. Bd3 Bh5 14. exf6 gxf6 { controlling the e5-square. It may look that our king is a bit unsafe, but we will use the h8-square and the g-file for a possible attack against the white king. } 15. Qe1 Qd7 16. Nh4 $6 { ½-½ Narciso Dublan, M - Ferreira, J Toledo, 2021. Black could have gotten a better position... } 16... e5 $15 { All pawn trades favor Black since White does not have the rooks connected yet. } * 

