1. e4 c5 2. f4 { This move is sometimes seen at club level, but it allows 2... d5. } 2... d5 { We directly strike in the center. If the position gets opened, White could have a weak kingside due to the f4-pawn. } 3. Bb5+ { Maybe the most interesting set-up for White in this 2. f4 complex. } 3... Bd7 4. Bxd7+ Qxd7 5. d3 { White plays similarly to the lines with Be2 but with the bishop out of the pawn chain, which makes some sense. } 5... Nf6 $1 { A subtle move. We try the lure the knight to c3 before exchanging queens. } 6. Nc3 dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nc6 { [%cal Ge8c8,Gc6b4,Gc6d4][%csl Rc2,Rd1]We have forced Nc3, so the typical plan Nbd2, c3, & Kc2 is not available for White. If the king goes to e2 moves like ...Nd4/Nb4 will always be difficult to meet. } * 

