1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a4 Nc6 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O Be7 { The Scheveningen is the most reliable system against the Be2 systems. } 9. Be3 O-O 10. f4 Qc7 11. Kh1 { This kind of move is always useful for White in this structures, getting the king out of the a7-g1 diagonal. } 11... Nxd4 { This is the new trend that we recommend in our course. } 12. Bxd4 e5 { The typical reaction when White takes with the bishop. We want to have the e5-square for our knight in the future. } 13. Be3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Be6 { The pawn on d6 is weak, but the pawn on e4 is also isolated. Usually, we play ...Nd7-Ne5, put the rooks in the center and try to redirect the dark-squared bishop to the h8-a1 diagonal. } 15. Qd3 Nd7 16. Qg3 { A good square for the queen, targeting g7 and d6 at the same time. } 16... Ne5 17. Be3 Rfe8 { f7 is well protected, so we can improve the situation of our rook. } 18. Bd4 Bf8 19. Qf2 Rac8 { The rooks are now placed on the semi-open files, and that means the best files possible. } 20. Rfd1 g6 { Typical maneuver for the bishop. From g7 it will be more active. } 21. h3 Bg7 22. Bb6 Qe7 23. Bd4 Rc6 { We can think of doubling rooks on the c-file, increasing the pressure. } 24. a5 ( 24. Nd5 $2 $146 { This is never possible since c2 is hanging. } 24... Bxd5 25. exd5 Rxc2 $19 { and White's position collapses. } ) 24... Nd7 { Trading the dark-squared bishops makes sense. White has a lot of weaknesses along the dark squares. } 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. Ra4 Rec8 27. Rad4 Ne5 28. Qf4 f6 { There were some tricks with Rxd6 followed by Qxe5+. We stop them for good. } 29. Qd2 Qc7 { [%csl Ga5]a5 is also hanging. } 30. Rb4 ( 30. Rxd6 Qxa5 { and Black is fine. } ) 30... Rb8 31. Ra4 b5 32. axb6 Rbxb6 33. Qc1 $6 { This passive move is inaccurate } ( 33. Qd4 { This was the active way to indirectly protect b2 since } 33... Rxb2 { can be met with } 34. Nb5 $146 Rxb5 35. Bxb5 $10 { and White cannot recapture with the a-pawn since ...Ra7 is in the air. } ) 33... Qb8 $1 34. Qd2 Qc8 $1 { A great move! Protecting a6 and getting ready to take on b2 and also keeping and eye on h3. } ( 34... Rxb2 { is met with } 35. Rxa6 { and White holds } ) 35. Qc1 Bxh3 $1 { Kaboom! } 36. Nd5 ( 36. gxh3 Qxh3+ 37. Kg1 Rxb2 { This is the key! } 38. Qxb2 Rxc3 $19 { and White is forced to sacrifice the queen, otherwise the rook finishes the game. } ) 36... Bxg2+ 37. Kg1 ( 37. Kxg2 Rxc2 38. Qe3 Rbxb2 $19 { and White can resign. Qg4+ is also coming. } ) 37... Bf3 38. Qf4 Bxe2 39. Qxf6+ Kh6 { [%cal Gf6h4,Ge2h5]The e2 bishop can protect the king in case of Qh4! } 40. Qf4+ g5 41. Qf6+ Kh5 42. Ne3 Qh3 { The rest of the game is easy. } 43. Nf5 Qg4+ 44. Kf2 Qf4+ 45. Kg1 Nf3+ 46. Kf2 Ne1+ 47. Kxe1 Qf1+ 48. Kd2 Rxc2+ 49. Ke3 Rb3+ 0-1 

