1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be2 { This is an old and solid line. White's idea is to complete the development first and then start some active play in the center or on the kingside according to what Black does. } 6... a6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Be3 Be7 9. f4 d6 10. a4 O-O 11. Kh1 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 { The most critical, centralizing the queen. } 12... Bd7 { Calmly completing development. Without preparation, one could be worried about depriving Black's f6-knight of the d7-square, but as we will see 13.e5 is not too dangerous. } 13. e5 Ne8 { [%cal Gd7c6,Ga8d8,Gg7g6,Ge8g7]Black is cramped at the moment, but our position contains a lot of energy, and White is kind of overextended. ...Bc6, ...Rd8, & ...g6 to regroup with ...Ng7 are moves we need to have in mind. } 14. Bd3 Bc6 { [%cal Ga8d8,Gd6e5]Preparing ...Rd8, when dxe5 will be a threat, because White does not want to take on e5 with the queen. } 15. Bf2 Rd8 16. Qe3 g6 { [%cal Ge8g7]This is where our course stops. ...g6 is very useful, protecting h7 and preparing the recycling route for the knight. } 17. a5 Ng7 18. Qe2 { [%cal Gf2b6]} 18... Rd7 { Avoiding tactics associated with Bb6. } 19. Bb6 Qb8 20. Rad1 Bd8 { That b6-bishop is very annoying. The f6-square will be very weak, but the the white knight can only access to it via e4 and in that case, we will eliminate it with our bishop. } 21. Ne4 Bxe4 22. Bxe4 Bxb6 23. axb6 Qd8 24. Rxd6 Rxd6 25. exd6 Qxb6 { This is the typical position where the d6-pawn is scary but at the same time extremely weak. } 26. Rd1 Rd8 27. d7 ( 27. Qd3 { does not manage to solve the protection issues with the d-pawn. } 27... Ne8 $146 28. d7 Nf6 $19 $146 { give me that! } ) 27... Nh5 { [%csl Gf4,Gf6]A fantastic move, targeting f4 and intending ...Nf6. } 28. Bf3 Nf6 ( 28... Nxf4 $146 { is actually a losing move because of } 29. Qe5 Nd5 $146 30. Bxd5 exd5 31. Qe8+ Kg7 32. Rf1 { and Black can resign. } ) 29. Qe5 Nxd7 30. Qd4 { Black is a pawn up but the knight on d7 is pinned! } 30... Qc7 31. c3 a5 32. f5 $2 { A significant mistake. Black was preparing ...Kf8 followed by ...Ke7 to unpin the d7-knight. } ( 32. g4 $13 { was necessary to prepare f5. } ) 32... gxf5 33. g4 f4 $1 { we need to close files, since our king could be in real danger if the g-file gets opened. } 34. g5 Kf8 { Black is still focused on unpinning the knight! Once it is done, it will be game over for White. } 35. h4 Ke7 36. Be4 e5 37. Qd5 Nc5 38. Qxd8+ Qxd8 39. Rxd8 Kxd8 40. Bxh7 Na4 { The game is over. Black captures on b2 or c3, and the black king stops the h-pawn. } 41. b4 b6 42. bxa5 bxa5 43. c4 Nc5 44. Bb1 Ke7 45. Kg2 e4 46. h5 a4 47. Kf2 a3 48. Kg2 e3 49. Kf3 Ne6 { [%csl Gg5]g5 falls. } 0-1 

