1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Bf4 { This is an attempt that has gained some popularity in recent times. It has the advantage of manually avoiding the Taimanov: now ...Qc7 would certainly not be a good move! } 5... d6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. c4 { The main move. White aims to increase control over the center. } 7... Rb8 { Immediately asking White a question: how do you defend the pawn on b2? } 8. Qc2 c5 9. Nc3 Ne7 { [%cal Ge7c6,Gc6d4]The best move in the position. Black's knight would have no future on f6: by developing it to e7, we are immediately putting our eye on the weak d4-square. } 10. O-O-O Nc6 11. e5 { White goes for the throat. } ( 11. Nb5 $2 $146 { allows } 11... e5 { , so it's a now-or-never moment for him. } ) 11... g5 $1 { After this pawn launch, the game becomes a three-result affair. Our bishop can come to g7 and start to pressure White's queenside. } 12. Be3 Nd4 { Super strong move. Without the dark-squared bishop, White will suffer along the dark squares. } 13. Rxd4 $1 ( 13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Rxd4 Bg7 15. Rxd6 Qa5 { and e5 falls and the white king is in real trouble. } ) 13... cxd4 14. Bxd4 Bg7 { Pinning the e5-pawn. } 15. Bxa7 { 15...Ra8Ν This is the novelty that we recommend in our course. } 15... Rb7 16. Bd4 dxe5 { At least now the diagonal is not open for the g7-bishop. } 17. Bc5 Qa5 ( 17... f5 { This is the crazy move that the engine recommends, giving the f7-square for the king. } ) 18. Qa4+ Qxa4 19. Nxa4 Bd7 20. Nb6 { White has a knight and a pawn plus 3 passed pawns for the exchange, so in my opinion Black is the one having to be careful in this position. } 20... Bf8 ( 20... Rc7 { the only move to equalize. } ) 21. Be3 ( 21. Bxf8 { guaranteed White a nice advantage. } 21... Rxb6 22. Bg7 { and e5 falls. } ) 21... Bc6 { g5 is untouchable. } 22. c5 f5 { Black needs to react, otherwise the white pawns are too dangerous. Now f4 followed by Bxc5 is the threat. } 23. b4 Rxb6 $1 24. cxb6 Bxb4 { Now the passed pawns are controlled and weak. } 25. f3 f4 26. Bf2 Ke7 { The rook is joining the party. } 27. Ba6 e4 28. fxe4 Bxe4 29. Kb2 Rb8 ( 29... Ba5 { was much stronger threatening ...Bxb6 followed by ...Rb8. } ) 30. Rc1 Bxg2 31. b7 Bd6 ( 31... Bxb7 $2 32. Rc7+ Kd6 33. Rxb7 { and White wins. } ) 32. Rc8 Rxb7+ 33. Bxb7 Bxb7 { Now the 4 vs 1 is Black's best asset vs the a-pawn, which is White's only hope. } 34. Rg8 Be5+ 35. Kc2 Kf6 36. a4 Bc7 37. Rf8+ Kg7 38. Bc5 ( 38. Re8 { was the only move to fight for equality. } ) 38... Bb6 $1 { Boom! } 39. Bd6 f3 { Now the f-pawn arrives to f1 easily. } 40. Kd1 f2 41. a5 Ba7 42. Be7 Ba6 0-1 

