1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 { The Alapin variation! } 3... Nf6 4. e5 Nd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 { The best move, developing the bishop to its most active square. } 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. a3 { Modest but decent. It is useful to take control of the b4-square for White. } 9... Bd7 10. Bxd5 { This is very solid for White, but Black does not have any problems. } 10... exd5 11. Nc3 Be6 $1 ( 11... Bc6 $2 { This can be played sometimes if dxe5-dxe5 is included, but here it is not very good, because the bishop is very passive. For example: } ) 12. Bf4 Nc6 13. exd6 Bxd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 { The position is symmetric and equal now. } 15. Re1 Rac8 { The rook to the open or semi-open files. } 16. Qd3 f6 { I like this move, covering e5 and g5. The bishop can be hidden now on f7 and Black can fight for the e-file as well. } 17. h3 Bf7 18. Rac1 Qd7 { Prophylaxis against Nb5. } 19. Nh2 Rfe8 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Nf1 g6 22. Ne3 Kg7 23. Na4 Qd6 ( 23... b6 $2 { after this move, Black's position is a little bit uncomfortable after } 24. Qb5 ) 24. Nc3 h5 25. Rd1 a6 26. Rc1 h4 { Caruana dreams with an attack on the kingside. It does not look very dangerous, but is playing around without making any progress. } 27. Rd1 Na5 28. b4 { Too optimistic and not necessary. Now the knight jumps to c4 and if White takes, Black gets a nice passed pawn on the c-file. } 28... Nc4 29. Nxc4 dxc4 30. Qd2 Bd5 ( 30... b5 $2 31. d5 { followed by Qd4 and Black has to be careful. } ) 31. b5 { White stops ...b5 from Black, that would protect the c4-pawn for good. } 31... Bf7 { [%cal Gd6a3]Now a3 is targeted. } 32. bxa6 bxa6 33. a4 g5 34. d5 Bg6 { The d3-square is very tasty for the bishop. } 35. Re1 Qf4 36. Qd1 ( 36. Qxf4 { loses } 36... Rxe1+ $19 ) 36... Bc2 { Another tactical shot by Fabi! } 37. Qa1 Re5 38. Rxe5 Qxe5 39. a5 Kg6 40. Kh1 Be4 { The d-pawn is about to fall. } 41. d6 Bc6 42. Qb2 Qxd6 0-1 

