1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Bc4 e6 5. Nf3 d6 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 { This is clearly the most testing move. It is not easy for White to develop the minor pieces on the queenside to good squares, so he decides to improve the Q on d1 and the R on f1 to its best available squares: e2 for the queen and d1 for the rook. } 9... dxe5 { Black releases tension in the center and force White to decide if he wants to take with the knight or the pawn. } 10. dxe5 Bd7 { The key move in our system against the Alapin is to develop the bishop to the a8-h1 diagonal. It's important to avoid the natural move b6, for both concrete and positional reasons. The concrete reason is that the rook on a8 is hanging in some variations. The positional reason is that the bishop will be protected on c6 by a pawn, which can be quite useful. } 11. Rd1 { The mainline, putting pressure on the d5-knight and centralizing the rook. } 11... Bc6 12. Bxd5 Bxd5 13. Nc3 Bxf3 $1 { great move, otherwise the bishop on d5 would suffer. } 14. Qxf3 Qb6 { Positionally, Black is perfectly fine and even slightly better, but White has some attacking opportunities in the kingside } 15. Ne4 Nc6 { No fear! } 16. Nf6+ Bxf6 17. exf6 Rfd8 { Looks very risky, but it works! } ( 17... g6 18. Be3 { this is very dangerous for Black. } ) 18. Be3 $6 ( 18. fxg7 Ne5 $146 19. Qh5 Rxd1+ 20. Qxd1 Rd8 21. Qe2 Nd3 $10 $146 { Black has easy equality. Notice how the g7-pawn actually shields our king! } ) 18... Qxb2 19. fxg7 Rd5 { great move by Grieve. White cannot take on d5 since the a1-rook is hanging. Black will get control over the d-file. } 20. Rab1 Rad8 { using the back-rank problems! } 21. Rf1 ( 21. Rxb2 Rxd1+ { mate! } ) 21... Qc2 22. h4 ( 22. Rxb7 { runs into } 22... Ne5 $146 { protecting f7 and attacking f3. Rd1 comes finishing the business. } ) 22... Ne5 23. Qg3 h5 { I find this move very natural, supporting an eventual Ng4. } 24. f3 b6 25. Bf4 Qf5 { at the end of the day Black will capture the g7 pawn and will be an extra healthy pawn. } 26. Kh2 Ng6 27. Bg5 f6 28. Be3 Qe5 { makes sense to trade queens. Once this is done, the black king will never suffer. } 29. f4 Qf5 { White managed to avoid the queen trade, but the cost has been hight since now the light squares are very weak and the dark-squared bishop is very clumsy. } 30. Rbc1 R5d7 31. a4 Rxg7 32. Qh3 Qe4 33. Rf3 Ne7 34. Re1 Nf5 35. Bf2 Qc4 36. g3 Rd2 37. Qf1 Qd5 38. Rc3 Qa2 ( 38... Qd4 { this was winning immediately! } 39. Rf3 Nxg3 $19 $146 ) 39. Kg1 Nxh4 40. Qb5 { Counterplay! Qe8 followed by Qxh5 is the threat! } 40... Qd5 41. Qxd5 exd5 42. Re8+ ( 42. Re6 { This was the only move to fight for equality. } ) 42... Kh7 43. Be1 Rd1 44. Kh2 d4 45. Rb3 Nf5 46. Bf2 h4 47. gxh4 Rd2 { White resigned. } 0-1 

