1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Nb3 Qb6 8. Be3 Qc7 9. O-O a6 10. f4 Be7 11. Bd3 b5 12. Qf3 { This is just a transposition to our chapter 'Weird 6th moves' } 12... Bb7 13. Qh3 { After this move, we need to be especially careful with the e5 push, since h7 is very weak. } 13... O-O 14. Rae1 Nb4 { A very typical move, trying to eliminate the super dangerous d3-bishop. } 15. Nd4 Rae8 16. g4 { White goes all in. } 16... Nd7 { Prophylactic play. } 17. g5 Nxd3 18. cxd3 Nc5 { White needs to many tempi in order to double heavy pieces on the h-file to mate Black. } 19. Rd1 ( 19. Qh5 { too optimistic } 19... Nxd3 $146 20. Rf3 g6 21. Qh6 Bxg5 22. fxg5 Nxe1 $146 23. Rh3 f5 $19 { and the queen protects h7! } ) 19... b4 20. Nce2 f5 $1 { A fantastic move. Black tries to open the position, since thanks to our bishop pair and the white over-expansion on the kingside, the white king could suffer. } 21. gxf6 Bxf6 22. Ng3 g6 { Stopping Nh5. } 23. Qg2 ( 23. f5 { is always strongly met with } 23... exf5 { since the e3-bishop is hanging. } ) 23... Bg7 24. Nf3 Qa5 25. b3 ( 25. h4 { would have been more interesting for White since h5 comes with an interesting attack. } ) 25... Qb5 { [%csl Gd3]} 26. Qd2 a5 { Once Black has managed to attract the white queen to the center of the board, the black king is not in danger and therefore Black can focus on creating play on the queenside with the plan a5-a4. } 27. Bd4 e5 28. fxe5 dxe5 29. Ba1 Ba6 { d3 collapses now. } 30. d4 exd4 31. Nxd4 Rxf1+ 32. Rxf1 Qd7 { The bishop pair makes a big difference now with that white king being so exposed. The engine says +5! } 33. Re1 Nd3 34. Nc2 Qa7+ 35. Qe3 Qxe3+ 36. Rxe3 Bh6 37. Rf3 Rc8 { White loses a piece! } 38. Rf6 Rxc2 39. Rxa6 Be3+ 40. Kh1 Rc1+ 41. Kg2 Rxa1 { The rest is easy for somebody like the great Svidler! } 42. Rxa5 Bd4 43. Ne2 Bc3 44. Kf3 Nc1 45. Ra8+ Kg7 46. Ra7+ Kh6 47. Nf4 Rxa2 48. Re7 Nxb3 49. e5 Nd2+ 50. Kg4 b3 51. Nd5 Ra4+ 52. Kg3 Bxe5+ 53. Rxe5 b2 0-1 

