1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 ( 3. b3 { is a solid setup against 2...e6. It doesn't work as well against Black's other 2nd moves. For example, against 2. Nf3 2...d6 , 3.b3 doesn't make much sense, as Black can neutralize White's bishop with 3...e5 . With ...e6 already played, this plan is off the table, which makes 3.b3 much more viable. White usually plays Bb2, Be2 and O-O next. } ) 3... a6 { Preparing d5 under better circumstances. } 4. c4 { The main move, stopping d5. } 4... Nc6 5. Bb2 Nf6 { We have already seen this idea. It makes sense to provoke e5, because it limits the scope of the bishop on b2. } 6. e5 Ng4 7. h3 Nh6 8. g4 { The most ambitious move. White wants to leave our knight out of the game. But Black has enough counterplay. } 8... d6 ( 8... d5 { is our recommendation. After exd6 it actually transposes to the game. } ) 9. exd6 ( 9. Bg2 { is the best engine option and that is why we recommend 8..d5 instead of 8...d6 } ) 9... f6 { An important immediate move. We want to take on d6 with the bishop, not the queen. } 10. d4 { Otherwise Black can play e5 and lead White with a very strange pawn structure. } 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 ( 11. c5 { is strongly met with } 11... Qa5+ $15 { and the c5-pawn falls. } ) 11... Qxd6 { Now it makes sense to take with the queen to avoid wrecking our pawn structure. } 12. Qd2 ( 12. Bg2 Qe5+ 13. Kf1 Bd7 $13 { the position is unclear but I would take Black because of White's king situation. } ) 12... Qe5+ 13. Kd1 ( 13. Be2 $2 { loses because of } 13... Bb4 14. Bc3 Nxd4 $146 15. Bxb4 Nf3+ $146 { game over! } ) 13... Qc7 { The black queen already did its mission, leave White without the right to castle. } 14. Bg2 ( 14. Nxc6 $146 Qxc6 15. Rg1 Bd7 16. Bg2 Qc7 17. Kc2 { This was the only way for White to fight for equality. } ) 14... Bd7 { A rook on d8 will be devastating. } 15. Re1 O-O-O 16. Bxc6 Bxc6 17. Rxe6 Bc5 18. Kc1 Nf7 19. f4 Qd7 { White is not on time to protect the d4-knight and the e6-rook at the same time! } 0-1 

