1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 4. Nf3 e6 5. O-O { The most critical move, recommended by British Grandmaster Gawain Jones in his Coffeehouse Repertoire series. } ( 5. Nxd4 $146 { This move is already a bit mistake! } 5... cxd4 6. Ne2 $146 Qg5 $17 { and Black targets b5 and g2 at the same time! } ) 5... a6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Re1 { This move looks very logical, preparing for aggressive options like Bf1 or the simpler Bf1 to support pushing d4. But it has a very big problem: it deprives the knight on f3 of the e1-square, and it is kind of trapped now! } 7... g5 $1 { Extremely strong. } 8. g3 { Giving the h4-square to the knight. } 8... d6 { Black has a fantastic position already since White cannot break on the center. This where our course stops. } 9. Bf1 g4 10. Nh4 Be7 11. Ng2 { The only way to avoid losing a pawn on h4. } 11... h5 { Very intuitive. Black wants to open the h-file and mate White. } 12. d3 Nd4 13. Be2 { White needs to stop the fork on f3. } 13... Nf6 14. Be3 Nd7 { Great move, intending Ne5 and finally landing on f3 with a knight. } 15. Bxd4 { desperate measures. Besides having more space and attacking chances, Black will also have now the bishop pair. } ( 15. Nb1 $146 { was the best try for White to cover f3! } 15... Ne5 $146 16. Nd2 $146 { followed by c3 and White survives. } ) 15... cxd4 16. Nb1 Qb6 17. b3 Qc5 { From c5, the queen targets c2 and also dreams about being transferrer to h5 to finish the business at some point. } 18. Nd2 b5 19. a4 Bb7 ( 19... b4 { was much better. The knight never has an outpost on c5 since d5 is in the air all the time. } ) 20. axb5 axb5 21. Rxa8+ Bxa8 22. f3 Ne5 23. f4 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6b4]The king is not the only target. c2 will be a nightmare for White as well. } 24. Qa1 { [%cal Ga1a8]Attacking a8 } 24... Bb7 25. Qb2 Kd7 { The king is fantastically placed on d7 and the rook comes now to the action on the queenside. } 26. Ra1 Nb4 27. Bd1 f5 { [%cal Gb7h1]Opening the main diagonal would be a disaster for White thanks to the power of the b7-bishop. } 28. Kf1 h4 29. gxh4 Bxh4 30. Qa3 Bf6 { [%cal Gh8a8,Ga8a1,Gb4c2]Targeting h2 and threatening ...Ra8 followed by ...Rxa1 and ...Nxc2. } 31. Qa7 Qc6 32. Qa5 { [%cal Gh8a8]White stopped suffering. ...Ra8 just wins the game! } 0-1 

