1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 { This move is a decent way for White to fight for an advantage. It has been recommended by Wesley So in his Lifetime Repertoire and was even played by Magnus Carlsen in his World Championship match against Anand. } 3... d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 { The only critical move. } ( 5. Bg2 { is met with } 5... Qe7+ { our course recommendation. } ) 5... cxd4 { The modern approach, recently played by top players such as Nepomniachtchi, Gelfand, and Dubov. 5...Nc6 and 5...Nf6 are also decent, but it is interesting to open the center and play very concretely. } 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Bg2 { The most natural move and the one who has been played the most. } 7... Bc5 8. Nxc6 { I think it is difficult to believe that White can fight for an advantage without us having an isolated pawn on d5. } 8... bxc6 9. O-O Nf6 10. c4 { This looks standard, but it can become very dangerous for White with his undeveloped queenside, as we will see. } ( 10. Re1+ Be6 { and Black is ready to castle next move. } ) 10... O-O 11. cxd5 { White's idea, but it is another slight mistake. } 11... Ba6 $1 { [%csl Gf2]This is the key! Black develops the last minor piece with a tempo. After Re1, f2 becomes much more weaker. } 12. Re1 cxd5 13. Nc3 Qb6 { White needs to protect f2 now. } 14. Be3 { makes sense, since after d4 it looks like White has Na5 winning some material, but wait... } ( 14. Qc2 { was necessary but after } 14... Rac8 $15 { is clear that Black is on top. } ) 14... d4 15. Na4 dxe3 $1 { Brilliant! } 16. Nxb6 exf2+ 17. Kh1 fxe1=Q+ 18. Qxe1 Bxb6 19. Bxa8 Rxa8 { And Black has three pieces for the queen but the white king is extremely exposed. } 20. h3 Re8 21. Qd1 Re2 { ...Bb7 is coming. White resigned. } 0-1 

