1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O Be7 9. f3 { With this move we have just entered the famous English Attack. } 9... b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 { It is tremendously important to start by taking on d4 before playing ...Bb7. } 11. Qxd4 { This move has two main problems: after ...Bb7 & ...Rc8, White needs to spend a tempo defending against b4, and White also has to consider ...Bc5, which exchanges dark-squared bishops—something that always works in our favor. } 11... Bb7 12. g5 { White needs to create some play; otherwise we will be more than fine after Rc8. } 12... Nh5 13. Ne2 { Too slow in my opinion. Black can punish White. } 13... Rc8 { Threatening mate on c2. } 14. Qd2 ( 14. c3 e5 15. Qd2 d5 16. exd5 Rd8 { and Black gets the d5-pawn with a fantastic position. } ) 14... d5 { We should always keep this move in mind in the English Attack! Many times, its appearance on the board signals that Black is taking control. } 15. e5 d4 $1 { A very beautiful. It is more important to open the bishop on b7 than to keep a pawn. Here, White doesn't even manage to hold material due to his weaknesses on f3 and e5. } ( 15... Qxe5 { is also playable. } ) 16. Nxd4 O-O 17. Bg2 Rfd8 18. f4 Bxg2 19. Qxg2 Qc4 { Getting the material back thanks to the pressure against d4. } 20. Kb1 Nxf4 21. Bxf4 Rxd4 22. Rxd4 Qxd4 { Perhaps if White plays very precisely can hold, but practically speaking, it is very tough. } 23. Qf3 Qc4 24. c3 Rd8 { Winning the battle on the d-file since White cannot play Rd1 now. } 25. Rf1 Rd7 { Keeping an eye on f7 before attacking on the queenside. } 26. b3 Qc8 27. h4 g6 28. Rc1 Rc7 29. Kb2 a5 { There we go! } 30. Qd3 ( 30. h5 { was better. White cannot abandon the main diagonal! } ) 30... Qb7 $1 31. c4 Rd7 32. Qe2 bxc4 $6 ( 32... a4 { was the strongest continuation, trying to destroy all White's king defenses } 33. cxb5 axb3 34. axb3 Rd5 $17 { and b5 falls at the end. } ) 33. Qxc4 Qf3 34. Rc2 Rd5 35. Rd2 $2 ( 35. Bc1 { an almost impossible move to make was the only way to survive. } 35... Rxe5 $2 { is punished with } 36. Qc7 ) 35... Rc5 $1 { [%csl Gc3]} 36. Qd4 a4 { And a3 is in the air, creating a lot of mating nets. } 37. Be3 ( 37. bxa4 { runs into mate! } 37... Qb7+ 38. Ka1 Rc1# ) 37... a3+ 38. Kb1 Rd5 39. Qf4 Qh1+ 40. Kc2 Qa1 { White resigned since he cannot stop ...Qxa2. } 0-1 

