1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... Nf6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Be7 9. f3 { This is the well known English attack against the Taimanov. } 9... b5 10. g4 { This is the most natural move, continuing the English Attack line by pushing g4. } 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 { The most natural and popular recapture. } 11... Bb7 12. g5 { The most concrete move, leading to many forced lines. } 12... Nh5 13. Be5 { This surprising move has been known for a long time, and Black has found decent antidotes against it. } 13... Qxe5 { We need to accept the challenge! } 14. Qxd7+ Kf8 15. Qxb7 Qb8 { This was already mentioned by Van Kampen as an interesting alternative to taking on g5, and I still believe it's easier for us to play and trickier for White to handle. White has an extra pawn but at the same time g5 is very weak and Black owns the dark squares. } 16. Rd7 Qxb7 17. Rxb7 h6 $5 { The idea! We want to activate our rook on h8. This approach is riskier, but it offers better winning chances. Typically, only very solid White players opt for this variation, as it has largely been mapped out to a draw. } 18. g6 ( 18. gxh6 Rxh6 { We are a pawn down, but we have sufficient counterplay on the kingside. } ) 18... fxg6 19. a4 Kf7 { Connecting the rooks. The pawn on b5 is not so important here. } 20. axb5 $6 { This move is actually a mistake, because it opens the a-file for Black's rook and White will not be on time to capture the b-pawn. } ( 20. e5 $2 { is a better try. } ) 20... axb5 21. Kb1 ( 21. Bxb5 Ra1+ { and White loses the rook! } ) ( 21. Nxb5 $146 Ra1+ 22. Kd2 Rd8+ 23. Kc3 Kf8 $17 { unpinning the bishop before entering with the other rook on d1! } ) 21... b4 22. Nb5 Rhb8 { It makes sense to eliminate White's best piece. } 23. Rxb8 Rxb8 24. Bc4 { The most natural move, targeting e6. } ( 24. Ka2 { is the first engine option. Idea: Kb3 & Bc4. } ) 24... Nf4 ( 24... Rc8 { was Black's best answer. If White plays b3, then the king is never activated through b3. } 25. Bb3 Rc5 26. Nd4 $146 Nf4 $146 { and Black can slowly progress, and meanwhile it is not so clear what are White next moves. } ) 25. Ka2 $1 Rd8 26. Kb3 Rd2 27. c3 $6 ( 27. e5 $13 { was the best move with the idea of Nd6+ and trade the e5-pawn for the one on b4. } ) 27... bxc3 28. bxc3 Kf6 29. Nd4 e5 30. Nc2 Bc5 { The white rook is very passive and the passed pawn on c3 is well controlled by the dark-squared bishop. } 31. Bd5 Kg5 32. Nb4 Kh4 { There we go! } 33. Kc4 Be7 ( 33... Bd6 { was better since Nc6 does not come with a tempo. } ) 34. Nc6 Bf6 35. Kc5 Kh3 36. Kd6 Kg2 37. Ra1 Kxh2 38. c4 { This is very chaotic now and anything can happen. } 38... Nd3 { [%cal Gc4c5,Gd2c2]} 39. Ra3 $6 ( 39. Nb8 $146 { was one of the first engine options, intending Nd7 followed by c5. } ) 39... h5 40. Rc3 { This is too slow. } 40... h4 41. c5 h3 42. Na5 Nxc5 { Time to sacrifice a piece to win the game with the h-pawn. The white pieces are just too far away. } 43. Rxc5 Kg3 44. Nc4 Rc2 45. Ra5 h2 46. Ne3 Rc1 0-1 

