1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 { The starting position of the Taimanov. } 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 { The English Attack, White's most ambitious and critical attempt. White typically plays Qd2, O-O-O, and f3 next. They go for a quick pawn storm on the kingside; one key motif is g4-g5. } 6... a6 7. g4 h6 { The point is to slow down g5 and give Black's knight a safe square on f6 if possible. In general, it leads to less forced play and gives White more chances to make mistakes in the early stages, especially if he's not very familiar with the line details. } 8. h4 { This is White's most logical move, expanding further on the kingside. } 8... Nf6 { [%cal Gf8b4]This is strong now that White cannot play g5. The next move we would like to play is ...Bb4. } 9. Nxc6 { In many lines, ...Ne5 provides Black a lot of counterplay, but this move denies that possibility. } 9... Qxc6 10. f3 Ba3 { Using the tactics against c3! } 11. bxa3 Qxc3+ 12. Kf2 d5 { We should react quickly in the center, since the white king is quite exposed. } 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Bd4 Qxa3 { Now White can take on g7, but it isn't very dangerous for us. The trickiest line is when White plays for compensation in the endgame. } 15. Bxg7 Qe3+ 16. Kg3 { Black can force a draw in this way if he wants to with Qf4+. However Taimanov expert Ivanisevic decided to play on. From the theoretical point of view, it's enough knowing we have at least a draw and that we can play on if we want to. } 16... Rg8 17. Qd4 ( 17. Bd4 $2 { runs into } 17... Rxg4+ 18. Kxg4 Qf4+ 19. Kh3 e5+ 20. Kg2 exd4 $19 { and Black is winning. } ) 17... Bd7 18. Bd3 Rxg7 { A super interesting exchange sacrifice. The black king will be super safe on the queenside and White suffers along the dark squares. } 19. Qxg7 Qf4+ 20. Kf2 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6g4]} 21. Rag1 $2 ( 21. Qh8+ { was the only way to fight for equality here } 21... Ke7 22. Qxa8 Nxg4+ $146 23. Kg2 Bc6 24. Rh3 Qd2+ 25. Kg3 f5 { and White has to find here the difficult } 26. Qa7 { to cover the f2 square } 26... h5 27. Qc5+ Ke8 28. Bxf5 exf5 29. Qxf5 Qf2+ 30. Kf4 Qd2+ { leading to a crazy draw. } ) 21... Bc6 { [%csl Gf3]} 22. g5 Qxf3+ 23. Ke1 Ne4 ( 23... O-O-O { was better! } 24. Qxf6 Qe3+ 25. Kf1 Rd4 $19 { with ...Rf4 coming! } ) 24. Qh8+ Ke7 25. Qd4 $1 Rd8 26. Bxe4 Bxe4 27. Qf6+ Qxf6 28. gxf6+ Kxf6 { Black has a bishop and two pans for the rook. Besides that, the white pawns are very weak and easy target. } 29. Rh2 Rd4 30. Rg4 Ke5 31. h5 Rc4 32. Rf2 f5 33. Rg6 f4 34. Rxh6 f3 { Black goes all in. The good news is that the bishop is a fantastic piece to stop the h-pawn. } 35. Rd2 Bf5 36. Kf2 Kf4 37. Rf6 { [%cal Ge6e5]} 37... Kg5 38. Rxf5+ $4 { White went a little bit crazy with this exchange sacrifice. There was no need for that. } ( 38. Rf8 { and f3 is hanging. Black is the one here having to fight for the draw! } ) 38... exf5 39. Kxf3 Rc3+ 40. Ke2 Kxh5 $19 { Black is a pawn up. Besides that, the white rook is very passive and the passed pawn on the f-file runs very fast. } 41. Rd7 Rxc2+ 42. Kf3 Kg5 43. Rg7+ Kf6 44. Rxb7 Rxa2 45. Rb8 Ra3+ 46. Kf4 Ra4+ 47. Kf3 Ke5 48. Re8+ Kd4 49. Kf4 Ra1 50. Rd8+ Kc4 51. Rc8+ Kb4 52. Rb8+ Ka4 53. Kxf5 Re1 54. Kf4 a5 55. Kf3 Ka3 0-1 

